window.EXAM_QUESTIONS = [{"id": 1, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 68-year-old patient with heart failure, type 2 diabetes, and chronic kidney disease stage 3 is being discharged after a 5-day hospitalization. She lives alone in a third-floor walk-up apartment with no elevator. Which discharge concern should the case manager address first?", "options": {"A": "Arranging home health services for medication management and vital sign monitoring.", "B": "Scheduling a follow-up cardiology appointment within seven days of discharge.", "C": "Evaluating whether the physical environment safely supports her functional needs.", "D": "Confirming the patient has transportation to her primary care physician."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The patient's physical environment poses an immediate safety risk because she lives alone on a third floor with no elevator and has multiple chronic conditions limiting her mobility and energy. Home health services are appropriate but cannot be optimized until the living situation is assessed. A follow-up appointment is necessary but scheduling it before knowing where the patient will recover is premature. Transportation is a valid concern but is secondary to determining whether the home is physically safe."}, {"id": 2, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which criterion best identifies a patient who would benefit most from intensive case management services rather than standard care coordination?", "options": {"A": "A patient with a single chronic condition who is adherent to prescribed therapy.", "B": "A patient with three or more chronic conditions and two hospitalizations in the past year.", "C": "A patient who requests a referral to a specialist for a new diagnosis.", "D": "A patient recovering from elective surgery with full family caregiver support."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Patients with multiple chronic conditions and a recent pattern of acute care utilization represent the highest-complexity tier and gain the most from intensive case management. A patient adherent to therapy for a single condition has low risk and does not require intensive intervention. A specialist referral request represents a straightforward coordination task, not a complexity indicator. A post-surgical patient with strong caregiver support typically follows a predictable recovery trajectory without intensive oversight."}, {"id": 3, "domain": "care_management", "question": "InterQual criteria are used by a case manager reviewing a patient's continued hospital stay. The patient has stabilized but the physician has not yet documented a discharge plan. How should the case manager proceed?", "options": {"A": "Discharge the patient immediately based on criteria.", "B": "Escalate to the physician and medical director that the stay no longer meets inpatient criteria.", "C": "Wait 48 hours for the physician to complete discharge documentation independently.", "D": "Request a social work consult and defer the physician conversation to the next shift."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When InterQual criteria no longer support continued inpatient level of care, the case manager must promptly communicate this finding to the attending physician and escalate to the medical director if needed, following the chain of command. The case manager does not have authority to discharge a patient; that decision belongs to the physician. Waiting 48 hours without escalation allows avoidable days to accumulate, creating payer and compliance risk. Deferring the physician conversation to another shift delays a time-sensitive utilization management action."}, {"id": 4, "domain": "care_management", "question": "The primary goal of transitional care management is to reduce adverse events after hospital discharge. Which action by the case manager most directly supports this goal during the first 72 hours post-discharge?", "options": {"A": "Mailing a written care summary to the patient's primary care provider.", "B": "Calling the patient to confirm medication reconciliation and identify new symptoms.", "C": "Scheduling the patient's six-week surgical follow-up appointment.", "D": "Submitting a prior authorization request for home infusion therapy."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A telephone follow-up call within 72 hours to confirm that medications were filled, reconciled, and understood, and to screen for early signs of decompensation, is the highest-yield transitional care action in the immediate post-discharge window. Mailing a care summary is appropriate but passive and does not confirm the patient received or understood the information. A six-week follow-up appointment, while necessary, addresses a later phase of recovery. Prior authorization tasks, though important, do not directly reduce the patient's immediate risk of readmission."}, {"id": 5, "domain": "care_management", "question": "When stratifying a caseload by complexity, the case manager should prioritize which patient for immediate outreach and intervention?", "options": {"A": "A 45-year-old with controlled hypertension who attends annual wellness visits regularly.", "B": "A 71-year-old recently discharged after COPD exacerbation who lives in a rural area alone.", "C": "A 55-year-old with type 2 diabetes whose hemoglobin A1c improved to 7.1% last month.", "D": "A 38-year-old post-operative patient whose wound care is managed by home health."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The 71-year-old with a recent COPD hospitalization, social isolation, and geographic barriers to care represents the highest risk for rapid deterioration and early readmission and should receive priority outreach. The patient with controlled hypertension and consistent preventive care engagement has low complexity and low near-term risk. Improved glycemic control in a diabetic patient signals positive trajectory and reduced urgency. The post-operative patient already has active home health oversight, lowering the case manager's immediate burden."}, {"id": 6, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A hospital-based case manager reviews utilization data and finds that a patient with lupus has visited the emergency department four times in six weeks, each time for pain crises. Which intervention is most appropriate for reducing this pattern?", "options": {"A": "Flagging the patient in the medical record system as a frequent utilizer.", "B": "Coordinating an ambulatory pain management plan with rheumatology and primary care.", "C": "Referring the patient to the social work department for behavioral health evaluation.", "D": "Requesting that the patient sign a pain management contract with the ED team."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Frequent ED visits for pain crises in a patient with lupus indicate a gap in outpatient pain management; coordinating a proactive ambulatory plan with the relevant specialists addresses the root cause. Flagging the patient as a frequent utilizer is a documentation step that does not change the care gap driving the visits. A behavioral health referral may be appropriate if psychosocial factors are identified but should not be the first response to undertreated disease-related pain. A pain contract is a reactive, punitive tool that does not address the systemic care gap."}, {"id": 7, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which tool is most commonly used by case managers to assess a hospitalized patient's risk for unplanned readmission within 30 days of discharge?", "options": {"A": "The Confusion Assessment Method, which screens for acute delirium at the bedside.", "B": "The LACE index, which scores length of stay, acuity, comorbidities, and ED visits.", "C": "The Braden Scale, which predicts pressure injury risk based on mobility and moisture.", "D": "The PHQ-9, which quantifies severity of depressive symptoms over the past two weeks."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The LACE index is a validated, widely used readmission risk tool that combines length of stay, acuity of admission, comorbidity burden, and recent emergency department use into a single score that guides post-discharge intensity. The Confusion Assessment Method is a delirium screening instrument, not a readmission predictor. The Braden Scale is specific to pressure injury prevention and has no readmission predictive function. The PHQ-9 measures depression severity and, while depression may correlate with readmission, it is not a readmission risk stratification tool."}, {"id": 8, "domain": "care_management", "question": "The case manager is developing a care plan for a 58-year-old patient with uncontrolled type 2 diabetes and stage 4 chronic kidney disease. The patient reports not checking blood glucose because strips are too expensive. Which action addresses the highest-priority barrier?", "options": {"A": "Recommending the patient reduce carbohydrate intake and exercise for 30 minutes daily.", "B": "Connecting the patient with a pharmaceutical assistance program for glucose monitoring supplies.", "C": "Scheduling a diabetes education class offered at the outpatient clinic next month.", "D": "Requesting a nephrology consultation to discuss dialysis planning and preparation."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The patient has identified a concrete financial barrier preventing self-monitoring, which is a social determinant of health directly causing poor glucose control; removing this barrier through an assistance program is the most direct and actionable intervention. Lifestyle counseling is appropriate but unhelpful if the patient lacks the tools to track glucose responses to behavior changes. A diabetes education class addresses knowledge but not the identified resource gap and is scheduled too far out to have immediate impact. Dialysis planning may be appropriate for stage 4 CKD but does not address the active management barrier."}, {"id": 9, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is completing a social determinants of health screening for a newly enrolled patient. The patient discloses food insecurity and inconsistent access to medications. Which next step best reflects evidence-based case management practice?", "options": {"A": "Documenting the findings in the chart and notifying the attending physician by secure message.", "B": "Linking the patient to a community food bank and a medication assistance program promptly.", "C": "Referring the patient to social work and closing the case pending their assessment.", "D": "Scheduling a follow-up screening in 90 days to reassess food and medication access."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When social determinants of health screening reveals actionable barriers like food insecurity and medication access, best practice calls for immediate linkage to community resources to address those barriers and prevent downstream health deterioration. Documentation and physician notification are important but insufficient on their own if they do not result in direct patient support. Transferring the case entirely to social work without initiating resource linkage may cause delay and gaps in care. Deferring action to a 90-day follow-up ignores the urgency of active food and medication insecurity."}, {"id": 10, "domain": "care_management", "question": "During a care conference, the attending physician disagrees with the case manager's recommendation that a post-surgical patient be discharged to a skilled nursing facility. The physician believes the patient can go home safely. Which action is most appropriate for the case manager?", "options": {"A": "Defer to the physician's decision and close the discharge planning case immediately.", "B": "Present objective functional assessment findings and safety concerns to support the SNF recommendation.", "C": "Contact the insurance company to override the physician's discharge decision.", "D": "Ask the patient to refuse discharge home and demand SNF placement in writing."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The case manager's role in a care conference disagreement is to advocate for the patient using objective data, including functional assessments, home safety evaluations, and caregiver capacity findings, while respecting the interdisciplinary process. Simply deferring to the physician without presenting clinical rationale fails the advocacy function of case management. Insurance companies do not override physician discharge decisions; they determine coverage, not clinical appropriateness. Coaching the patient to refuse discharge is ethically inappropriate and outside the case manager's scope."}, {"id": 11, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which intervention is most consistent with population health management when a case manager identifies a panel of 200 patients with diabetes who have not had a hemoglobin A1c test in over 12 months?", "options": {"A": "Calling each patient individually to schedule an appointment at the next available slot.", "B": "Designing a targeted outreach campaign using text messages and care gap alerts for the panel.", "C": "Flagging the five most complex patients and referring the remaining patients to primary care.", "D": "Waiting for the patients to present to the clinic before initiating diabetes care discussions."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Population health management uses systematic, panel-level outreach strategies to close care gaps across a defined patient group rather than relying on individual ad hoc contacts, making a targeted multi-modal campaign the most appropriate intervention. Calling each patient individually is time-intensive and not scalable for a panel of 200. Limiting action to only the most complex five patients ignores the remaining 195 with an unaddressed care gap. Waiting for patients to self-present is a reactive approach that perpetuates the care gap and contradicts population health principles."}, {"id": 12, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient with COPD is being evaluated for home oxygen therapy after hospitalization. The treating pulmonologist has ordered it, but the payer is requesting prior authorization with clinical documentation. Which task falls within the case manager's role?", "options": {"A": "Prescribing supplemental oxygen at the flow rate specified by the pulmonologist.", "B": "Compiling and submitting clinical documentation supporting the prior authorization request.", "C": "Contacting the payer's medical director and overturning the authorization requirement.", "D": "Advising the patient to purchase oxygen equipment out of pocket while the authorization is pending."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Gathering clinical documentation and submitting or coordinating a prior authorization request is a core utilization management function of the case manager. Prescribing oxygen is a physician function and outside the case manager's scope of practice. The case manager may escalate a prior authorization to a peer-to-peer review, but cannot unilaterally overturn a payer requirement. Advising the patient to pay out of pocket without first exhausting the authorization process creates financial harm and reflects poor advocacy."}, {"id": 13, "domain": "care_management", "question": "When coordinating post-acute care for a patient being discharged after a hip replacement, the first step the case manager should take is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Assessing the patient's functional status, home environment, and caregiver support.", "B": "Contacting three skilled nursing facilities to check bed availability for the patient.", "C": "Ordering physical therapy to begin inpatient sessions before discharge planning starts.", "D": "Submitting a home health referral based on the standard post-hip-replacement protocol."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Post-acute care planning must begin with a thorough assessment of the patient's functional abilities, home environment, and available support systems so that the most appropriate level of post-acute care can be matched to the patient's actual needs. Contacting SNFs before knowing whether SNF care is even appropriate wastes resources and may result in a poor placement decision. Physical therapy is a clinical order placed by the physician or therapist, not a case management function that initiates planning. Submitting a home health referral without first assessing the patient's needs may result in an inadequate or mismatched level of care."}, {"id": 14, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient with stage 3 heart failure refuses discharge to a skilled nursing facility and insists on going home despite the case manager's safety concerns. The patient has decision-making capacity. How should the case manager respond?", "options": {"A": "Respect the patient's decision and arrange the maximum available support for a safe home discharge.", "B": "Obtain a court order to mandate SNF placement for the patient's safety.", "C": "Document the refusal and discharge the patient without any follow-up plan or resources.", "D": "Ask the patient's family to override the patient's preference and consent to SNF placement."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A patient with decision-making capacity has the legal and ethical right to refuse any recommended care setting, including SNF placement; the case manager's obligation is to respect that autonomy and maximize safety within the chosen setting. A court order for placement is legally and ethically untenable for a capacitated patient. Discharging without a safety plan or resources abandons the patient and violates the standard of care. Asking family to override a capacitated patient's decision disregards the foundational principle of patient autonomy."}, {"id": 15, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which of the following best describes the role of a case manager in utilization review during an inpatient stay?", "options": {"A": "Evaluating the clinical necessity of continued hospitalization against evidence-based criteria.", "B": "Approving or denying claims submitted by the hospital to the insurance company.", "C": "Determining the diagnosis-related group assigned to each patient on admission.", "D": "Auditing physician documentation for coding accuracy and billing compliance."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Utilization review is the ongoing evaluation of whether a patient's clinical status justifies the current level of care, typically measured against criteria such as InterQual or MCG, and communicating findings to the treatment team and payer. Claims approval and denial is a function of the payer's utilization management department, not the hospital-based case manager. DRG assignment is handled by medical coders using physician documentation, not by the case manager. Documentation auditing for billing compliance is a revenue cycle or compliance function, separate from clinical utilization review."}, {"id": 16, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 74-year-old patient with dementia is hospitalized after a fall. The family wants the patient discharged home, but the patient lives alone and the home assessment reveals fall hazards throughout the dwelling. Which action should the case manager take first?", "options": {"A": "Facilitate a family meeting to discuss safety findings and explore realistic discharge options.", "B": "Contact Adult Protective Services immediately to report suspected elder neglect.", "C": "Discharge the patient home per family request and schedule a home safety evaluation later.", "D": "Request a psychiatric consult to assess whether the patient should be placed under guardianship."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A family meeting that presents objective safety findings and explores options, including in-home support services, family caregiver arrangements, or alternative care settings, is the appropriate first step to align all stakeholders around a safe plan. APS reporting is appropriate when there is evidence of active neglect or abuse, not simply when the home environment requires modification. Discharging the patient into a known unsafe environment without a safety plan violates the case manager's duty and the standard of care. A guardianship evaluation is a significant legal step that is premature before a structured conversation has occurred."}, {"id": 17, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which clinical pathway feature most directly supports length of stay reduction in a hospital setting?", "options": {"A": "Standardizing day-by-day care milestones that trigger discharge readiness criteria.", "B": "Requiring physician approval before any nursing intervention is performed on the unit.", "C": "Allowing patients to self-report pain levels rather than relying on nurse assessment.", "D": "Limiting specialist consultations to reduce documentation burden for attending physicians."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Clinical pathways that define expected daily milestones and link them to discharge readiness criteria create a shared roadmap for the team, reducing variation and identifying delays early, which supports shorter, safer lengths of stay. Requiring physician approval for all nursing interventions would create bottlenecks and slow care delivery rather than shorten stays. Patient self-reporting of pain does not address the structural drivers of length of stay. Limiting specialty consultations without clinical justification risks missing diagnoses and can actually prolong stays."}, {"id": 18, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager notices that a 63-year-old patient with asthma has filled her rescue inhaler six times in the past four months but has not refilled her controller inhaler once. What does this pattern most likely indicate?", "options": {"A": "The patient is overusing rescue therapy because controller therapy is not being taken as prescribed.", "B": "The patient's asthma has been well-controlled and she no longer needs the controller inhaler.", "C": "The patient is stockpiling rescue inhalers to share with family members at home.", "D": "The controller inhaler prescription may have been written in error by the prescribing physician."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "High rescue inhaler use combined with zero controller inhaler refills is a strong signal that the patient is not taking her maintenance therapy, which is causing poorly controlled asthma and symptomatic reliance on rescue medication. Well-controlled asthma results in minimal rescue inhaler use, not increased use. While inhaler sharing cannot be ruled out, it is not the most clinically relevant or probable explanation and does not guide care management intervention. A prescribing error is possible but would require verification; the refill pattern more strongly suggests an adherence issue."}, {"id": 19, "domain": "care_management", "question": "MCG (Milliman Care Guidelines) criteria indicate that a patient's surgical procedure qualifies for same-day surgery rather than inpatient admission. The surgeon insists on a two-night inpatient stay as personal preference. Which response by the case manager is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Discuss the criteria findings with the surgeon and explain the risk of a payer denial.", "B": "Document the surgeon's preference and bill the stay as inpatient without further review.", "C": "Override the surgeon's order and schedule the patient for outpatient surgery immediately.", "D": "Contact the patient's family to ask them to pressure the surgeon to change the plan."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The case manager's role is to communicate the evidence-based criteria findings to the surgeon in a collegial way that informs the clinical decision, including explaining that an inpatient stay not supported by criteria carries a high risk of payer denial and financial liability for the hospital. Documenting the preference and billing without review exposes the hospital to denial and potential compliance issues. Overriding a physician's order is outside the case manager's scope of practice. Involving the family to influence the surgeon's clinical decision is inappropriate and outside the bounds of the case manager's role."}, {"id": 20, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is performing health coaching for a patient with hypertension who has not taken antihypertensive medication consistently for three months. Which motivational interviewing technique is most appropriate to begin the conversation?", "options": {"A": "Asking the patient an open-ended question about what makes taking medication difficult.", "B": "Telling the patient directly that stopping medication increases the risk of stroke and death.", "C": "Reviewing the patient's blood pressure log and pointing out every reading above 140/90.", "D": "Providing a printed list of hypertension complications to review during the appointment."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Motivational interviewing begins with open-ended questions to understand the patient's perspective, barriers, and readiness to change without triggering defensiveness, which is the most effective starting point for an adherence conversation. Stating mortality risk directly may feel threatening and increase resistance rather than engagement. Reviewing elevated readings and pointing them out focuses on the problem rather than the patient's experience, which can feel judgmental. Providing educational materials alone is a passive, didactic approach that does not engage the patient in exploring their own barriers."}, {"id": 21, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 52-year-old patient with end-stage renal disease on hemodialysis three times per week is admitted for a catheter-related infection. The case manager begins discharge planning on day one. Which post-acute need should be identified as the highest priority?", "options": {"A": "Verifying that the patient's dialysis center can accommodate the scheduled treatment after discharge.", "B": "Confirming a follow-up appointment with the patient's nephrologist for lab monitoring.", "C": "Arranging transportation to and from the dialysis center after hospital discharge.", "D": "Educating the patient about dietary restrictions for patients receiving hemodialysis."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "For a patient receiving hemodialysis, confirming that the dialysis center can continue scheduled treatments immediately after discharge is the highest clinical priority because missed dialysis sessions pose an immediate life-threatening risk. A nephrology follow-up is important but is secondary to ensuring the life-sustaining procedure continues without interruption. Transportation is critical but logistically cannot be arranged until the dialysis site and schedule are confirmed. Dietary education is an ongoing process that should have been initiated earlier and is not the priority during acute hospitalization planning."}, {"id": 22, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which of the following best describes case finding, as it relates to case management practice?", "options": {"A": "The systematic identification of individuals who would benefit from case management services.", "B": "The process of closing cases when a patient no longer meets high-risk criteria.", "C": "A legal process used to investigate malpractice claims involving high-risk patients.", "D": "A method of organizing patient records by diagnosis for quality reporting purposes."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Case finding refers to the proactive, systematic process of identifying patients in a population who have complex needs or high-risk characteristics and would benefit from case management enrollment. Closing cases when criteria are no longer met describes case termination, not case finding. Case finding has no legal or investigative connotation in the case management context. Organizing records by diagnosis for reporting is a data management function unrelated to the case management enrollment process."}, {"id": 23, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A community-based case manager is working with a 66-year-old patient recently diagnosed with Parkinson's disease. The patient mentions difficulty bathing and dressing independently. Which community resource most directly addresses this functional need?", "options": {"A": "A senior center offering weekly bingo and social luncheons for older adults.", "B": "A local transportation voucher program for medical appointment travel.", "C": "A home health aide who assists with activities of daily living several times per week.", "D": "A telephone reassurance program that provides daily check-in calls to isolated seniors."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A home health aide provides direct hands-on assistance with bathing and dressing, which are activities of daily living the patient has explicitly identified as difficult, making it the most targeted and appropriate resource. A senior center addresses socialization, not functional assistance with ADLs. Transportation vouchers address mobility to appointments, not in-home personal care needs. A telephone reassurance program addresses social isolation and safety monitoring but does not provide the physical assistance the patient requires."}, {"id": 24, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A payer denies coverage for a patient's inpatient psychiatric stay, citing insufficient documentation of medical necessity. The case manager disagrees with the denial. What is the appropriate next step?", "options": {"A": "Advise the patient to pay the hospital bill and pursue reimbursement independently.", "B": "Accept the denial as final and discharge the patient from inpatient psychiatric care immediately.", "C": "File a formal appeal with supporting clinical documentation within the required timeframe.", "D": "Contact the state insurance commissioner to report the payer for bad faith practices."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "When a payer denies coverage and the case manager believes the denial is not clinically supported, the standard process is to file a formal appeal with supplemental clinical documentation that addresses the specific reason for denial, within the payer's timeframe. Advising the patient to self-pay before appealing bypasses the appeals process and may create unnecessary financial harm. Accepting the denial without appeal fails the patient by not exhausting available options. Reporting to the insurance commissioner is a regulatory escalation step appropriate only after internal and external appeal processes have been exhausted."}, {"id": 25, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 78-year-old patient with advanced heart failure and a life expectancy of less than six months has expressed a desire to stop aggressive treatment and focus on comfort. The family is pushing for continued curative interventions. Which action by the case manager is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Support the family's request for curative interventions to avoid a conflict of interest.", "B": "Ask the physician to change the goals-of-care plan without involving the patient's family.", "C": "Facilitate a palliative care or hospice referral consistent with the patient's expressed wishes.", "D": "Document the patient's wishes and take no further action until the family reaches agreement."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The case manager advocates for the patient's expressed preferences, and when a capacitated patient articulates a desire for comfort-focused care, facilitating a palliative care or hospice referral is the most appropriate and ethical action. Prioritizing the family's wishes over those of a capacitated patient violates patient autonomy. Changing the care plan without engaging the family in a structured conversation may miss an opportunity for reconciliation and can escalate family conflict. Documenting the wishes without taking action leaves the patient's goals unaddressed and misses the advocacy function of the case manager."}, {"id": 26, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which of the following is a core function of care coordination that distinguishes it from disease management?", "options": {"A": "Focusing exclusively on a single chronic condition to achieve specific clinical outcome targets.", "B": "Providing clinical treatments such as medication titration and wound debridement.", "C": "Organizing and linking services across multiple providers, settings, and time to meet patient needs.", "D": "Conducting population-level analysis of claims data to identify cost reduction opportunities."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Care coordination is defined by its cross-setting, multi-provider, patient-centered organizational function that ensures services are connected and communicated across the full care continuum. Disease management focuses on a specific chronic condition and uses protocol-driven interventions to improve clinical outcomes in that disease. Clinical treatments such as medication titration and wound care are functions of licensed clinicians practicing within their scope, not care coordinators. Population-level claims analysis is a health economics or quality analytics function, not a defining feature of care coordination."}, {"id": 27, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is reviewing the discharge plan for a patient who will need wound care after a below-knee amputation. The patient has Medicaid and lives in a rural county. Which barrier should the case manager anticipate as most likely to disrupt the post-discharge wound care plan?", "options": {"A": "The patient's Medicaid plan may not cover any home health services after hospital discharge.", "B": "The surgeon may reschedule the follow-up appointment due to the rural location of the clinic.", "C": "Rural home health provider availability may be limited, creating a delay in service start.", "D": "The patient will likely refuse wound care because of previous negative healthcare experiences."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Rural areas commonly experience home health provider shortages, and securing wound care services in a rural county may require early and persistent outreach to identify an available agency before discharge occurs. Medicaid does cover home health services for medically necessary wound care, so coverage is not the primary anticipated barrier here. Surgeon scheduling is not typically affected by the patient's home location. While health system distrust is a real issue for some patients, assuming refusal without evidence is not appropriate care planning and may reflect implicit bias."}, {"id": 28, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is assigned to a high-risk obstetrics program. Which prenatal patient should be flagged for intensive case management enrollment?", "options": {"A": "A 28-year-old with a first uncomplicated pregnancy who attends all scheduled prenatal visits.", "B": "A 25-year-old who has asked for additional childbirth education class resources.", "C": "A 32-year-old with gestational hypertension, a prior preterm birth, and unstable housing.", "D": "A 30-year-old in the second trimester with normal labs and a BMI of 24."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Gestational hypertension, a prior preterm birth, and unstable housing represent a convergence of clinical and social risk factors that significantly increase maternal and neonatal morbidity, making this patient the appropriate target for intensive case management. A first uncomplicated pregnancy with full prenatal engagement indicates low risk and does not require intensive enrollment. A request for childbirth education is a patient empowerment behavior, not a risk indicator requiring intensive management. A healthy second-trimester presentation with normal labs represents a low-risk profile inconsistent with intensive case management criteria."}, {"id": 29, "domain": "care_management", "question": "The case manager notices that a patient with chronic low back pain has been prescribed opioids by three different physicians over a two-month period, with no documentation of coordination between them. Which action best reflects the case manager's role?", "options": {"A": "Report each prescribing physician separately to the state medical board for investigation.", "B": "Instruct the patient to stop taking all opioid medications immediately and switch to over-the-counter options.", "C": "Facilitate communication among the treating physicians and refer the patient for a pain specialist evaluation.", "D": "Contact the pharmacy and ask them to refuse refills from all three physicians going forward."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The case manager's role is to facilitate communication among fragmented providers and coordinate a comprehensive, safe pain management plan, which includes identifying a single pain specialist to lead management and prevent duplicative prescribing. Reporting physicians to the medical board is a regulatory action reserved for clear safety violations with supporting evidence, not a care coordination tool. Instructing the patient to abruptly stop opioids carries serious medical risk including withdrawal and is a clinical decision, not a case management function. Directing a pharmacy to refuse prescriptions exceeds the case manager's authority and could harm the patient."}, {"id": 30, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A managed care case manager is reviewing a request for bariatric surgery for a 44-year-old patient with a BMI of 41, type 2 diabetes, and sleep apnea. The patient has completed six months of medically supervised weight loss. Which factor most strongly supports medical necessity approval?", "options": {"A": "The patient's family history of obesity and cardiovascular disease in first-degree relatives.", "B": "The patient's personal desire to improve appearance and quality of life after failed dieting attempts.", "C": "Documentation of obesity-related comorbidities combined with completion of required pre-surgery protocol.", "D": "The treating physician's opinion that surgery is the best option for this particular patient."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Medical necessity for bariatric surgery is typically established by a combination of qualifying BMI, documented obesity-related comorbidities, and completion of a medically supervised weight loss program, all of which are present in this case. Family history is a risk factor but is not a standard component of bariatric surgery medical necessity criteria. Patient desire for aesthetic improvement, while valid personally, does not meet the clinical standard for medical necessity determination. Physician opinion alone, without supporting objective documentation, is insufficient to establish medical necessity under payer criteria."}, {"id": 31, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 59-year-old patient with multiple sclerosis is transitioning from an inpatient rehabilitation facility to home. The patient uses a power wheelchair and lives with a spouse who works full-time. Which home modification is the case manager most likely to prioritize requesting?", "options": {"A": "Installation of a ceiling fan in the bedroom to reduce heat sensitivity during rest.", "B": "Placement of a hospital bed in a downstairs room to avoid elevator dependence.", "C": "Widening of doorways and installation of a wheelchair ramp for accessible home entry.", "D": "Addition of grab bars in the bathroom to assist with independent standing transfers."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A patient who uses a power wheelchair requires adequate doorway width and accessible entry ramps to physically enter and move through the home, which is the foundational modification for home discharge to be safe. A ceiling fan may help with temperature regulation in MS but is a comfort modification, not a structural safety necessity. A hospital bed may be appropriate but requires a prior assessment of whether the patient uses the bed independently or needs caregiver repositioning. Grab bars support standing transfers, which are not relevant for a patient who uses a power wheelchair."}, {"id": 32, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which approach to care plan development best reflects a patient-centered model of case management?", "options": {"A": "Creating a standardized care plan template and applying it uniformly to all patients with the same diagnosis.", "B": "Setting clinical outcome targets based on national benchmarks and monitoring the patient against those targets.", "C": "Developing goals collaboratively with the patient based on their values, preferences, and life circumstances.", "D": "Allowing the insurance company to define care plan goals based on coverage and cost considerations."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Patient-centered care planning requires that goals be developed with the patient rather than for the patient, reflecting what matters to the individual based on their values, daily realities, and personal priorities. Applying a uniform template ignores the individual variation that defines patient-centered care. Setting goals based solely on national benchmarks measures population averages rather than individual patient needs. Allowing a payer to define care goals prioritizes cost and coverage over clinical and personal need, which is contrary to patient-centered principles."}, {"id": 33, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A hospital-based case manager is asked to evaluate a patient's readiness for discharge from the medical-surgical unit. Which combination of findings most strongly indicates the patient is not ready for safe discharge?", "options": {"A": "Patient has a follow-up appointment scheduled and a family member at home during the day.", "B": "Patient is ambulatory with a walker and has been medically cleared by the attending physician.", "C": "Patient cannot demonstrate correct medication administration and has no caregiver available.", "D": "Patient expresses some anxiety about going home but understands the discharge instructions."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The combination of an inability to self-administer medications correctly and the absence of any caregiver creates a high-risk discharge scenario that could directly lead to medication errors, decompensation, and readmission. A patient with a follow-up appointment and daytime family support has basic safety elements in place. A patient who is ambulatory and medically cleared has met clinical discharge criteria even if functional and social planning continues. Mild anxiety with adequate health literacy and instruction comprehension does not constitute a safety barrier to discharge."}, {"id": 34, "domain": "care_management", "question": "The case manager is reviewing a patient's chart before a care conference. The patient's most recent depression screening score increased significantly from the last visit. The patient has untreated depression, poorly controlled diabetes, and frequent missed appointments. How should the case manager address this?", "options": {"A": "Focus the care conference exclusively on the diabetes A1c goal and defer the depression discussion.", "B": "Attribute the missed appointments to patient noncompliance and document accordingly in the chart.", "C": "Ask the primary care physician to prescribe an antidepressant without further patient evaluation.", "D": "Recognize that untreated depression may be driving the missed appointments and poor diabetes control."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Depression is a well-established driver of chronic disease nonadherence and appointment avoidance; recognizing this bidirectional relationship allows the case manager to address the root cause rather than treating diabetes control and missed appointments as isolated problems. Focusing solely on the A1c goal without addressing depression ignores the behavioral health factor most likely to undermine all other interventions. Recommending a specific medication without evaluation is a clinical decision that requires physician and patient involvement. Attributing missed appointments to noncompliance without exploring the underlying cause is a reductive and potentially stigmatizing documentation practice."}, {"id": 35, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is working with a health plan to reduce avoidable emergency department visits among high-risk members. Which population-level strategy is most likely to produce sustained reduction in ED utilization?", "options": {"A": "Increasing copayments for ED visits to discourage non-urgent use across all plan members.", "B": "Requiring all members to call a nurse hotline before visiting the emergency department.", "C": "Sending educational flyers explaining when to use urgent care instead of the emergency department.", "D": "Expanding after-hours primary care access and same-day urgent care slots for high-risk members."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Expanding after-hours primary care access and same-day urgent care availability addresses the structural gap that drives many avoidable ED visits, particularly for high-risk members who need timely clinical assessment but cannot access their regular provider. Financial penalties through higher copayments disproportionately harm low-income members and may result in delayed care for genuinely urgent conditions rather than behavior change. Educational flyers address awareness but not access, which is typically the primary barrier to appropriate care-seeking. Mandatory nurse hotline calls add friction to emergency care access and do not address the underlying access deficit."}, {"id": 36, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is working with a 70-year-old patient who reports taking 14 different medications prescribed by four different specialists. The patient cannot name half of the medications and is unsure which ones are for what conditions. Which action should the case manager initiate first?", "options": {"A": "Request a medication therapy management review by a clinical pharmacist.", "B": "Advise the patient to stop taking any medications they cannot name or identify.", "C": "Send a list of all 14 medications to each prescribing physician for individual review.", "D": "Recommend the patient purchase a pill organizer to improve daily medication adherence."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Medication therapy management by a clinical pharmacist is the appropriate structured process for reviewing a complex polypharmacy regimen, identifying interactions, duplications, and unnecessary medications, and simplifying the regimen with prescriber involvement. Advising the patient to stop taking unrecognized medications is dangerous and could cause serious adverse effects from abrupt discontinuation. Sending medication lists to each prescriber individually is fragmented and does not achieve the reconciliation and rationalization that a unified MTM review provides. A pill organizer improves adherence to a regimen but does not address the safety risk of an unreviewed 14-medication regimen."}, {"id": 37, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is evaluating post-acute options for a 66-year-old patient after a mild stroke with residual left arm weakness. The patient is motivated, has a spouse caregiver, and scored well on cognitive assessments. Which post-acute level of care is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Long-term acute care hospital for medically complex patients requiring extended physician oversight.", "B": "Skilled nursing facility for patients needing 24-hour nursing supervision after stroke.", "C": "Inpatient rehabilitation facility for patients requiring three hours of therapy per day.", "D": "Home with outpatient physical and occupational therapy and support from the spouse caregiver."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A motivated patient with mild deficits, preserved cognition, a capable in-home caregiver, and residual function that does not require intensive daily therapy is an appropriate candidate for home discharge with outpatient therapy, which is the least restrictive and most cost-effective option. LTACH is for patients with prolonged medical complexity requiring acute-level hospital services, which is not indicated here. Inpatient rehabilitation requires that the patient tolerate and benefit from three hours of therapy per day, which may exceed what mild weakness warrants. SNF is appropriate for patients needing skilled nursing care or daily skilled therapy that cannot be safely provided at home, which does not align with this patient's profile."}, {"id": 38, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is conducting an initial assessment for a newly enrolled patient with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Which assessment component most directly informs the development of a chronic disease management care plan?", "options": {"A": "The patient's ZIP code and proximity to the nearest hospital with a pulmonology department.", "B": "The patient's employment status and hours worked per week in their current occupation.", "C": "A review of the patient's insurance coverage to determine which medications are on the formulary.", "D": "The patient's current functional status, symptom burden, exacerbation history, and self-management capacity."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Functional status, symptom burden, exacerbation frequency, and self-management capacity are the core clinical and behavioral dimensions that directly shape the goals, interventions, and intensity of a COPD disease management care plan. Geographic proximity to a hospital informs access considerations but does not guide the care plan's clinical content. Insurance formulary review is a practical step in care planning but is not the assessment component that defines management priorities. Employment status may affect scheduling and stress but does not directly inform the clinical structure of a chronic disease management plan."}, {"id": 39, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which of the following best defines the difference between a care manager and a care coordinator in most case management models?", "options": {"A": "Care coordinators hold advanced clinical licenses while care managers are typically lay health workers.", "B": "Care managers focus on inpatient settings and care coordinators manage only outpatient populations.", "C": "Care coordinators are employed by insurance companies while care managers work exclusively in hospitals.", "D": "Care managers take primary accountability for the care plan while care coordinators handle logistical tasks."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "In most case management models, care managers bear primary accountability for assessing complex patients, developing care plans, and monitoring outcomes, while care coordinators handle scheduling, referrals, and logistical follow-through to execute the plan. Care coordinators do not universally hold higher-level licenses; the reverse is more commonly true, with care managers often holding clinical credentials. Both roles are employed across payer, provider, and community settings, not segregated by employer type. The distinction is not defined by care setting but by scope of clinical accountability within the care team."}, {"id": 40, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 55-year-old patient with end-stage liver disease declines a referral for liver transplant evaluation and states that he wants to live his remaining time at home with his family. The care team believes he is making a medically inadvisable choice. Which case management principle applies here?", "options": {"A": "Beneficence requires that the case manager override the patient's decision to protect his health.", "B": "The care team should involve hospital legal counsel before the patient's decision can be honored.", "C": "The case manager should pursue a psychiatric evaluation to rule out decision-making impairment.", "D": "Patient self-determination supports the patient's right to decline transplant evaluation and choose comfort care."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Patient self-determination is a foundational ethical principle in case management; a patient with decision-making capacity has the right to decline any medical intervention, including transplant evaluation, and to choose how they spend their remaining time. Beneficence supports offering the best clinical options but does not permit overriding an informed, capacitated refusal. A psychiatric evaluation is appropriate when there is clinical evidence of impaired decision-making capacity, not simply because the patient's choice differs from the care team's recommendation. Legal involvement is not warranted when a capacitated patient exercises the right to decline unwanted medical intervention."}, {"id": 41, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager working in an accountable care organization is reviewing panel data and finds that patients with uncontrolled hypertension have a 40% rate of missing annual foot exams, which are covered benefits. What type of intervention addresses this care gap most efficiently?", "options": {"A": "A letter from the ACO CEO asking members to schedule preventive appointments this year.", "B": "Adding a foot exam reminder to the discharge paperwork for hypertension-related hospitalizations.", "C": "A provider education session about the importance of including foot exams in hypertension visits.", "D": "An automated outreach program that identifies overdue patients and offers direct appointment scheduling."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "An automated outreach program that identifies members with an overdue foot exam and directly connects them to scheduling is a scalable, efficient population health intervention that removes the patient-level barriers to care gap closure. A CEO letter is a passive communication with low impact on behavior change at scale. Provider education improves awareness but does not directly reach the 40% of patients who are currently missing the exam. Adding reminders to discharge paperwork only reaches patients who are hospitalized, leaving the majority of the panel unaddressed."}, {"id": 42, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 48-year-old construction worker with a new diagnosis of type 1 diabetes needs insulin but states he cannot afford the $300 monthly cost and has no health insurance. Which resource should the case manager explore first?", "options": {"A": "Referring the patient to the nearest emergency department where insulin can be obtained at no cost.", "B": "Advising the patient to monitor symptoms and return to the clinic if his glucose exceeds 400 mg/dL.", "C": "Recommending that the patient borrow insulin from a friend with a similar prescription.", "D": "Contacting the insulin manufacturer's patient assistance program for low-income, uninsured patients."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Pharmaceutical manufacturer patient assistance programs provide free or low-cost insulin to uninsured and underinsured patients who meet income criteria, and they are the most direct and appropriate resource to address this identified financial barrier. Emergency departments do not dispense insulin for ongoing chronic disease management and are not a sustainable or appropriate source. Borrowing insulin from another patient is medically unsafe because insulin types and doses are individualized and cannot be safely interchanged. Advising the patient to wait until critically high glucose levels occur is dangerous and delays medically necessary treatment for a newly diagnosed type 1 diabetic."}, {"id": 43, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is reviewing the care plan of a patient who has been enrolled in case management for six months after a myocardial infarction. The patient has achieved all care plan goals, is adherent to medications, attends cardiac rehab, and has had no further hospitalizations. Which action is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Continue monthly intensive case management contacts indefinitely as a preventive measure.", "B": "Enroll the patient in a disease management program to maintain motivation and engagement long-term.", "C": "Refer the patient to cardiology for continued case management oversight under specialist supervision.", "D": "Conduct a formal reassessment and consider stepping down the patient to a lower intensity or closing the case."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When a patient has met all care plan goals and demonstrates sustained self-management capability, the appropriate case management response is to formally reassess and consider transitioning the patient to a lower intensity level or closing the case, consistent with a goal-directed, outcomes-based practice model. Continuing intensive contact without clinical justification is not evidence-based and may create unnecessary dependency. Specialist referral for ongoing case management is not indicated for a patient who is stable and self-managing. Disease management enrollment may be appropriate for long-term support but should follow a structured reassessment, not be used as a substitute for case closure decision-making."}, {"id": 44, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Which of the following scenarios best illustrates the concept of avoidable hospitalization in the context of case management quality measurement?", "options": {"A": "A patient admitted for an elective knee replacement procedure that has been scheduled for three months.", "B": "A patient admitted for a new diagnosis of appendicitis requiring emergency surgical intervention.", "C": "A patient admitted to the ICU following a motor vehicle accident on the highway.", "D": "A patient with heart failure admitted for fluid overload because outpatient diuretic dose was not adjusted despite weight gain."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "An avoidable hospitalization is one that could have been prevented with timely and adequate outpatient management; a heart failure admission caused by failure to adjust diuretic therapy in response to documented weight gain represents a textbook example of a preventable acute care episode. An elective surgical admission is planned and necessary, not avoidable. A trauma admission following a motor vehicle accident is an acute, unforeseeable event outside the scope of disease management. Emergency appendicitis is a sudden surgical emergency that no amount of case management could reasonably prevent."}, {"id": 45, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is preparing a patient with newly diagnosed multiple sclerosis for a complex treatment regimen that includes infusion therapy every six weeks. The patient works full-time and has two young children. Which barrier should the case manager proactively assess?", "options": {"A": "Whether the patient's neurologist has board certification in multiple sclerosis management.", "B": "Whether the patient's spouse agrees with the neurologist's treatment recommendation.", "C": "Whether the infusion center has adequate parking for patients who drive to appointments.", "D": "Whether the patient can arrange childcare and schedule work absences around infusion appointments."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "For a working parent with young children, the practical barriers of childcare and work absence scheduling are high-probability obstacles to infusion appointment adherence that should be assessed and addressed before therapy begins. The neurologist's board certification is a provider credentialing concern, not a patient-level care coordination barrier. Parking availability is a logistical detail that the infusion center manages and is not a proactive case management assessment priority. The spouse's agreement with the treatment plan is relevant to support, but the patient's own ability to attend appointments is the primary adherence barrier to assess."}, {"id": 46, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 68-year-old patient recovering from bilateral total knee replacements is medically stable and can tolerate three hours of daily therapy. The case manager is recommending an appropriate post-acute placement. Which setting best matches her rehabilitation intensity needs?", "options": {"A": "Inpatient rehabilitation facility providing intensive therapy for at least three hours daily.", "B": "Long-term acute care hospital for patients requiring extended acute-level medical management.", "C": "Skilled nursing facility providing sub-acute rehabilitation at a reduced therapy intensity.", "D": "Home health agency offering physical therapy visits two to three times per week."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Inpatient rehabilitation facilities are designed for patients who can tolerate and benefit from at least three hours of therapy per day, making it the appropriate choice here. Long-term acute care hospitals serve patients with complex ongoing medical needs such as ventilator dependency, not primarily rehabilitation needs. Skilled nursing facilities provide sub-acute rehabilitation for patients who cannot manage three daily hours of therapy. Home health is appropriate for homebound patients needing low-intensity rehabilitation."}, {"id": 47, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient with poorly controlled Type 2 diabetes says, 'I know I should exercise more, but I just cannot find the time with my job and kids.' Which response by the case manager best reflects a motivational interviewing technique?", "options": {"A": "Let's look at your schedule right now and block out time for daily exercise sessions.", "B": "It sounds like you want to be more active but feel pulled in too many directions.", "C": "Exercise is one of the most effective ways to control your blood sugar long term.", "D": "Many patients with diabetes find that short 10-minute walks are very manageable."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Reflective listening, a core motivational interviewing skill, involves mirroring the patient's words and feelings to build rapport and explore ambivalence without judgment. Option A is a directive response that skips ambivalence exploration and may feel coercive. Option C is an unsolicited educational statement that can feel lecturing and damage the therapeutic alliance. Option D offers advice before the patient has expressed readiness to change, which may increase resistance."}, {"id": 48, "domain": "care_management", "question": "At discharge, a hospital-based case manager calculates a patient's LACE score of 11, placing the patient in the high-risk category. The LACE index was developed specifically to identify patients at risk for which outcome?", "options": {"A": "Falls during the inpatient stay requiring physical therapy consultation.", "B": "Medication non-adherence within the first 30 days after discharge.", "C": "Hospital readmission or death within 30 days of discharge.", "D": "Development of a hospital-acquired infection during the current admission."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The LACE index uses Length of stay, Acuity of admission, Comorbidities, and Emergency department visits to predict the risk of 30-day readmission or death after hospital discharge. It is not a falls prediction tool. It was not designed to predict medication adherence, though low adherence may contribute to readmission. Hospital-acquired infection prediction uses different screening tools. A LACE score of 10 or higher triggers intensive transitional care interventions."}, {"id": 49, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient with congestive heart failure is transferring from an acute care hospital to a skilled nursing facility. The case manager wants to prevent readmission during the first 72 hours after transfer. Which action is most critical to safe handoff?", "options": {"A": "Scheduling a follow-up appointment with the cardiologist within two weeks of transfer.", "B": "Providing the patient with a written list of heart failure warning signs before discharge.", "C": "Confirming that the skilled nursing facility accepts the patient's insurance plan.", "D": "Sending a complete and accurate medical summary including current medications to the SNF."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Incomplete medication information and gaps in clinical handoff documentation are leading causes of early readmission after care transitions, making a complete and accurate medical summary the most critical element. Scheduling a cardiology follow-up is important but occurs beyond the immediate 72-hour window. Warning signs education is valuable but secondary to ensuring the receiving facility has the clinical information needed to continue safe care. Insurance confirmation is an administrative step that should occur prior to arranging the transfer."}, {"id": 50, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is preparing discharge education for a patient identified as having low health literacy. Which approach is most appropriate when providing written discharge instructions to this patient?", "options": {"A": "Use plain language at a sixth-grade reading level with simple diagrams and pictures.", "B": "Provide clinical documentation from the chart as the patient's primary reference source.", "C": "Give a comprehensive booklet covering all possible complications and warning signs.", "D": "Ask the patient's family members to read and explain the materials to the patient."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Plain-language materials written at a sixth-grade reading level with visual supports are the evidence-based standard for patients with low health literacy. Clinical documentation uses medical terminology inappropriate for patient education. Comprehensive booklets overwhelm patients with low health literacy and reduce comprehension and adherence. Family members can supplement education but should not replace direct communication with the patient, who deserves understandable information about her own care."}, {"id": 51, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A managed care organization denies inpatient authorization for a patient admitted with pneumonia, stating the patient does not meet inpatient criteria. The attending physician disagrees with the clinical determination. What is the most appropriate next step for the case manager?", "options": {"A": "Discharge the patient immediately to avoid financial liability for the hospital.", "B": "Facilitate a peer-to-peer review between the attending physician and the payer's medical director.", "C": "File a formal written appeal with the state insurance commissioner on the patient's behalf.", "D": "Transfer the patient to a facility that accepts the patient's insurance without restriction."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A peer-to-peer review allows the attending physician to present clinical findings directly to the payer's medical director and frequently results in overturning an initial denial. Discharging a patient who requires inpatient care may constitute patient abandonment and is clinically unsafe. Filing with the state insurance commissioner bypasses the required internal appeal process. Transferring the patient does not resolve the coverage dispute and may be premature and clinically disruptive."}, {"id": 52, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A primary care practice adopts a patient-centered medical home model. In this model, the case manager's primary role is best described as which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Authorizing inpatient admissions and coordinating discharge planning for hospitalized patients.", "B": "Reviewing claims data to identify high-utilization patients for payer outreach programs.", "C": "Coordinating comprehensive care across the full care continuum for a defined patient panel.", "D": "Providing telephonic disease management for patients with specific chronic conditions only."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In a patient-centered medical home, the case manager coordinates all aspects of care for a defined panel of patients, addressing medical, behavioral, and social needs across all settings. Inpatient authorization and discharge planning are utilization management functions tied to hospital settings. Claims-based outreach is more typical of health plan case management. Disease management programs address specific chronic conditions rather than providing whole-person care coordination across the continuum."}, {"id": 53, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager reviewing her diabetic patient panel finds that 40% of patients have not received a dilated eye exam in the past 12 months. Which action most directly addresses this population-level care gap?", "options": {"A": "Report the finding to the state health department as a quality concern requiring investigation.", "B": "Notify each patient that she is at risk for diabetic retinopathy without arranging follow-up.", "C": "Request a formal chart audit by the quality improvement department of the practice.", "D": "Contact patients and their primary care providers to schedule overdue dilated eye exams."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Proactively contacting patients and coordinating scheduling with providers is the case manager's core role in closing population-level care gaps. Reporting to the state health department is not indicated for an internal care gap finding that can be addressed operationally. Notifying patients about retinopathy risk without arranging follow-up informs without solving the access problem. A quality audit documents the issue but does not resolve the care gap for individual patients."}, {"id": 54, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A high-risk patient with COPD calls the case manager reporting shortness of breath and considering going to the emergency department. The case manager determines her symptoms are consistent with a moderate exacerbation without severe respiratory distress. The best first action is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Contact the patient's primary care provider for same-day evaluation or telephone management.", "B": "Advise the patient to activate 911 for emergency transport to the nearest hospital.", "C": "Tell the patient to use her rescue inhaler and monitor symptoms for 24 hours alone.", "D": "Schedule a follow-up appointment with pulmonology within the next two weeks."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Connecting the patient with her primary care provider for same-day evaluation or telephone guidance is the appropriate response for a moderate exacerbation, preventing an unnecessary ED visit while ensuring medical assessment. Activating 911 is appropriate for severe respiratory distress, not a moderate exacerbation. Advising self-management without physician input is insufficient for a moderate exacerbation with worsening symptoms. A two-week pulmonology appointment does not address an acute problem requiring prompt attention."}, {"id": 55, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient is admitted from a skilled nursing facility with altered mental status. The case manager conducting medication reconciliation discovers two medications on the Beers Criteria list of potentially inappropriate medications for older adults. What is the case manager's most appropriate action?", "options": {"A": "Discontinue the Beers Criteria medications and document the change in the care plan.", "B": "Bring the identified medications to the attending physician's attention for clinical review.", "C": "Educate the patient about the risks associated with Beers Criteria medications at discharge.", "D": "Notify the skilled nursing facility that it has violated safe medication prescribing standards."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Medication reconciliation findings that suggest potentially unsafe prescribing must be escalated to the physician who holds prescribing authority, not acted on independently by the case manager. Case managers do not have independent prescribing authority and cannot discontinue medications. Patient education about medication risks is secondary to ensuring the physician reviews and acts on the clinical concern first. Notifying the SNF may be appropriate eventually but does not address the patient's immediate safety during the current admission."}, {"id": 56, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient with heart failure being discharged says, 'I want to learn everything I can about managing my condition at home.' Using the Patient Activation Measure (PAM), this statement most accurately reflects which level of patient activation?", "options": {"A": "Level 1, where the patient does not yet understand her role in self-management.", "B": "Level 2, where the patient lacks confidence and knowledge to take action independently.", "C": "Level 3, where the patient has goals and is beginning to take action toward self-management.", "D": "Level 4, where the patient maintains self-management behaviors even under stress."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "PAM Level 3 describes patients who are knowledgeable, set goals, and are beginning to take self-management actions, which aligns with the patient's expressed desire to actively learn. Level 1 patients do not yet recognize their role in care. Level 2 patients know they should act but lack the skills or confidence to do so. Level 4 patients sustain self-management behaviors consistently even during illness or life stressors, which has not yet been demonstrated by this patient."}, {"id": 57, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 72-year-old patient with Stage IV lung cancer continues receiving aggressive chemotherapy despite declining functional status and repeated hospitalizations for pain crises. He tells the case manager he is 'tired of fighting.' What is the most appropriate case management intervention?", "options": {"A": "Document the patient's statement and continue current care without changing the plan.", "B": "Consult social work to address the patient's emotional distress as an independent issue.", "C": "Notify the physician that the patient is experiencing signs of depression and anxiety.", "D": "Initiate a goals-of-care conversation and facilitate a palliative care consultation."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A patient with advanced cancer, declining function, and an expressed wish to stop fighting is signaling a possible shift in his goals away from curative treatment, warranting a goals-of-care conversation and palliative care consultation. Simply documenting the statement without acting on it misses a critical advocacy opportunity. Social work alone does not address the medical and goals-of-care dimensions. Depression referral is important but is a narrower response than a comprehensive goals-of-care discussion that includes the medical team."}, {"id": 58, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A payer's utilization management department requires concurrent review for all inpatient admissions. During concurrent review, what is the case manager's primary responsibility?", "options": {"A": "Provide clinical information to the payer supporting the medical necessity of continued inpatient care.", "B": "Process discharge paperwork and schedule post-discharge follow-up appointments for the patient.", "C": "Conduct a patient satisfaction survey to identify gaps in the care delivered during the stay.", "D": "Request prior authorization for post-acute services anticipated after the patient's discharge."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Concurrent review requires the case manager to submit updated clinical information to the payer justifying continued inpatient admission at the appropriate level of care. Discharge paperwork and follow-up scheduling are discharge planning functions, separate from concurrent review. Patient satisfaction surveys are quality improvement activities unrelated to utilization management. Post-acute service authorization is part of discharge planning and occurs as a separate process distinct from ongoing concurrent review."}, {"id": 59, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is implementing a self-management support program for patients with Type 2 diabetes. Which component is most essential to achieving long-term success in diabetes self-management?", "options": {"A": "Providing a standardized meal plan approved by a registered dietitian for all enrolled patients.", "B": "Teaching patients to monitor blood glucose and recognize and respond to their readings.", "C": "Scheduling quarterly physician visits to review HbA1c levels and medication adjustments.", "D": "Enrolling patients in group education classes led by a certified diabetes educator."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Teaching patients to self-monitor blood glucose, understand what readings mean, and take appropriate action is the foundational self-management skill for diabetes, without which patients cannot manage their condition between provider visits. Standardized meal plans ignore individual preferences, cultural factors, and co-existing conditions. Quarterly physician visits are insufficient without patient self-monitoring to detect problems between appointments. Group education is valuable but secondary to individual skill-building in self-monitoring."}, {"id": 60, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A Medicare patient was placed in observation status for two nights before inpatient admission. She is now being discharged and requires skilled nursing facility care. Which statement about her Medicare SNF benefit eligibility is correct?", "options": {"A": "She qualifies for Medicare Part A SNF coverage after a combined 48-hour observation stay.", "B": "She qualifies because any hospital stay immediately preceding SNF admission satisfies the requirement.", "C": "She does not qualify because observation status days do not count toward the inpatient requirement.", "D": "She qualifies if her physician certifies that skilled nursing care is medically necessary."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Medicare Part A SNF coverage requires a qualifying inpatient stay of at least three consecutive days, and observation status days do not count toward this requirement regardless of how many observation days occurred. Observation stays are billed under Medicare Part B, not Part A. The physician's certification of medical necessity is required but does not waive or substitute for the three-day inpatient rule. Any gap in the three-day inpatient count disqualifies the patient from Part A SNF coverage."}, {"id": 61, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A health plan case manager reviews claims data to identify members who would most benefit from intensive case management services. Which indicator most effectively identifies a member as high-complexity requiring prioritized outreach?", "options": {"A": "Membership in a Medicare Advantage plan for more than three consecutive years.", "B": "A single emergency department visit in the past 12 months without hospitalization.", "C": "A diagnosis of well-controlled hypertension managed with one antihypertensive agent.", "D": "Three or more chronic conditions combined with two or more ED visits in the past year."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Multiple chronic conditions combined with frequent emergency department utilization is a strong predictor of high cost and care complexity and is the most reliable indicator for prioritizing intensive case management outreach. Long-term Medicare Advantage enrollment alone does not indicate medical complexity. A single ED visit may reflect an isolated acute episode rather than ongoing complexity. Hypertension controlled on one medication typically represents a low-complexity, well-managed condition with limited case management need."}, {"id": 62, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 79-year-old patient recovering from hip replacement surgery is being considered for Medicare home health services after discharge. Which criterion must be met for the patient to qualify for Medicare home health benefits?", "options": {"A": "The patient must be homebound and require at least one skilled service such as nursing or therapy.", "B": "The patient must have been hospitalized for at least five consecutive days before discharge.", "C": "The patient must be unable to perform at least three activities of daily living independently.", "D": "The patient must have a family member available at home to assist with care daily."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Medicare home health eligibility requires that the patient be homebound, meaning leaving home requires a considerable effort, and that the patient need at least one skilled service such as skilled nursing, physical therapy, speech therapy, or occupational therapy. There is no minimum hospitalization length requirement for home health; patients may be referred directly from the community. ADL limitations are assessed but are not the sole defining eligibility criterion. A family caregiver is helpful but is not a Medicare home health eligibility requirement."}, {"id": 63, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient is enrolled in both Medicare and Medicaid. The case manager explains how her benefits coordinate when receiving services. Which statement most accurately describes how dual-eligible beneficiary coverage works?", "options": {"A": "Medicare and Medicaid split costs equally for all covered services the patient receives.", "B": "Medicare pays as the primary payer, and Medicaid may cover cost-sharing and additional services.", "C": "Medicaid pays first for all services because it targets lower-income individuals specifically.", "D": "Dual-eligible patients choose which program to use for each separate episode of care."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "For dual-eligible beneficiaries, Medicare is always the primary payer, and Medicaid acts as secondary, covering Medicare cost-sharing amounts and services not covered by Medicare such as long-term care. Medicare and Medicaid do not split costs equally. Medicaid does not pay first simply because it targets lower-income populations; federal rules establish Medicare's primary payer status. Dual-eligible patients do not choose between programs for individual services; the coordination rules are set by federal and state policy."}, {"id": 64, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager working in a value-based care program uses a predictive risk-stratification algorithm to identify high-risk patients. Which data source is most commonly used as input for population-level risk stratification models?", "options": {"A": "Patient-reported health surveys completed during annual wellness visits.", "B": "Telephone intake assessments conducted by health plan care coordinators.", "C": "Claims data reflecting diagnoses, procedures, and utilization patterns over time.", "D": "Social determinants of health screening forms completed in primary care offices."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Claims data are the most widely used input for population-level risk stratification models because they are available for all enrolled members, include longitudinal diagnostic and utilization history, and enable risk prediction at scale. Patient-reported surveys and telephone assessments are valuable but are not universally collected across entire populations. SDOH screening forms are increasingly used but are not yet consistently captured or standardized across all health systems to support algorithmic risk models."}, {"id": 65, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager receives a first-level denial from a payer for an inpatient psychiatric admission, citing that outpatient treatment was not first attempted. The case manager reviews the documentation and believes the denial was made in clinical error. What is the most appropriate next step?", "options": {"A": "Immediately escalate the case to the state insurance commissioner for external review.", "B": "Discharge the patient and arrange outpatient psychiatric follow-up as the payer requires.", "C": "Accept the denial and inform the patient that insurance coverage is unavailable.", "D": "Submit a written first-level appeal with clinical documentation supporting medical necessity."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A first-level written appeal with supporting clinical documentation is the required first step when disputing a payer denial through the internal appeal process. Escalating immediately to the state insurance commissioner bypasses required internal appeal steps. Discharging a patient who medically requires inpatient psychiatric care based on a coverage denial may be clinically unsafe and may constitute patient abandonment. Accepting the denial without appeal fails to advocate for the patient and does not fulfill the case manager's professional obligation."}, {"id": 66, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A hospital implements a clinical pathway for total hip replacement to standardize care and reduce variation. A clinical pathway is best described as which type of tool?", "options": {"A": "A document that outlines expected interventions and milestones by day for a specific diagnosis.", "B": "A staffing ratio guide that establishes minimum nurse-to-patient ratios for orthopedic units.", "C": "A set of physician orders for the duration of the patient's hospitalization from admission to discharge.", "D": "A quality metrics scorecard used to measure orthopedic department performance annually."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A clinical pathway is an evidence-based care management tool that defines the expected sequence of events, interventions, and outcomes for a specific condition or procedure on a day-by-day or phase-by-phase basis. It is not a staffing ratio guide. Physician order sets are related documents but define orders rather than the full expected care sequence. Quality metrics documents define measurement criteria rather than the sequenced progression of clinical care across a hospital stay."}, {"id": 67, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager conducts a post-discharge call to a heart failure patient 48 hours after discharge. The patient reports a weight gain of four pounds since leaving the hospital and mild ankle swelling. What is the most appropriate immediate response?", "options": {"A": "Advise the patient to restrict sodium intake and increase fluid intake over the next 24 hours.", "B": "Contact the patient's physician immediately to report the findings and receive further instructions.", "C": "Tell the patient to go directly to the emergency department for evaluation of worsening fluid.", "D": "Schedule a follow-up appointment with cardiology for the patient within the next 14 days."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A four-pound weight gain within 48 hours of heart failure discharge is a red flag for fluid retention and early decompensation, requiring prompt physician notification to determine whether medication adjustment or urgent evaluation is needed. Advising dietary changes without physician input delays appropriate medical management of a potential clinical deterioration. The ED may be appropriate but should be directed by the physician after clinical assessment, not by the case manager acting independently. A 14-day appointment is far too delayed for an acute symptom change."}, {"id": 68, "domain": "care_management", "question": "During a care management assessment, a patient reports living in overcrowded housing and struggling to afford food and medications each month. The case manager correctly identifies these challenges as which category of health barrier?", "options": {"A": "Clinical barriers related to poor self-management behaviors and medical non-adherence.", "B": "Behavioral barriers stemming from a lack of motivation and insufficient health knowledge.", "C": "Social determinants of health affecting the patient's ability to manage her conditions.", "D": "Financial barriers that fall outside the scope of the case manager's professional role."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Housing instability and food and medication insecurity are social determinants of health that directly affect health outcomes and the ability to manage chronic conditions. They are not primarily caused by poor self-management behavior or lack of motivation. SDOH barriers are squarely within the case manager's scope of practice to identify and address through community resource linkage, advocacy, and care coordination. Addressing social determinants is now a recognized core CCM competency aligned with CCMC standards."}, {"id": 69, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 70-year-old Medicare patient was placed in observation status for a chest pain workup, resolved after two nights, and was discharged home. She contacts the case manager concerned about unexpected hospital bills significantly higher than she anticipated. What is the most accurate explanation for the patient's higher costs?", "options": {"A": "Observation status is covered fully under Medicare Part A with no patient cost-sharing.", "B": "Observation patients receive the same Medicare benefits as formally admitted inpatients.", "C": "Her costs were higher than expected because she stayed more than 24 hours in observation.", "D": "Observation status is billed under Medicare Part B, which carries different cost-sharing than Part A."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Observation status is billed under Medicare Part B, meaning patients pay the 20% outpatient coinsurance rather than the lower inpatient deductible under Part A, which often results in higher out-of-pocket costs. Medicare Part A does not apply to observation stays regardless of duration. Observation patients do not receive the same benefits as inpatients; they are outpatients from a billing perspective. The number of observation days does not change the billing classification or applicable cost-sharing rules."}, {"id": 70, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient with moderate dementia and a history of falls refuses discharge to a skilled nursing facility and insists on returning home alone with no family support and inability to demonstrate safe functional ability. The case manager's first step is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Assess the patient's decision-making capacity with the assistance of the clinical team.", "B": "Honor the patient's request and arrange daily home health visits to minimize fall risk.", "C": "Contact Adult Protective Services to report the patient as unable to care for herself.", "D": "Request a court-ordered guardianship hearing before the patient's discharge is arranged."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Assessing the patient's decision-making capacity is the essential first step when a patient makes a potentially unsafe discharge decision. If capacity is confirmed, self-determination must be respected even when the decision appears clinically unwise. If she lacks capacity, the team may involve a surrogate or initiate a legal process. Immediately arranging home health assumes capacity without confirming it. APS referral is appropriate if abuse or neglect is suspected but is premature before capacity assessment. Guardianship is a last resort pursued only after capacity assessment and exhaustion of less restrictive options."}, {"id": 71, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient with COPD is being discharged with a prescription for home oxygen therapy. Before the case manager arranges DME delivery, the single most important step to complete first is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Contact the DME supplier to confirm equipment availability and estimated delivery timeline.", "B": "Obtain a written physician order and prior authorization from the patient's insurance plan.", "C": "Confirm that the patient's home has adequate electrical outlets for the oxygen concentrator.", "D": "Schedule a home health nursing visit to provide oxygen safety education before delivery."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A written physician order and insurance prior authorization are the necessary prerequisites for home oxygen delivery; without authorization, the equipment may not be covered and the patient may face unexpected out-of-pocket costs. Contacting the supplier is the appropriate next step after authorization is confirmed. Home safety assessment and nursing education are important but occur after coverage is secured. Proceeding to delivery without authorization exposes the patient to uncovered medical expenses."}, {"id": 72, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is designing a disease management program for patients with moderate-to-severe persistent asthma. Which single intervention has the strongest evidence for reducing asthma-related ED visits and hospitalizations?", "options": {"A": "Monthly nurse telephone calls to review medication lists and prescription refill needs.", "B": "Mailing written asthma action plans to all enrolled patients on a quarterly schedule.", "C": "Teaching patients to use a personalized written asthma action plan and peak flow meter.", "D": "Scheduling quarterly pulmonology visits for all patients enrolled in the asthma program."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Evidence consistently shows that providing patients with a personalized written asthma action plan and teaching them to use peak flow self-monitoring are the most effective interventions for reducing asthma exacerbations, ED visits, and hospitalizations. Telephone calls for medication review are helpful adjuncts but are less impactful than self-monitoring skill-building. Mailing written plans without education does not ensure patients understand how to use them during an exacerbation. Quarterly specialist visits are resource-intensive and have not demonstrated superior impact over self-management tools alone."}, {"id": 73, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A health plan audits inpatient claims after discharge and determines that two days of a five-day hospitalization did not meet criteria for inpatient level of care. What type of utilization review does this describe?", "options": {"A": "Prospective review, conducted before services begin to determine medical necessity.", "B": "Concurrent review, conducted during hospitalization to monitor ongoing necessity.", "C": "Expedited review, conducted within 72 hours when urgent care circumstances exist.", "D": "Retrospective review, conducted after services have already been provided and billed."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Retrospective review occurs after services have been provided and billed and is used to evaluate whether the level of care billed was medically necessary throughout the stay. Prospective review occurs before services begin. Concurrent review takes place during the hospitalization to authorize continued days. Expedited review is an urgent appeals process available when a patient faces immediate risk from a coverage delay. Understanding these distinct review types is fundamental to the case manager's utilization management role."}, {"id": 74, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A hospitalized patient cannot afford post-discharge medications and has missed prescriptions in the past due to cost. Which action best demonstrates the case manager's patient advocacy role?", "options": {"A": "Investigate patient assistance programs, 340B drug pricing, and generic alternatives to reduce cost.", "B": "Document the patient's non-adherence history and inform the attending physician of the pattern.", "C": "Refer the patient to social work and defer all medication access planning to their department.", "D": "Advise the patient to prioritize the most important medications and skip others if needed."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Case managers advocate for patients by identifying and directly addressing practical barriers to care adherence, including medication affordability. Investigating manufacturer assistance programs, 340B pricing, and generic alternatives is an active advocacy intervention that removes the financial barrier. Documenting non-adherence as a behavioral pattern mischaracterizes a systemic access barrier as patient failure. Deferring entirely to social work without engaging in the solution underutilizes the case manager's role. Advising the patient to skip medications is clinically unsafe and abandons the advocacy obligation."}, {"id": 75, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager completes a comprehensive care plan for a patient with multiple chronic conditions. Which element is most essential in the care plan to support effective continuity across multiple providers?", "options": {"A": "A detailed description of the patient's insurance coverage and current benefit limitations.", "B": "Identified patient goals, barriers, planned interventions, and expected timeframes per problem.", "C": "A complete list of every provider the patient has seen during the previous five years.", "D": "Documentation of all medications the patient has been prescribed since the initial diagnosis."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A care plan that documents patient goals, barriers, planned interventions, and expected timeframes gives all providers a shared framework for coordinated care across settings. Insurance details are administrative information, not clinical coordination tools that guide day-to-day care decisions. A five-year provider history is overly extensive and does not guide active care management. A comprehensive historical medication list does not communicate the current active plan; only the current reconciled medication list serves that coordination function."}, {"id": 76, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A hospitalist case manager identifies a patient whose length of stay has exceeded the expected DRG by two days due to delayed surgical scheduling. What is the most appropriate action for the case manager to take?", "options": {"A": "Request that the payer extend the number of authorized hospital days for the delay.", "B": "Discharge the patient to a lower-level facility as soon as possible regardless of clinical status.", "C": "Identify the root cause of the scheduling delay and work with the care team to resolve it.", "D": "Document the extended stay in the chart and await the next available surgical date passively."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Identifying and removing the root cause of a length-of-stay delay is the case manager's primary responsibility in LOS management. Simply requesting more authorized days treats the symptom without resolving the bottleneck. Discharging a patient who is not yet ready creates patient safety risks and transfers the problem rather than solving it. Passively documenting the delay without taking action to resolve it fails to fulfill the case manager's proactive utilization management role."}, {"id": 77, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A health system places a registered nurse case manager inside a primary care clinic to work alongside the physician team in the same physical space. This care delivery model is best described as which type of case management?", "options": {"A": "Telephonic case management, where the case manager contacts patients remotely by phone.", "B": "Disease management, where the case manager focuses exclusively on one chronic condition at a time.", "C": "Health plan case management, coordinating care on behalf of the insurance company payer.", "D": "Embedded or integrated case management, with the case manager co-located in the clinical team."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "An embedded or integrated case management model places the case manager within the clinical setting alongside the care team, enabling face-to-face patient engagement and real-time, in-person care coordination. Telephonic case management is conducted remotely via telephone. Disease management programs address specific chronic conditions rather than comprehensive whole-person coordination. Health plan case management is employed by payers and operates external to provider settings, typically by telephone or secure messaging."}, {"id": 78, "domain": "care_management", "question": "The CCMC defines case management as a collaborative process that assesses, plans, implements, coordinates, monitors, and evaluates options and services. What is the primary stated purpose of this process according to the CCMC definition?", "options": {"A": "To meet an individual's health needs while promoting quality and cost-effective outcomes.", "B": "To reduce hospital readmissions and improve the organization's financial performance.", "C": "To monitor patients for adherence to physician-ordered treatment plans and medications.", "D": "To coordinate benefits and authorize services on behalf of payers and insurance companies."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The CCMC defines the primary purpose of case management as meeting individual health needs while promoting quality outcomes and cost-effective use of resources, reflecting a dual focus on the individual patient and the broader healthcare system. Reducing readmissions and improving financial performance are important outcomes but are not the CCMC's stated primary purpose. Compliance monitoring frames case management as punitive rather than collaborative. Authorizing services on behalf of payers describes utilization management, not the full scope of professional case management."}, {"id": 79, "domain": "care_management", "question": "Before discharging a patient with heart failure, the hospital case manager calls the patient's primary care office and speaks directly with the clinic nurse to transfer clinical information and coordinate the first follow-up appointment. This action is an example of which care transition best practice?", "options": {"A": "Concurrent review confirming coverage for the post-discharge follow-up office visit.", "B": "A warm handoff transferring clinical information and accountability to the next provider.", "C": "A prior authorization request confirming the patient's coverage for the follow-up visit.", "D": "A discharge summary documenting the patient's hospital course for the medical record."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A warm handoff is a direct, real-time communication between the discharging provider and the receiving provider that transfers clinical information and shared accountability for the patient's ongoing care. It is distinct from a cold handoff, which relies solely on written documentation sent without direct conversation. Concurrent review involves payer communication, not provider-to-provider clinical transfer. Prior authorization is a payer function. A discharge summary is a written document, not a verbal real-time handoff."}, {"id": 80, "domain": "care_management", "question": "The case manager is convening an interdisciplinary team meeting for a patient with cancer, diabetes, and depression. Which team member's participation is most critical to address this patient's psychosocial needs during the meeting?", "options": {"A": "The oncologist, who is leading the patient's primary cancer treatment and medical plan.", "B": "The diabetes educator, who manages the patient's blood glucose self-monitoring goals.", "C": "The social worker, who assesses support systems and connects the patient to community resources.", "D": "The pharmacist, who reviews the patient's complex multi-drug regimen for interactions."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Social workers are specifically trained to assess psychosocial needs, family and support systems, emotional coping, and community resource connections, making their participation most critical for addressing the psychosocial dimension of care. The oncologist addresses the medical dimension. The diabetes educator focuses on glycemic self-management. The pharmacist addresses medication safety. While all team members contribute to comprehensive care, the social worker is the most appropriate lead for psychosocial assessment and resource linkage."}, {"id": 81, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A health plan case manager has attempted to contact a newly identified high-risk member three times by phone and twice by letter over two weeks without a response. What is the best next step?", "options": {"A": "Close the case and remove the member from the high-risk panel permanently.", "B": "Escalate the case to the medical director as a potential patient abandonment situation.", "C": "Send a certified letter requiring the member to respond within 30 days or lose coverage.", "D": "Document all contact attempts and try alternative methods such as email or text outreach."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When initial contact attempts are unsuccessful, the standard practice is to document all attempts and try alternative contact methods before closing the case, as the member may have unmet needs and barriers to responding. Closing the case after limited attempts abandons a high-risk member and does not reflect best practice. Escalating to the medical director is premature before alternative outreach options are exhausted. Requiring members to respond under threat of losing coverage is coercive and is not a standard case management practice."}, {"id": 82, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager has a caseload of 85 active patients and receives three new referrals at the start of the week. Which patient should receive the highest priority for initial contact and comprehensive assessment?", "options": {"A": "A patient discharged 48 hours ago after a heart failure hospitalization with no follow-up arranged.", "B": "A patient with well-controlled hypertension who missed a blood pressure check last month.", "C": "A stable diabetic patient who called to ask about a new diet program she recently read about.", "D": "A newly diagnosed asthma patient who just completed a specialist visit with a new action plan."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A heart failure patient discharged 48 hours ago without follow-up arranged represents the most urgent case management need because the first 72 hours after heart failure discharge are the highest-risk period for readmission and decompensation. Stable hypertension without acute changes is a lower-priority, routine follow-up need. A patient seeking information about a diet program has an educational need that is not urgent. The newly diagnosed asthma patient who just completed a specialist visit with an action plan has her immediate medical needs met."}, {"id": 83, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager is working with an elderly patient who lives alone, has limited income, and cannot prepare her own meals due to severe arthritis. Which community program referral most directly addresses her nutritional needs?", "options": {"A": "A hospice program offering palliative nutritional support to qualifying terminal patients.", "B": "The Meals on Wheels program, which delivers prepared meals to homebound older adults.", "C": "A community food pantry providing non-perishable grocery items for eligible individuals.", "D": "A senior living facility with a communal dining room available to community members."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Meals on Wheels is the most appropriate referral because it delivers prepared, nutritious meals directly to homebound older adults who are unable to prepare food independently due to functional limitations. Hospice is appropriate only for terminal patients nearing end of life, which does not describe this patient. A food pantry requires the ability to travel and prepare food, which her arthritis prevents. A senior living facility is a residential placement that is a far larger intervention than what this patient's nutritional need requires."}, {"id": 84, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A health plan implements a telephonic disease management program for members with Type 2 diabetes. Which outcome measure best evaluates the clinical effectiveness of this program at six months?", "options": {"A": "The number of member calls completed per disease management nurse per week.", "B": "The percentage of enrolled members who rate the telephonic program as satisfactory.", "C": "The proportion of enrolled members with HbA1c less than 8% at six-month reassessment.", "D": "The total cost of the telephonic program per member per month compared to the budget."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "HbA1c reduction is the primary clinical outcome measure for a diabetes disease management program because it directly reflects glycemic control achieved by the intervention. Call volume measures nurse productivity, not clinical impact on patient health. Member satisfaction measures patient experience but not clinical effectiveness. Cost per member per month measures financial efficiency but not whether the clinical program is actually improving diabetes control. Evaluating clinical programs requires clinical outcome metrics."}, {"id": 85, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A 58-year-old patient with sepsis has been in the ICU for 12 days, remains ventilator-dependent with multiple organ involvement, but shows gradual clinical improvement. Which post-acute placement is most appropriate for this patient?", "options": {"A": "Inpatient rehabilitation facility for intensive daily therapy targeting ventilator weaning.", "B": "Skilled nursing facility with a ventilator program for sub-acute respiratory management.", "C": "Home health with a private duty nursing agency to manage ventilator care at home.", "D": "Long-term acute care hospital for medically complex patients requiring extended acute care."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Long-term acute care hospitals are designed for patients who need prolonged hospital-level care for complex conditions such as ventilator dependency, wound management, and multi-organ system involvement. IRFs require the ability to participate in at least three hours of active therapy daily, which a ventilator-dependent critically ill patient typically cannot sustain. SNF ventilator units provide sub-acute care for patients who are more medically stable. Home ventilator management is appropriate only after successful weaning to a manageable and stable level."}, {"id": 86, "domain": "care_management", "question": "According to the Chronic Care Model developed by Wagner, effective management of chronic disease requires which fundamental transformation in the delivery of care?", "options": {"A": "A shift from reactive, visit-based care to proactive, planned, and patient-centered care delivery.", "B": "Replacing primary care physicians with specialist teams for management of all chronic diseases.", "C": "Limiting case management resources to patients who demonstrate consistent adherence.", "D": "Focusing all intervention resources exclusively on the highest-cost 5% of the population."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The Chronic Care Model calls for transforming care from a reactive model that responds to acute illness into a proactive model that anticipates patient needs, plans care systematically, and supports ongoing self-management. Replacing primary care with specialists contradicts the CCM's emphasis on integrated primary care teams as the foundation of chronic disease management. Limiting care to adherent patients contradicts the model's equity and support principles. Targeting only the top cost tier applies resource management principles inconsistent with the CCM's population-health focus."}, {"id": 87, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A patient was injured at work and is being case-managed for lumbar disc herniation requiring surgery and rehabilitation. The case manager identifies that the patient also has group health insurance. Which payer is the primary payer for this work-related injury?", "options": {"A": "The patient's group health insurance.", "B": "Workers' compensation.", "C": "Medicare, if the patient is 65 or older and enrolled in Medicare coverage.", "D": "Both payers share responsibility equally under standard coordination of benefits rules."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Workers' compensation is always the primary payer for injuries and illnesses that arise out of and in the course of employment, regardless of other insurance the patient carries. Group health insurance is secondary and may cover expenses not paid by workers' compensation. Medicare is not primary for work-related injuries when workers' compensation coverage is available, per Medicare Secondary Payer rules. Workers' compensation and group health do not share costs equally; workers' compensation pays first as the liable payer."}, {"id": 88, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager documents a patient contact using the SOAP note format. Which section of the SOAP note contains the case manager's professional analysis and clinical judgment about the patient's status and response to the care plan?", "options": {"A": "The subjective section, which captures what the patient reports about current symptoms and concerns.", "B": "The objective section, which records measurable data such as vital signs and test results.", "C": "The assessment section, which reflects the case manager's professional analysis of all findings.", "D": "The plan section, which outlines the next interventions and follow-up actions to be taken."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The assessment component of a SOAP note is where the clinician or case manager documents their professional interpretation, synthesis, and judgment about the subjective and objective findings. The subjective section captures the patient's own report of symptoms, concerns, and history. The objective section records observable, measurable clinical data. The plan section documents what actions will be taken next. Clear SOAP documentation is essential for professional communication and defensible medical record standards."}, {"id": 89, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A case manager using the Transtheoretical Model is working with a patient who says, 'I have been thinking about quitting smoking for a while, but I haven't made any concrete plans yet.' This patient is most likely in which stage of change?", "options": {"A": "Precontemplation, where the patient is not yet considering making a behavior change.", "B": "Action, where the patient is actively implementing steps to change the target behavior.", "C": "Preparation, where the patient is making concrete plans to begin behavior change soon.", "D": "Contemplation, where the patient is thinking about change but has not committed to a plan."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Contemplation is characterized by awareness of a problem and consideration of change without a specific action plan or commitment, which matches this patient's statement. Precontemplation is when the patient is unaware of the need to change or is not considering it at all. Action involves actively implementing the behavior change itself. Preparation involves concrete planning with an intended action date within 30 days. Correctly identifying the stage allows the case manager to apply stage-appropriate motivational interventions."}, {"id": 90, "domain": "care_management", "question": "A hospital implements the Project RED (Re-Engineered Discharge) bundle to reduce 30-day readmission rates. Which element is a core component of the Project RED discharge intervention?", "options": {"A": "Scheduling all high-risk patients for a day-three post-discharge telehealth visit.", "B": "Requiring payers to authorize an extended 48-hour observation stay for high-risk patients.", "C": "Assigning a dedicated hospitalist to contact all discharged patients within one week.", "D": "Reconciling medications and providing a written discharge plan with scheduled follow-up appointments."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Project RED (Re-Engineered Discharge) includes medication reconciliation, a personalized written discharge plan, scheduled follow-up appointments, and a post-discharge telephone reinforcement call as core components. Day-three telehealth visits are not a standard RED component. RED is a hospital-based protocol, not a payer authorization requirement. RED does not require dedicating a hospitalist specifically to post-discharge calls; the reinforcement call is typically made by a nurse or case manager within 72 hours of discharge."}, {"id": 91, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A recently widowed woman tells the case manager, 'I know my husband is gone, but sometimes I catch myself cooking dinner for two and calling his name when I get home.' Which stage of Kubler-Ross's grief model does this behavior most likely reflect?", "options": {"A": "Denial, where the bereaved person has difficulty accepting the reality of the loss.", "B": "Bargaining, where the bereaved person attempts to negotiate to reverse the loss.", "C": "Anger, where the bereaved person feels rage or resentment toward self or others.", "D": "Depression, where the bereaved person experiences deep sadness and social withdrawal."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Denial in grief involves difficulty accepting the reality of loss, often manifested through unconscious behaviors that assume the deceased is still present, such as cooking for them or calling their name. Bargaining involves negotiating or making promises in exchange for reversing the loss. Anger is characterized by resentment or rage directed at self, others, or the deceased. Depression involves persistent sadness and withdrawal from daily activities. These stages do not occur in a fixed sequence."}, {"id": 92, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager asks a patient, 'On a scale of 0 to 10, how important is it to you to control your blood pressure, and what made you give it that number?' This technique is an example of which motivational interviewing component?", "options": {"A": "Affirmation, explicitly recognizing and validating the patient's strengths and past efforts.", "B": "Open-ended questioning to explore the patient's values, priorities, and motivation for change.", "C": "Reflective listening, restating the patient's words to deepen understanding of ambivalence.", "D": "Summarizing, consolidating key conversation themes to transition toward next steps."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Asking an open-ended question using an importance ruler is a classic motivational interviewing technique that invites the patient to articulate her own motivation and values in her own words. Affirmation involves explicitly recognizing and validating patient strengths. Reflective listening involves paraphrasing or mirroring the emotional content of what the patient said. Summarizing involves pulling together key themes from the conversation to consolidate progress. Open-ended questioning forms the foundation of the OARS approach."}, {"id": 93, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "During a case management assessment, a long-term smoker states, 'Smoking is part of who I am. I've tried quitting before and it never sticks, so I'm not interested in trying again.' This patient is in which stage of the Transtheoretical Model?", "options": {"A": "Contemplation, where the patient is considering change but has not made specific plans.", "B": "Relapse, where the patient previously made a change but returned to the prior behavior.", "C": "Precontemplation, where the patient is not yet considering or open to behavior change.", "D": "Maintenance, where the patient has sustained a behavior change for six months or longer."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Precontemplation is characterized by the patient not recognizing the need for change or explicitly stating she is not interested in changing, which matches this patient's statement perfectly. Contemplation involves awareness of the problem and some consideration of change. Relapse describes returning to a behavior after a sustained period of change. Maintenance involves sustaining a new behavior for six or more months. Stage-appropriate interventions for precontemplation focus on raising awareness rather than action planning."}, {"id": 94, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager visits the home of an elderly patient with advanced dementia. The patient's daughter, the sole caregiver, reports she has had no days off in eight months, sleeps poorly, and has stopped seeing her own physician. Which tool is most appropriate to assess the caregiver's level of burden?", "options": {"A": "The PHQ-9, which screens for the severity of depressive symptoms in adult patients.", "B": "The GAD-7, which assesses the frequency and severity of generalized anxiety symptoms.", "C": "The Mini-Mental State Examination to assess the caregiver's cognitive function and status.", "D": "The Zarit Burden Interview, designed to measure subjective burden experienced by caregivers."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The Zarit Burden Interview is a validated tool specifically designed to measure the physical, emotional, social, and financial burden experienced by family caregivers of patients with dementia and other chronic illnesses. The PHQ-9 screens for depression severity in patients and can serve as a secondary screen. The GAD-7 assesses anxiety symptoms specifically. The MMSE assesses cognitive function rather than caregiver burden. The Zarit Burden Interview is the gold standard for caregiver burden assessment in case management practice."}, {"id": 95, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "During an initial case management assessment, a patient reports drinking six or more standard drinks daily and states he has tried to cut down twice without success. Using the SBIRT model, which intervention level is most appropriate for this patient?", "options": {"A": "Referral to treatment.", "B": "Brief intervention only, to provide targeted feedback about his current drinking level.", "C": "Screening only, as this assessment alone constitutes the full recommended approach.", "D": "Watchful waiting, to allow the patient to reduce his drinking independently over time."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The SBIRT model directs referral to treatment for patients who screen positive for moderate-to-severe substance use disorder, which this patient demonstrates through daily heavy drinking and two failed attempts to cut down. Brief intervention is appropriate for hazardous or at-risk drinkers who have not developed a disorder. Screening alone is insufficient when a disorder has been identified. Watchful waiting is not a component of the SBIRT framework when a substance use disorder is clearly present."}, {"id": 96, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is working with a Somali refugee patient who declines mental health counseling, stating that discussing emotional problems with a stranger is not acceptable in her community. Which response by the case manager is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Inform the patient that accepting mental health services is required for continued case management.", "B": "Explore culturally acceptable forms of support and ask about trusted community or faith leaders.", "C": "Document the patient's refusal and note that no further mental health outreach will be attempted.", "D": "Refer the patient immediately to a mental health professional from the same cultural background."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Cultural humility requires exploring what forms of support the patient finds acceptable within her own cultural framework, such as community elders, faith leaders, or informal networks, rather than insisting on a Western model of mental health counseling. Making mental health acceptance a condition of case management is coercive and unethical. Documenting refusal without exploration abandons the patient without seeking alternatives. Referring to a same-culture provider may be appropriate eventually but skips the essential exploration step."}, {"id": 97, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager screens a patient with congestive heart failure using the PHQ-9 and obtains a score of 16. According to PHQ-9 scoring, this result falls in which severity range and warrants which level of clinical follow-up?", "options": {"A": "Mild depression, suggesting watchful waiting with rescreening in three months.", "B": "Moderate depression, warranting counseling referral at the patient's own discretion.", "C": "Moderately severe depression, warranting active treatment planning with clinical follow-up.", "D": "Minimal symptoms, requiring no further mental health assessment at this time."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A PHQ-9 score of 16 falls in the moderately severe depression range (scores 15-19), which warrants active treatment planning including medication evaluation, psychotherapy referral, and close clinical follow-up. Mild depression corresponds to scores of 5-9, warranting watchful waiting. Moderate depression (10-14) warrants counseling referral. Minimal symptoms correspond to scores below 5 and require no immediate action. Depression significantly complicates chronic disease management and must be addressed to improve overall health outcomes."}, {"id": 98, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "During a home visit, a case manager observes multiple unexplained bruises on an elderly patient's arms and torso. The patient becomes anxious when asked about them, stating his son provides all his personal care. The case manager suspects physical abuse. What is the case manager's legal obligation?", "options": {"A": "Confront the son directly and document his explanation in the chart for clinical review.", "B": "Contact the patient's physician to request a physical examination to document the injuries.", "C": "Ask the patient's permission before making any report, since he is a competent adult.", "D": "Report suspected abuse to Adult Protective Services as required by mandatory reporting law."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Case managers are mandatory reporters in most states, legally required to report suspected elder abuse to Adult Protective Services without waiting for confirmation or patient consent. Confronting the suspected abuser may place the patient at greater risk and is not the appropriate first step. Physician examination is important but does not replace the required mandatory report. Mandatory reporting laws supersede individual consent requirements to protect vulnerable adults from harm, even when the patient is a competent adult."}, {"id": 99, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager uses the CAGE questionnaire to screen a patient for alcohol use disorder and the patient answers 'yes' to two of the four CAGE questions. How should the case manager interpret a score of two or more on the CAGE?", "options": {"A": "A score of two or more is a positive screen suggesting possible alcohol use disorder requiring further assessment.", "B": "A score of two or more is inconclusive and should be repeated in six months using a different tool.", "C": "A score of two or more rules out alcohol use disorder and indicates controlled social drinking.", "D": "A score of two or more only indicates a problem if the patient also reports drinking daily."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A CAGE score of two or more is considered a positive screen for possible alcohol use disorder, warranting further clinical assessment to determine diagnosis and appropriate intervention level. The CAGE is a rapid screening tool, not a diagnostic instrument, so a positive screen requires follow-up evaluation but is not itself a diagnosis. A score of two or more does not rule out a disorder; higher scores increase the likelihood of a clinically significant problem. Daily drinking is not required to screen positive on the CAGE."}, {"id": 100, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "During a motivational interviewing session, a patient with obesity says, 'I really do want to feel healthier, and I know losing weight would help my knees and my energy.' The case manager recognizes this statement as an example of which motivational interviewing concept?", "options": {"A": "Resistance, where the patient is pushing back against the case manager's suggestions.", "B": "Change talk, where the patient expresses motivation or desire to make a behavior change.", "C": "Sustain talk, where the patient argues for reasons to maintain the current behavior.", "D": "Ambivalence, where the patient simultaneously holds motivation for and against change."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Change talk consists of statements in which the patient expresses desire, ability, reason, or need to change, and this patient's statement clearly expresses desire for better health and recognition of the benefits of change. Resistance involves the patient pushing back against or disagreeing with the practitioner's direction. Sustain talk consists of statements favoring maintaining the current behavior unchanged. Ambivalence refers to holding both motivations and barriers simultaneously, whereas this statement reflects only the motivation side of the equation."}, {"id": 101, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager learns that a patient with chronic pain, substance use disorder, and frequent ED visits has a significant childhood trauma history. Which approach best reflects trauma-informed care when working with this patient?", "options": {"A": "Avoid discussing the patient's trauma history entirely to prevent re-traumatization during sessions.", "B": "Require the patient to address trauma in therapy as a prerequisite for case management engagement.", "C": "Create a safe, predictable, and transparent environment that does not require trauma disclosure.", "D": "Focus case management exclusively on the substance use disorder and pain management goals."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Trauma-informed care creates a safe, predictable, and transparent care environment that does not require patients to disclose trauma to receive services, while recognizing that trauma may underlie the presenting clinical concerns. Avoiding any mention of trauma is not trauma-informed care; sensitivity to triggers differs from avoiding the topic entirely if the patient initiates. Requiring trauma therapy as a prerequisite creates an unnecessary barrier to case management engagement. Focusing only on substance use and pain ignores the trauma context shaping both presentations."}, {"id": 102, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A 74-year-old patient recently moved to a new city after retirement and reports having no close friends or family nearby and feeling completely disconnected from her community. Which health risk is most directly and consistently associated with chronic social isolation in older adults?", "options": {"A": "Increased likelihood of developing Type 2 diabetes due to reduced physical activity levels.", "B": "Higher rates of medication non-adherence due to the absence of caregiver supervision.", "C": "Greater susceptibility to respiratory infections due to a reduced immune response.", "D": "Increased risk of cognitive decline, depression, and premature mortality."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Research consistently links chronic social isolation in older adults to increased risk of cognitive decline, depression, and premature mortality, with effects on health comparable to smoking 15 cigarettes daily. While physical inactivity may accompany isolation, Type 2 diabetes is not the primary direct risk documented in the literature. Medication non-adherence may occur but is not the most established direct health risk of social isolation. Respiratory infection susceptibility, while affected by general health, is not the primary risk specifically attributed to social isolation."}, {"id": 103, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager follows up with a patient 18 months after her husband's death. The patient reports she cannot accept he is truly gone, has withdrawn completely from family and friends, and is unable to return to any previous life activities. Which condition best describes what this patient is experiencing?", "options": {"A": "Complicated grief, characterized by prolonged functional impairment and inability to accept the loss.", "B": "Major depressive disorder requiring antidepressant medication and immediate psychiatric evaluation.", "C": "Normal grief, since everyone processes loss differently and there is no standard timeline for grief.", "D": "Adjustment disorder with depressed mood related to a single identifiable psychosocial stressor."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Complicated grief (prolonged grief disorder) is characterized by intense grief persisting beyond 12 months with functional impairment, inability to accept the loss, and withdrawal from life activities. It is distinct from normal grief, which, while painful, generally allows for gradual return to function over time. Major depressive disorder may co-occur but complicated grief is a distinct condition requiring specific clinical intervention. Adjustment disorder typically resolves within six months of the stressor and does not apply to this prolonged and profoundly impairing presentation."}, {"id": 104, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient with schizophrenia on oral antipsychotics has been hospitalized twice this year due to medication non-adherence. The case manager and psychiatrist are discussing strategies to improve adherence. Which intervention has the strongest evidence for reducing rehospitalization in patients with schizophrenia who struggle with oral adherence?", "options": {"A": "Increasing the frequency of outpatient psychiatric appointments to weekly monitoring visits.", "B": "Transitioning the patient to a long-acting injectable antipsychotic medication formulation.", "C": "Providing the patient with daily medication reminders through a smartphone application.", "D": "Enlisting a family member to directly supervise the patient's daily oral medication administration."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Long-acting injectable antipsychotic medications eliminate the daily adherence decision and are associated with significantly lower rates of rehospitalization compared to oral formulations in patients with documented non-adherence. Increasing appointment frequency improves monitoring but does not prevent adherence gaps between visits. Smartphone reminders rely on patient engagement with technology and have modest evidence in severe mental illness populations. Family supervision may create conflict and is not consistently available or sustainable across all patients and family situations."}, {"id": 105, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager discovers that a patient with Type 2 diabetes often runs out of food before month's end and eats infrequently due to financial constraints. Which intervention most directly addresses this barrier to diabetes management?", "options": {"A": "Prescribe a low-carbohydrate diet plan.", "B": "Reduce the patient's insulin dose to lower the risk of hypoglycemia from inconsistent meals.", "C": "Connect the patient with a local food pantry.", "D": "Educate the patient about the importance of eating consistently at regular daily meal intervals."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Connecting the patient with food assistance resources directly addresses the social determinant causing inconsistent food access and supports safer, more stable diabetes management. Prescribing a dietary plan the patient cannot afford or access perpetuates the barrier without removing it. Insulin dose reduction should be a physician-directed clinical decision based on data, not a case management workaround for a food access problem. Educating about meal consistency is not actionable when the underlying problem is food insecurity, not knowledge."}, {"id": 106, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient calls the case manager and says, 'I don't see any point in going on. I have been thinking about ending my life,' and the case manager determines the patient has a specific plan. What is the most appropriate immediate action?", "options": {"A": "Ask the patient to call a family member for support and monitor his situation over 24 hours.", "B": "Advise the patient to schedule an urgent appointment with his psychiatrist within 48 hours.", "C": "Document the patient's statement and flag it for the clinical supervisor at the next team meeting.", "D": "Activate emergency services or direct the patient to the nearest emergency department immediately."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A patient who expresses suicidal ideation with a specific plan requires immediate emergency intervention to ensure his physical safety. Activating emergency services or directing the patient to the ED provides the immediate psychiatric evaluation and safety measures this level of risk requires. Asking the patient to call a family member does not ensure immediate safety in an active crisis with a specific plan. A 48-hour psychiatry appointment is insufficient for active suicidal ideation with a method. Documenting without acting immediately fails the patient at a critical moment."}, {"id": 107, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is educating a patient with heart failure about daily weight monitoring and fluid restriction. To confirm the patient's understanding before ending the education session, the most effective technique is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Ask the patient to explain in her own words how she will monitor weight and respond to changes.", "B": "Have the patient read the written discharge instructions aloud.", "C": "Ask the patient if she has any remaining questions and provide a phone number to call.", "D": "Provide the patient with a printed daily monitoring checklist of heart failure tasks to take home."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The teach-back method, in which the patient explains the information back in her own words, is the most effective technique for confirming comprehension and identifying gaps in understanding before discharge. Having the patient read instructions aloud confirms literacy but not comprehension of the content. Asking if the patient has questions relies on her knowing what she does not understand, which is an unreliable method for identifying gaps. Providing a printed checklist is a useful reinforcement tool but does not confirm comprehension during the current encounter."}, {"id": 108, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is working with a patient recovering from alcohol use disorder. The patient's wife frequently calls to share observations about his drinking without his knowledge and asks the case manager to share treatment details. Which response by the case manager is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Share relevant details with the wife since her observations are clinically valuable for care planning.", "B": "Explain that patient confidentiality prevents sharing information without the patient's written consent.", "C": "Ask the wife to document her observations in writing and submit them to the care team directly.", "D": "Encourage the wife to continue providing updates as a form of supportive monitoring for the patient."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Patient confidentiality requires that the case manager not share protected health information with the patient's spouse without explicit written consent, regardless of the wife's intentions or the potential clinical value of her observations. Sharing clinical information without consent violates HIPAA and professional ethical standards. Asking the wife to submit written observations bypasses the consent requirement without resolving it. Encouraging continued unauthorized reporting perpetuates a confidentiality violation and may damage the therapeutic alliance with the patient."}, {"id": 109, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager assesses a patient who frequently cancels appointments, appears anxious during home visits, and has had multiple unexplained injuries over six months. The case manager wants to screen for intimate partner violence. Which approach is most appropriate for initiating this screening?", "options": {"A": "Ask the patient's partner to step out and then ask the partner to describe how the injuries occurred.", "B": "Inform the patient you are required to report suspected domestic violence and will be doing so today.", "C": "Ask the patient directly in a private, non-judgmental way whether she has felt unsafe at home.", "D": "Document your observations and wait for the patient to disclose abuse voluntarily on her own terms."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Directly and privately asking the patient about her safety at home in a non-judgmental manner is the recommended evidence-based screening approach for intimate partner violence. Asking the partner to describe the injuries reverses the power dynamic and may endanger the patient. Adult domestic violence mandatory reporting laws vary by state and are not universal; announcing a report before assessing the situation may increase the patient's risk. Waiting for unsolicited disclosure means many abused patients are never identified or offered support."}, {"id": 110, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient recently diagnosed with multiple sclerosis says, 'I've been reading everything I can find about MS and joined an online support group to connect with others who have it.' This patient is using which type of coping strategy?", "options": {"A": "Avoidant coping, where the patient focuses on activities to distract from the diagnosis.", "B": "Emotion-focused coping, aimed at managing the emotional distress caused by the diagnosis.", "C": "Denial, where the patient engages in information-seeking to delay accepting the diagnosis.", "D": "Problem-focused coping, directed at gaining knowledge and connecting with relevant resources."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Problem-focused coping involves taking active, practical steps to understand and manage the stressor, such as researching the illness and joining peer support networks, which is exactly what this patient demonstrates. Avoidant coping involves activities that sidestep the stressor rather than engaging with it. Emotion-focused coping addresses the emotional response to the stressor rather than the problem itself. While information-seeking could theoretically co-exist with some denial, actively researching and connecting with support reflects adaptive, problem-focused engagement."}, {"id": 111, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A terminally ill patient who says he is not religious tells the case manager, 'I keep wondering if I've done enough good in my life.' The case manager wants to address his spiritual dimension of care. Which response is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Ask the patient to share more about what living a meaningful life has meant to him.", "B": "Offer to contact the hospital chaplain to provide religious counseling and spiritual support.", "C": "Reassure the patient that many people feel this way at end of life and that it will pass.", "D": "Document the patient's concerns and refer to the palliative care team for further follow-up."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Asking an open, exploratory question invites the patient to articulate his own values and sources of meaning, which is the core of spiritually sensitive case management that does not impose a religious framework. Offering a chaplain assumes the patient wants religious support, which he explicitly said he does not seek. Dismissive reassurance that the feelings will pass does not honor the patient's genuine existential concern. Documentation and referral alone without first engaging the patient's concern in the moment fails to address his immediate need."}, {"id": 112, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A family of a patient given a three-to-six-month prognosis due to advanced heart failure describes the patient's daughter crying daily and unable to stop thinking about life after her father dies even though he is still alive. Which psychosocial process is this family member experiencing?", "options": {"A": "Pathological grief requiring immediate psychiatric evaluation and medication management.", "B": "Anticipatory grief, which is a normal response to an expected and impending loss.", "C": "Complicated grief, characterized by functional impairment lasting more than 12 months after loss.", "D": "Depression triggered by caregiving stress rather than grief related to the anticipated death."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Anticipatory grief is the process of mourning a loss before it occurs, which is a normal and adaptive response when facing an impending death. It involves many of the same emotions as bereavement, including sadness and preoccupation with the loss, but occurs before the actual death. Complicated grief is diagnosed after the death and is characterized by prolonged impairment beyond 12 months. While caregiver stress may co-exist, the daughter's statements specifically reference grief about the anticipated loss rather than caregiver burnout."}, {"id": 113, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient who has survived a serious illness, job loss, and divorce in the past two years continues to engage with care, reports purposeful daily activities, and maintains a positive outlook. Which concept best describes this patient's adaptive capacity in the face of adversity?", "options": {"A": "Posttraumatic stress, the psychological impact of multiple simultaneous adverse life events.", "B": "Emotional repression, where the patient avoids processing difficult emotions to maintain function.", "C": "Resilience, the ability to adapt positively and recover function following significant adversity.", "D": "Denial, a temporary coping mechanism preventing full awareness of loss and ongoing trauma."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Resilience is the capacity to adapt positively and maintain or recover function in the face of significant adversity, which this patient demonstrates through continued engagement and positive outlook despite major stressors. Posttraumatic stress involves intrusive symptoms and functional impairment following trauma. Emotional repression involves consciously or unconsciously suppressing emotions, which is not indicated by this patient's engaged, purposeful behavior. Denial involves not acknowledging reality, whereas this patient has clearly faced and adapted to real adversity."}, {"id": 114, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient with severe mental illness is being discharged from an inpatient psychiatric unit and needs ongoing comprehensive community-based support. Which community resource best provides psychiatric rehabilitation, medication management, and community integration for patients with severe mental illness?", "options": {"A": "An outpatient therapist providing individual cognitive-behavioral therapy on a weekly basis.", "B": "A crisis stabilization unit for patients experiencing acute psychiatric decompensation.", "C": "An intensive outpatient program for substance use disorder and co-occurring mental health needs.", "D": "An Assertive Community Treatment team providing intensive mobile community-based support."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Assertive Community Treatment (ACT) provides comprehensive, community-based psychiatric care including medication management, therapy, housing support, and vocational assistance through a multidisciplinary team that brings services directly to the patient. It is specifically designed for individuals with severe mental illness who struggle with traditional outpatient engagement. Weekly outpatient therapy alone is insufficient for patients requiring comprehensive support. Crisis stabilization units address acute episodes. IOPs serve different acuity levels and are focused primarily on substance use or mild-to-moderate mental health needs."}, {"id": 115, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient with poorly controlled asthma is repeatedly hospitalized. During a comprehensive assessment, the case manager discovers the patient lives in an apartment with mold and cockroach infestations. Which intervention most directly addresses the environmental contributor to his asthma exacerbations?", "options": {"A": "Assist the patient in contacting the housing authority and documenting conditions for a formal complaint.", "B": "Educate the patient on proper inhaler technique and adherence to controller medication regimen.", "C": "Increase the frequency of follow-up calls to monitor symptom patterns and medication use.", "D": "Refer the patient to a pulmonologist for escalation of his current asthma medication regimen."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Mold and cockroach allergens are documented environmental triggers for asthma, and the most direct intervention is addressing living conditions by helping the patient report habitability violations to the housing authority. Inhaler education and adherence are important but do not remove the environmental trigger causing repeated hospitalizations. Monitoring calls do not reduce the patient's allergen exposure in the home. Medication escalation does not address the root cause when the primary driver of exacerbations is the patient's housing environment."}, {"id": 116, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient who repeatedly misses appointments, does not fill prescriptions, and says, 'My doctor takes care of all that. I just show up when he tells me to,' most reflects which level of patient activation using the PAM framework?", "options": {"A": "Level 3, where the patient is actively taking some action toward self-management goals.", "B": "Level 1, where the patient does not yet believe self-management is her own role.", "C": "Level 4, where the patient maintains self-management behaviors consistently under all conditions.", "D": "Level 2, where the patient has some knowledge but lacks confidence to act independently."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Level 1 of the Patient Activation Measure describes patients who believe the physician is solely responsible for health decisions and do not yet see self-management as their own role, which precisely aligns with this patient's statement. Level 3 patients are actively engaged in self-management efforts toward personal goals. Level 4 patients sustain self-management consistently even during adversity and illness. Level 2 patients understand their role but lack the confidence or skills to act on it. Recognizing Level 1 activation guides the case manager to build awareness before any action planning."}, {"id": 117, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is working with a patient with opioid use disorder who requests help initiating medication-assisted treatment. Which medication is FDA-approved and considered evidence-based first-line pharmacotherapy for opioid use disorder?", "options": {"A": "Naltrexone in oral form taken daily, which fully blocks opioid receptors to eliminate cravings.", "B": "Clonidine administered during acute withdrawal to manage opioid detoxification symptoms only.", "C": "Buprenorphine-naloxone, a partial agonist formulation that reduces cravings and withdrawal symptoms.", "D": "Methadone administered exclusively in a federally certified opioid treatment program setting."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Buprenorphine-naloxone (Suboxone) is FDA-approved, evidence-based, and can be prescribed in office-based settings by certified providers, making it the most accessible first-line treatment for opioid use disorder. Naltrexone blocks opioid receptors and is evidence-based but is not a first-line agent during initiation because it requires full opioid clearance first. Clonidine manages withdrawal symptoms but is not a treatment for opioid use disorder itself. Methadone is effective but is restricted to certified opioid treatment programs, significantly limiting patient access."}, {"id": 118, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "During a case management assessment, the case manager wants to evaluate the full breadth of the patient's social support network. Which question most comprehensively assesses the patient's available social support system?", "options": {"A": "Do you live with a family member who can help you with daily activities at home?", "B": "Are you married or do you have a domestic partner involved in your medical care?", "C": "Do your neighbors or coworkers check on you when you have been sick or missed work?", "D": "Who can you count on to help with practical tasks, emotional support, and health needs?"}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "An open-ended question about who can help with practical tasks, emotional support, and health needs captures the full functional breadth of the social support network without assuming a particular relationship type or household arrangement. Asking only about family in the home excludes broader support sources. Asking about marital status does not identify other support systems including friends, neighbors, or community groups. Asking only about neighbors is too narrow and does not capture the patient's full network. A comprehensive social support assessment identifies multiple types of support across varied relationship types."}, {"id": 119, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is working with a 78-year-old patient with multiple chronic conditions who has never completed an advance directive. Which action best describes the case manager's appropriate role in advance care planning?", "options": {"A": "Initiate a conversation about the patient's values and goals and encourage advance directive completion.", "B": "Prepare the advance directive document and have the patient sign it at the next appointment.", "C": "Notify the patient's physician that advance care planning is legally required for all elderly patients.", "D": "Refer the patient to an attorney to complete a legally binding advance directive document."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The case manager's role in advance care planning is to initiate values-based conversations, provide education about advance directives, and encourage the patient to document her preferences and appoint a healthcare proxy. Case managers do not prepare or complete legal documents on behalf of patients. Advance care planning is a recommended best practice, not a legal requirement for elderly patients. An attorney may be needed for complex documents but is not required for a standard healthcare advance directive, and the case manager's role is to facilitate the conversation, not provide legal services."}, {"id": 120, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient with depression has suicidal ideation without a specific plan. The psychiatric team asks the case manager to work with the patient on a safety plan before a follow-up appointment tomorrow. Which element is most essential to an effective safety plan?", "options": {"A": "A signed no-suicide contract stating the patient will not attempt suicide before the next appointment.", "B": "A personalized list of warning signs, coping strategies, and crisis contacts for when distress escalates.", "C": "A written acknowledgment that the patient has been informed of the risks of leaving treatment early.", "D": "A schedule of daily activities designed to keep the patient engaged and prevent idle unstructured time."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "An effective safety plan includes personalized warning signs, coping strategies the patient can use independently, trusted social contacts, crisis resources, and a plan for accessing emergency help, giving the patient a concrete roadmap for managing escalating distress. Safety contracts are not evidence-based and create false reassurance without addressing the underlying risk factors. Informed consent acknowledgments are administrative documents, not safety interventions. Daily activity schedules alone do not address the cognitive and emotional escalation processes that lead to suicidal crisis."}, {"id": 121, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient with generalized anxiety disorder and COPD cannot distinguish her anxiety symptoms from her breathing symptoms and frequently goes to the ED. Which case management approach best addresses the interaction between her anxiety and COPD?", "options": {"A": "Advise the patient to visit the ED whenever she is uncertain whether symptoms are respiratory or anxiety.", "B": "Refer the patient exclusively to a psychiatrist to treat anxiety as the only underlying cause.", "C": "Coordinate care between the pulmonologist and a behavioral health provider to address both conditions.", "D": "Teach the patient to use a peak flow meter and respond to readings to replace anxiety-driven ED visits."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Coordinating care between the pulmonologist and a behavioral health provider addresses the complex interaction between anxiety and COPD, where each condition can exacerbate the other and where both require integrated clinical management. Advising ED visits for uncertainty perpetuates high-cost care without resolving the underlying diagnostic confusion. Referring exclusively to psychiatry ignores the respiratory component driving symptom overlap. Teaching peak flow monitoring is helpful but insufficient without also addressing the anxiety component driving symptom confusion and ED utilization."}, {"id": 122, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager completing a comprehensive psychosocial assessment for a newly enrolled patient wants to ensure the assessment is thorough and meets biopsychosocial-spiritual standards. Which domains should be included?", "options": {"A": "Medical history, current medications, insurance coverage, and appointment compliance patterns.", "B": "Psychiatric diagnosis, substance use history, mental health treatment records, and hospitalizations.", "C": "Employment status, income level, housing type, and transportation access only.", "D": "Mental health, substance use, social support, spirituality, functional status, and social determinants."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A comprehensive biopsychosocial-spiritual assessment encompasses mental health status, substance use, social support systems, spiritual or existential concerns, functional status, and social determinants of health. Medical history and insurance data are important administrative components but do not constitute a psychosocial assessment. A psychiatric history alone is too narrow for a comprehensive assessment. SDOH screening alone omits the psychological, social support, and spiritual dimensions. The full biopsychosocial-spiritual framework is the recognized standard for comprehensive case management assessment."}, {"id": 123, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager using motivational enhancement is working with a patient ambivalent about starting a cardiac exercise program. Which technique best helps the patient resolve ambivalence in favor of behavior change?", "options": {"A": "Exploring the benefits of changing and the costs of staying the same from the patient's own perspective.", "B": "Presenting a detailed exercise prescription developed by the cardiac rehabilitation team.", "C": "Sharing statistics about the cardiovascular benefits of regular exercise in similar patient populations.", "D": "Setting a specific exercise goal with the patient and scheduling a follow-up call for accountability."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Decisional balance exploration, in which the patient examines the pros and cons of changing and not changing from her own perspective, is an evidence-based motivational enhancement technique for resolving ambivalence. Presenting an exercise prescription assumes readiness to change that has not been established. Sharing statistics shifts focus to external data rather than the patient's own values, which drive sustained behavior change. Goal-setting and accountability are appropriate after ambivalence is resolved, not during the ambivalence stage itself."}, {"id": 124, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is working with a veteran who reports nightmares about combat, avoids busy public places, is hypervigilant in all environments, and is having difficulty in his family relationships. Which condition do these symptoms most likely indicate?", "options": {"A": "Adjustment disorder with mixed emotional and conduct disturbance related to returning from deployment.", "B": "Posttraumatic stress disorder, characterized by re-experiencing, avoidance, and hyperarousal symptoms.", "C": "Major depressive disorder with seasonal pattern related to environmental and routine changes.", "D": "Generalized anxiety disorder triggered by life transitions and stressors following military service."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "PTSD is characterized by re-experiencing the trauma (nightmares), avoidance of trauma reminders (busy places), and hyperarousal (hypervigilance), which precisely match this veteran's presentation. Adjustment disorder involves emotional or behavioral symptoms in response to a stressor but does not include the re-experiencing and hyperarousal cluster specific to PTSD. Major depressive disorder does not account for the re-experiencing and avoidance features described. Generalized anxiety involves persistent worry but not the trauma-specific re-experiencing cluster this veteran demonstrates."}, {"id": 125, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient with diabetes misses approximately 40% of her primary care appointments. Assessment reveals she has no car, lives 15 miles from the clinic, and cannot afford ride-share services. Which intervention most directly removes this barrier to care?", "options": {"A": "Advise the patient to reschedule appointments to times when a family member can drive her.", "B": "Switch the patient's care to a closer clinic even if it requires changing her established provider.", "C": "Connect the patient with Medicaid non-emergency medical transportation or available transportation benefits.", "D": "Transition the patient permanently to telehealth visits since she cannot reliably attend in person."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Non-emergency medical transportation (NEMT) is a benefit available through Medicaid to help eligible patients reach medical appointments, and connecting the patient with this benefit directly addresses the root transportation barrier. Relying on family members is not a reliable structural solution and does not address the underlying access problem. Changing clinics introduces a new provider relationship without solving the transportation problem if the new location remains inaccessible. Telehealth alone may not be appropriate for all visits requiring physical examination or laboratory work."}, {"id": 126, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A family reports that their 8-year-old son has become clingy, regressed to bedwetting, and refuses to go to school since his mother died of cancer two months ago. The case manager recognizes these behaviors as which type of response in children following significant loss?", "options": {"A": "Conduct disorder triggered by unresolved anger at the loss of his primary attachment figure.", "B": "Childhood depression requiring immediate evaluation for antidepressant medication.", "C": "Posttraumatic stress disorder secondary to witnessing the mother's prolonged illness and death.", "D": "Normal grief responses in children, who often express grief through behavioral regression."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Children frequently express grief through behavioral regression, clinginess, school refusal, and physical symptoms such as bedwetting, which are developmentally normal responses to loss of a primary caregiver. Conduct disorder involves a persistent pattern of rule-violating behavior beyond grief-related regression. Childhood depression is possible but should be assessed after first recognizing that the described behaviors are within the range of normal childhood grief responses at two months. PTSD requires the specific re-experiencing and hyperarousal symptom cluster, which is not described here."}, {"id": 127, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is designing patient education for patients newly diagnosed with heart failure. Which educational content has the strongest evidence for reducing heart failure-related hospitalizations when taught effectively?", "options": {"A": "Daily weight monitoring with a specific action plan for weight gains of two or more pounds.", "B": "Detailed explanation of heart failure pathophysiology and ejection fraction measurement methods.", "C": "A comprehensive medication list with pharmacological properties of each prescribed drug class.", "D": "Nutritional content of common foods and a calorie-counting diary for tracking daily intake."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Teaching patients to monitor their daily weight and follow a specific action plan when weight increases by two or more pounds (indicating fluid retention) has the strongest evidence for reducing heart failure hospitalizations and is the core self-management skill for this population. Understanding pathophysiology is educational but does not drive self-management behavior independently. Detailed pharmacology is beyond the scope of patient education and does not improve outcomes at the patient level. Calorie counting is not the primary concern in heart failure; sodium and fluid restriction are the directly relevant dietary interventions."}, {"id": 128, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient who needs a mental health referral refuses, saying, 'People who go to therapy are weak. I can handle this myself.' Which initial approach by the case manager is most likely to reduce this patient's resistance to mental health care?", "options": {"A": "Inform the patient that untreated depression will significantly worsen his chronic medical conditions.", "B": "Explore the patient's beliefs about therapy non-judgmentally and acknowledge his perspective.", "C": "Ask the patient's family members to encourage him to accept the mental health referral.", "D": "Document the refusal and wait for the patient to independently request mental health services."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Exploring the patient's beliefs about therapy in a non-judgmental way directly addresses the stigma, builds rapport, and opens space for the patient to reconsider without feeling coerced. Warning about consequences is confrontational and may increase resistance rather than invite reconsideration. Enlisting family members may feel like pressure and bypasses the patient's autonomy. Documenting and waiting abandons the patient and may allow an untreated condition to worsen. Motivational interviewing principles call for exploring and rolling with resistance as the first therapeutic step."}, {"id": 129, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager discovers a patient with hypertension is non-adherent with her antihypertensive medication because she believes, based on a family member's experience, that the medication will damage her kidneys. Which category of adherence barrier does this represent?", "options": {"A": "Structural barrier, related to medication access, cost, or availability in the community.", "B": "Cognitive barrier, related to low health literacy or inability to understand medical instructions.", "C": "Belief-based barrier, where inaccurate health beliefs conflict with recommended treatment.", "D": "Motivational barrier, where the patient understands the need but does not prioritize treatment."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A belief-based adherence barrier exists when inaccurate or culturally influenced beliefs about a medication lead to non-adherence, which is exactly what this patient demonstrates. Structural barriers involve medication access, cost, or pharmacy availability. Cognitive barriers involve literacy or comprehension limitations that prevent the patient from understanding instructions. Motivational barriers involve understanding the need but deprioritizing the treatment. Addressing belief-based barriers requires respectfully exploring and correcting the inaccuracy using patient education and shared decision-making."}, {"id": 130, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is caring for a patient in her final weeks of life who expresses that her greatest fear is dying alone. Which response by the case manager is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Reassure the patient that modern hospice ensures no patient ever dies alone under professional care.", "B": "Refer the patient to the hospital chaplain to address her existential fear of dying alone.", "C": "Document the patient's fear in the chart and alert the hospice nurse at the next team meeting.", "D": "Explore the patient's wishes for companionship at end of life."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Exploring the patient's wishes about companionship at end of life and working with family to create a presence plan honors her autonomy and directly addresses her expressed fear. Reassuring her that hospice ensures she will never die alone makes a promise that cannot always be kept and dismisses the emotional reality of her concern. A chaplain referral addresses spiritual matters but not the practical desire for family presence. Documentation without immediate action delays addressing a time-sensitive, deeply personal end-of-life need."}, {"id": 131, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is working with a Spanish-speaking patient who does not speak English. The patient's adult son offers to serve as the interpreter for the case management appointment. The most appropriate response by the case manager is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Arrange for a qualified medical interpreter instead, as using family members poses clinical and legal risks.", "B": "Allow the son to interpret since he is fluent in both Spanish and English and is readily available.", "C": "Conduct the appointment in English and ask the son to translate key points to his mother afterward.", "D": "Reschedule the appointment for a time when a bilingual staff member is available in the office."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Using a qualified medical interpreter is the legally and ethically appropriate standard under Title VI of the Civil Rights Act and professional case management standards. Family members may omit sensitive information, mistranslate technical terms, or create conflicts when private clinical information about the patient is present. Conducting the appointment in English entirely excludes the patient from her own care. Rescheduling because a bilingual staff member is unavailable unnecessarily delays care when qualified interpreter services can be arranged through the facility or telephone interpretation."}, {"id": 132, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is prioritizing interventions for a patient who is homeless, has untreated schizophrenia, and has no food security. Using Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs as a framework, which need should the case manager address first?", "options": {"A": "Self-actualization needs related to finding personal meaning and purpose in daily life.", "B": "Physiological needs including food, shelter, and immediate physical safety.", "C": "Esteem needs related to the patient's sense of dignity and self-worth in the community.", "D": "Belonging needs including social connectedness and integration into a support community."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs places physiological needs at the foundation, meaning food, shelter, and safety must be addressed before higher-level needs can be meaningfully pursued. A homeless patient without food security cannot effectively engage with mental health treatment, social belonging, or self-actualization until basic survival needs are met. Self-actualization is the highest level of the hierarchy. Esteem and belonging needs are important but are higher-order needs that require the foundation of physiological and safety needs to be established first."}, {"id": 133, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is working with a patient with Bipolar I Disorder who reports several days of needing very little sleep, spending excessively, and developing grandiose plans to start multiple businesses simultaneously. Which phase of bipolar disorder do these symptoms most likely indicate?", "options": {"A": "Major depressive episode, characterized by persistent low mood.", "B": "Mixed state, where features of both depression and mania occur simultaneously over several days.", "C": "Manic episode, characterized by elevated mood, decreased need for sleep, and impulsive behavior.", "D": "Hypomanic episode, a less severe form of mania that does not cause marked functional impairment."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A manic episode in Bipolar I Disorder is characterized by elevated or expansive mood, markedly decreased need for sleep, grandiosity, and impulsive behavior such as excessive spending, which precisely matches this patient's presentation. A major depressive episode presents with low mood, fatigue, and loss of interest. A mixed state involves simultaneous manic and depressive features. A hypomanic episode is less severe and does not cause marked impairment; the patient's grandiose business plans and excessive spending suggest a full manic episode with impairment."}, {"id": 134, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager assessing a patient with multiple substance use relapses wants to identify factors that support the patient's long-term recovery. Which of the following is an evidence-based protective factor associated with improved substance use disorder recovery outcomes?", "options": {"A": "History of early-onset substance use beginning before age 15 years.", "B": "Co-occurring untreated depression and generalized anxiety disorder.", "C": "Limited social support network and recent loss of employment.", "D": "Strong family support, stable housing, and engagement in a recovery community."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Strong family support, stable housing, and engagement with a recovery community such as AA, NA, or peer support programs are evidence-based protective factors consistently associated with improved substance use disorder recovery outcomes. Early-onset substance use is a risk factor, not a protective factor, associated with more severe disorder. Co-occurring untreated mental illness increases relapse risk significantly. Limited social support and unemployment are risk factors associated with worse recovery outcomes. Identifying protective factors guides strengths-based case management planning."}, {"id": 135, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is assessing suicide risk in a patient who has disclosed passive suicidal ideation. Which single factor most significantly elevates the patient's risk level above low to moderate?", "options": {"A": "A previous suicide attempt, which is the strongest individual predictor of future suicide risk.", "B": "Family history of depression, indicating a possible genetic predisposition to suicidal behavior.", "C": "Recent job loss, a situational stressor that temporarily increases emotional distress.", "D": "Age over 65, which is associated with increased vulnerability but is not the strongest single predictor."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A prior suicide attempt is the single most powerful predictor of future suicide risk and significantly elevates risk classification above low or moderate in all recognized suicide risk frameworks. Family history of depression is a risk factor but is a distal and indirect predictor. Recent job loss is a significant situational stressor but is a less specific predictor than prior attempt history. Age over 65 is associated with increased risk, particularly in men, but is not the strongest single predictor compared to a documented prior attempt."}, {"id": 136, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is coordinating care for a patient with both Type 2 diabetes and major depression who struggles to manage either condition effectively. Research most consistently shows that addressing which condition first leads to better outcomes for both conditions?", "options": {"A": "Diabetes management.", "B": "Depression.", "C": "Both conditions simultaneously using a fully integrated care management approach from the start.", "D": "Neither condition until the patient demonstrates readiness and motivation to engage with both programs."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Evidence consistently shows that treating depression in patients with co-occurring chronic disease leads to meaningful improvements in self-management behaviors, adherence, and clinical outcomes for both conditions. This is the basis for integrating behavioral health into chronic disease management programs. While integrated care is ideal, the evidence specifically highlights that depression treatment is the lever that unlocks better chronic disease self-management. Waiting for readiness before initiating either treatment delays care for a clinically urgent mental health condition affecting multiple dimensions of health."}, {"id": 137, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager assessing an older adult's ability to live independently conducts a functional assessment. Which assessment tool most specifically evaluates the patient's ability to perform instrumental activities of daily living?", "options": {"A": "The Katz Index of Activities of Daily Living, measuring basic self-care such as bathing and dressing.", "B": "The Mini-Mental State Examination, measuring cognitive function across multiple domains.", "C": "The Lawton IADL Scale, measuring complex activities such as managing finances and using transportation.", "D": "The Barthel Index, assessing functional independence in feeding, mobility, and basic self-care."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The Lawton IADL Scale is specifically designed to assess instrumental activities of daily living, including complex tasks such as managing medications, handling finances, cooking, housekeeping, and using transportation, which are critical indicators of community-living capacity. The Katz Index measures basic ADLs such as bathing, dressing, and toileting. The MMSE assesses cognitive function rather than functional independence. The Barthel Index measures basic ADL performance in mobility and self-care. IADLs are key to determining whether a patient can safely live independently in the community."}, {"id": 138, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is working with a patient in recovery from alcohol use disorder who is preparing to attend a colleague's retirement party where alcohol will be served. Which relapse prevention strategy is most appropriate to discuss before the event?", "options": {"A": "Advise the patient to avoid all social situations where alcohol might be present indefinitely.", "B": "Tell the patient it is safe to have one drink at the event and practice moderation strategies.", "C": "Suggest the patient take a dose of naltrexone before attending to reduce alcohol cravings.", "D": "Help the patient identify an exit strategy and plan responses to offers of alcohol at the event."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Planning an exit strategy and preparing specific responses to offers of alcohol is a core relapse prevention skill that allows the patient to participate in social life while managing recovery challenges. Permanent social avoidance is unrealistic, socially isolating, and not aligned with recovery principles. Suggesting moderation is contraindicated for alcohol use disorder; abstinence is the evidence-based standard goal. Recommending naltrexone dosing is a medical decision that should not be made unilaterally by the case manager without physician direction."}, {"id": 139, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager wants to begin an advance care planning conversation with a 68-year-old patient with COPD who has never discussed his end-of-life preferences. Which opening question best initiates this conversation in a patient-centered way?", "options": {"A": "Have you ever thought about what kind of care would be most important to you if you became very ill?", "B": "I need you to complete a do-not-resuscitate form before your next hospitalization if possible.", "C": "Studies show that most patients with COPD eventually require ventilator support at end of life.", "D": "Your family will need to make decisions for you if you cannot speak for yourself in the future."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "An open-ended question inviting the patient to reflect on his own values and preferences is the most patient-centered way to open an advance care planning conversation. Immediately presenting a DNR form is premature and directive before any exploration of the patient's values and wishes. Citing statistical outcomes can feel alarming and may not reflect the patient's individual prognosis. Focusing on family decision-making skips the patient's own preferences and may feel coercive. The goal of advance care planning is to elicit, honor, and document what matters most to the patient."}, {"id": 140, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient with health anxiety frequently believes that a headache signals a brain tumor and that fatigue means an undiagnosed serious illness. Which therapeutic approach best addresses these maladaptive catastrophic thought patterns?", "options": {"A": "Psychodynamic therapy exploring the unconscious childhood origins of the patient's health fears.", "B": "Cognitive-behavioral therapy targeting identification and restructuring of catastrophic thoughts.", "C": "Acceptance and commitment therapy focusing on accepting health uncertainty without reassurance-seeking.", "D": "Medication management with an SSRI to address the neurobiological substrate of health anxiety."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) directly targets catastrophic thinking patterns by helping patients identify automatic negative thoughts, examine evidence for and against them, and develop more balanced cognitive responses. It has the strongest evidence base for health anxiety. Psychodynamic therapy explores underlying relational patterns but does not directly target cognitive distortions. Acceptance and commitment therapy takes a different approach of accepting uncertainty rather than directly restructuring distorted thoughts. SSRIs may be helpful adjuncts but do not address the cognitive patterns themselves."}, {"id": 141, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is developing a support program for patients newly diagnosed with Type 2 diabetes. Research on group-based diabetes support programs shows which primary benefit compared to individual education alone?", "options": {"A": "Group education eliminates the need for individual case management follow-up after the program.", "B": "Group programs are more cost-effective and therefore always preferable to individual education.", "C": "Peer support in group settings improves self-management behaviors and reduces social isolation.", "D": "Group formats ensure all patients receive identical information, reducing variation in clinical outcomes."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Peer support in group settings provides patients with role models, shared experiences, and social accountability that improve self-management behaviors and reduce the social isolation that often accompanies chronic illness. Group education does not eliminate the need for individual follow-up; complex patients still require individualized case management. Cost-effectiveness is a consideration but should not override patient preference or clinical appropriateness. Providing identical information to all group members ignores the individual needs and learning styles better addressed through personalized education."}, {"id": 142, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager provides bereavement follow-up six weeks after the death of a hospice patient. The patient's spouse says, 'I know people expect me to be doing better by now, but I miss him every day and I cry almost every night.' Which response by the case manager is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Many people do feel better within a few weeks. Let's look at whether therapy might speed your healing.", "B": "Crying every night at six weeks might be a sign of complicated grief requiring a psychiatry referral.", "C": "You should try to stay busy and get out more. Activity is the best way to move through grief.", "D": "Grief takes as long as it takes. What you are experiencing six weeks after your husband's death is completely normal."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Normalizing the grief experience and validating that six weeks is far too soon to expect resolution is the most appropriate and therapeutic response. Suggesting most people feel better within weeks imposes an artificial timeline and invalidates the spouse's lived experience. Diagnosing complicated grief at six weeks is premature; complicated grief is generally not diagnosed until 12 or more months after bereavement with persistent functional impairment. Advising the bereaved person to stay busy is dismissive and avoids genuine emotional engagement with the reality of their grief."}, {"id": 143, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager notices that a patient with bipolar disorder frequently describes herself as 'my own worst enemy' and expresses shame about her diagnosis when interacting with providers. This self-perception most accurately reflects which psychosocial concept?", "options": {"A": "Internalized stigma, where the patient has absorbed and applied negative societal beliefs about her diagnosis.", "B": "Poor insight, where the patient lacks awareness of her diagnosis and its real impact on daily functioning.", "C": "Learned helplessness, where the patient believes her outcomes are entirely outside her own control.", "D": "Identity fusion, where the patient has entirely merged her personal identity with her mental illness."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Internalized stigma, also called self-stigma, occurs when individuals with mental illness absorb and apply negative societal stereotypes to themselves, resulting in shame, reduced self-esteem, and reluctance to seek or remain in care. Poor insight involves lack of awareness of the illness, not shame about it. Learned helplessness involves the belief that actions cannot affect outcomes. Identity fusion is not a standard clinical or case management concept. Addressing internalized stigma requires validation, strengths-based framing, and peer support to rebuild self-worth."}, {"id": 144, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient in recovery from serious mental illness wants to connect with others who understand his experience from the inside. Which community resource is most aligned with the principles of the recovery model and peer-delivered support?", "options": {"A": "An inpatient psychiatric rehabilitation unit for patients requiring extended symptom stabilization.", "B": "A certified peer specialist or peer support group led by individuals with lived mental health experience.", "C": "A therapist-led psychoeducation group focused on medication adherence and symptom monitoring.", "D": "An Assertive Community Treatment team providing intensive community-based clinical support services."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Certified peer specialists and peer-led support groups are grounded in the recovery model's principles of hope, self-determination, and mutual support, and are specifically designed to leverage shared lived experience in a way no professional can replicate. They are the most aligned resource for a patient seeking connection with others who truly understand his experience. Inpatient rehabilitation addresses acute clinical needs. Psychoeducation groups are therapist-led and clinically focused, not peer-centered. ACT provides intensive clinical services, not the peer support connection this patient is seeking."}, {"id": 145, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager asks a patient to consider reducing his alcohol intake and the patient responds, 'I only drink a few beers after work to relax. That's normal. You're making a big deal out of nothing.' The best response using the motivational interviewing principle of rolling with resistance is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Let me share some information about how your current drinking level compares to safe use guidelines.", "B": "Your physician flagged this as a concern, which is why I brought it up at today's appointment.", "C": "It sounds like winding down after work is really important to you. What else helps you relax?", "D": "I understand you feel that way, but your liver function tests suggest your drinking may be causing damage."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Rolling with resistance involves acknowledging the patient's perspective without arguing or confronting, then gently redirecting toward exploration of values. Acknowledging his need to unwind and asking about other relaxation strategies invites engagement without escalating resistance. Sharing data is informational and may increase defensiveness. Citing physician authority may feel dismissive of the patient's autonomy. Referencing liver function tests is confrontational and may cause the patient to disengage, as this contradicts the motivational interviewing approach of avoiding argumentation."}, {"id": 146, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A 78-year-old patient who recently lost his driving privileges, has reduced mobility, and is no longer able to live as independently as before tells the case manager he feels 'useless and invisible.' Which psychosocial issue is this patient most likely experiencing?", "options": {"A": "Major depressive disorder requiring antidepressant medication and weekly psychotherapy sessions.", "B": "Adjustment disorder with depressed mood directly related to the loss of driving privileges alone.", "C": "Cognitive decline causing the patient to misinterpret his social role and physical abilities.", "D": "Role loss and grief related to the transition from an active, independent identity to dependency."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Role loss and grief related to major life transitions such as retirement, loss of driving, and reduced independence are common and expected psychosocial challenges in older adults that affect identity and self-worth. This does not necessarily indicate a clinical disorder and should first be understood as a normal response to significant role transition. Major depressive disorder is possible but should not be assumed without further assessment meeting full diagnostic criteria. Attributing the concern to one lost privilege oversimplifies a multifactorial transition. Cognitive decline is not suggested by the patient's articulate self-reflection."}, {"id": 147, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager is developing a care plan for a 72-year-old patient with a terminal diagnosis who explicitly prioritizes quality of life over longevity in all future treatment decisions. Which care planning decision best reflects this patient's stated values?", "options": {"A": "Focus on comfort-focused interventions, symptom management, and activities that provide meaning.", "B": "Enroll the patient in the highest-intensity clinical trial available for his terminal diagnosis.", "C": "Encourage the patient to reconsider his values since curative treatment may extend his survival.", "D": "Document his stated values but proceed with the oncologist's aggressive treatment recommendation."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When a patient explicitly prioritizes quality of life over longevity, the care plan should center on comfort, symptom management, and meaningful activities, which directly honors his stated values and reflects patient-centered case management. Enrolling in an intensive clinical trial contradicts his quality-of-life priority. Encouraging the patient to reconsider his values is paternalistic and undermines his autonomy, which is a core ethical principle. Proceeding with aggressive treatment despite stated values ignores self-determination and the CCMC's patient-centered care planning standard."}, {"id": 148, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A case manager has confirmed that a patient is experiencing domestic violence and is not yet ready to leave the relationship, saying, 'I know I should leave but I'm not ready.' Which intervention is most appropriate at this point in the case management relationship?", "options": {"A": "Inform the patient that staying in the relationship removes the case manager's ability to help further.", "B": "Provide a safety plan including emergency contacts, important documents to gather, and a safe place to go.", "C": "Contact law enforcement to report the domestic violence as a mandatory obligation in all states.", "D": "Refer the patient immediately to a domestic violence shelter and encourage her to go right away."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When a patient is not yet ready to leave an abusive relationship, safety planning empowers the patient with concrete steps she can take to protect herself when she is ready or if danger escalates suddenly. Removing support because of the patient's decision is coercive and abandons a vulnerable patient at a critical moment. Domestic violence mandatory reporting laws for adult victims vary significantly by state and are not universal; a blanket report without exploring the patient's wishes may increase danger. Pressuring immediate shelter referral before the patient is ready may cause disengagement from all services."}, {"id": 149, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A patient with chronic schizophrenia is being discharged from a psychiatric hospitalization. To reduce the risk of early readmission, which discharge planning element has the strongest evidence base for psychiatric patients?", "options": {"A": "Providing a written list of crisis hotline numbers and local emergency resources at discharge.", "B": "Completing a peer wellness recovery plan during the hospitalization for the patient to carry home.", "C": "Arranging a follow-up appointment within seven days and ensuring the patient has medication supply.", "D": "Scheduling a telehealth check-in within 30 days following discharge from the inpatient unit."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A follow-up appointment within seven days of psychiatric discharge combined with ensuring the patient has adequate medication supply are the two interventions with the strongest evidence for reducing psychiatric readmission. This is a quality standard supported by CMS and the Joint Commission. A list of crisis hotlines is insufficient without a structured appointment. Wellness plans are useful adjuncts but secondary to ensuring concrete, scheduled follow-up care. A 30-day telehealth check-in is too delayed to intervene in the highest-risk early post-discharge period for psychiatric patients."}, {"id": 150, "domain": "psychosocial_concepts_and_support_systems", "question": "A 61-year-old woman caring for her husband with ALS for two years reports neglecting her own health appointments because she cannot leave him alone. The case manager wants to address caregiver self-care. Which intervention is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Explain to the caregiver that her own health must come first and encourage her to prioritize herself.", "B": "Assess whether the patient with ALS qualifies for nursing home placement to provide caregiver relief.", "C": "Refer the caregiver to a support group and document that self-care education was completed.", "D": "Coordinate respite care services to allow the caregiver time for her own medical appointments."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Coordinating respite care directly removes the practical barrier preventing the caregiver from attending her own health appointments by providing safe, temporary coverage for her husband. Simply telling the caregiver to prioritize herself does not remove the structural barrier. Nursing home placement is a major decision that should be the caregiver's own choice and is not appropriate as a case management-initiated intervention for this situation. Referring to a support group and documenting self-care education alone does not resolve the specific practical barrier of being unable to leave the patient unattended."}, {"id": 151, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A patient with full decision-making capacity refuses a blood transfusion recommended by the surgeon, citing deeply held religious beliefs. The surgeon insists the patient will die without the transfusion. What is the case manager's most appropriate action?", "options": {"A": "Advocate for the patient's right to refuse treatment and document the patient's informed refusal.", "B": "Support the surgeon's plan and encourage the patient to reconsider for his own safety.", "C": "Arrange an emergency ethics committee consultation to override the patient's religious refusal.", "D": "Contact the patient's family and ask them to persuade the patient to accept the transfusion."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A competent patient has the absolute right to refuse any medical treatment, including life-sustaining treatment, based on personal or religious beliefs, and the case manager's ethical obligation is to advocate for the patient's autonomy and ensure the refusal is informed and documented. Supporting the physician's plan against the patient's wishes undermines the principle of self-determination. An ethics committee cannot override a competent patient's refusal. Enlisting family to pressure the patient circumvents his autonomous decision-making and may constitute coercion."}, {"id": 152, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A patient's employer contacts the case manager requesting information about the patient's diagnosis, treatment plan, and prognosis to determine future job duties. Which response by the case manager is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Share general health information with the employer since the employer finances the patient's insurance.", "B": "Decline to share any health information without the patient's specific written authorization.", "C": "Provide a summary limited to functional limitations directly relevant to current work duties.", "D": "Refer the employer to the patient's physician, who can share information directly with the employer."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "HIPAA prohibits sharing protected health information with any third party, including an employer, without the patient's specific written authorization, regardless of who finances the health coverage. Sharing general health information without authorization still constitutes a HIPAA violation. Functional limitation summaries may be appropriate in workers' compensation contexts but still require patient authorization in general employer inquiries. Referring the employer to the physician does not resolve the authorization requirement and may also result in unauthorized disclosure."}, {"id": 153, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is asked by a supervisor to approve an extended hospital stay for a patient who clearly meets discharge criteria, in order to maximize insurance reimbursement for the facility. Which ethical principle does this request most directly violate?", "options": {"A": "Beneficence, the obligation to act in the patient's best interest at all times in care management.", "B": "Autonomy, the patient's right to make informed decisions about her own care and treatment.", "C": "Justice, requiring fair and equitable allocation of healthcare resources without waste or misuse.", "D": "Nonmaleficence, the obligation to avoid exposing patients to unnecessary harm or risk."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Extending a hospital stay beyond medical necessity to maximize reimbursement constitutes misuse of healthcare resources, violating the principle of justice, which requires equitable and appropriate allocation of limited healthcare resources. Nonmaleficence is also relevant since unnecessary hospitalization exposes patients to iatrogenic risks, but the request is primarily a resource allocation and institutional integrity issue. Beneficence supports doing what is in the patient's best interest. Autonomy governs patient decision-making rather than the institutional policy being described here."}, {"id": 154, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A patient discloses to her case manager that she has a specific plan to harm a named coworker and intends to carry it out this week. Which legal doctrine most directly governs the case manager's obligation in this situation?", "options": {"A": "HIPAA privacy rule, requiring the case manager to protect all patient health disclosures.", "B": "The principle of nonmaleficence, obligating the case manager to avoid causing harm to patients.", "C": "The doctrine of informed consent, requiring disclosure to the patient before any action is taken.", "D": "The Tarasoff duty to warn, requiring notification to the identifiable intended victim and authorities."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The Tarasoff duty to warn requires healthcare providers to take steps to protect an identifiable intended victim when a patient makes a credible, specific threat of harm to that person, and this duty can override HIPAA confidentiality protections when a serious imminent threat exists. HIPAA explicitly permits disclosures necessary to prevent a serious and imminent threat to a person. Nonmaleficence applies to clinical care decisions. Informed consent is unrelated to mandatory warning obligations that arise from a specific credible threat to an identifiable third party."}, {"id": 155, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A researcher with IRB approval contacts a case manager requesting access to the case records of her entire caseload for a readmission study. What is the case manager's most appropriate response?", "options": {"A": "Decline to share records until confirming that patient authorization or a HIPAA data sharing agreement exists.", "B": "Share all case records immediately since IRB approval constitutes permission to access patient data.", "C": "Remove patient names and identifiers and share the remaining records with the researcher.", "D": "Share records for patients who are no longer active in the case management program only."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "IRB approval authorizes a research study but does not by itself grant access to individually identifiable patient records without patient authorization or a HIPAA-compliant data sharing agreement or waiver. Sharing records based solely on IRB approval violates HIPAA. De-identifying records may be appropriate but requires following HIPAA Safe Harbor or Expert Determination methods, not simply removing patient names. Inactive patient records carry the same privacy protections as active records and cannot be shared without appropriate authorization or agreement."}, {"id": 156, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A 92-year-old patient with advanced dementia has a POLST form indicating DNR and comfort measures only. When her breathing becomes labored, her son who holds healthcare proxy demands full resuscitation. What is the most appropriate action?", "options": {"A": "Comply with the son's demand since he holds the legal healthcare proxy designation for his mother.", "B": "Honor the POLST form as the patient's own expressed wishes, which take precedence over proxy demands.", "C": "Contact the ethics committee and suspend all care decisions pending their formal recommendation.", "D": "Ask the attending physician to make the final decision and document that the family conflict was reported."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A POLST form represents the patient's own medical orders and is legally binding in most states, and the patient's documented wishes generally take precedence over a healthcare proxy's conflicting demands since the proxy's role is to represent the patient's wishes, not override them. Complying with the son's demand would violate the patient's documented preferences. The ethics committee may be consulted for ongoing conflict but does not supersede the patient's existing legally binding orders. The attending physician provides medical guidance but the POLST form governs the resuscitation decision."}, {"id": 157, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A hospital-based case manager discovers that a colleague has been falsifying concurrent review notes to obtain insurance authorizations for admissions that do not meet medical necessity criteria. The most appropriate action is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Confront the colleague directly and advise her to self-report to the supervisor within 24 hours.", "B": "Ignore the behavior since it benefits patients by obtaining coverage they would otherwise be denied.", "C": "Report the behavior through the organization's compliance reporting process or to a direct supervisor.", "D": "Document personal observations privately and take no action unless the behavior continues for 30 days."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Falsifying medical documentation to obtain insurance authorizations constitutes healthcare fraud, a serious legal and ethical violation that must be reported through the organization's compliance process or to a supervisor or compliance officer. Confronting the colleague directly without reporting may allow the fraud to continue and expose the case manager to liability for failure to act. Ignoring fraud because it seems to benefit patients does not make it legally or ethically acceptable. Delaying reporting allows ongoing fraud and increases both institutional and personal liability."}, {"id": 158, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A Jehovah's Witness patient is brought to the ED unconscious after a motor vehicle accident with no advance directive available and no family present. The patient requires an immediate blood transfusion to survive. What is the most appropriate course of action?", "options": {"A": "Defer treatment until a family member can be reached to consent on the patient's behalf.", "B": "Contact the hospital ethics committee for a formal ruling before proceeding with the transfusion.", "C": "Document the patient's presumed religious objection and provide transfusion-free emergency care only.", "D": "Proceed with the transfusion under the emergency exception to informed consent to save the patient's life."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The emergency exception to informed consent permits providers to render life-saving treatment when the patient lacks capacity and there is no time to locate a surrogate, as the law assumes a reasonable person would consent to life-saving treatment in an emergency. Without a documented advance directive, the patient's religious beliefs cannot be confirmed. Deferring treatment risks preventable death. Ethics committees cannot convene fast enough for immediately life-threatening emergencies. Providing transfusion-free care based on presumed religious beliefs without written documentation may result in a preventable death."}, {"id": 159, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A managed care organization instructs the case manager to deny post-acute rehabilitation services to a patient who clearly meets clinical criteria, citing cost containment goals. The case manager believes the denial is clinically inappropriate. What is the most appropriate first response?", "options": {"A": "Advocate for the patient by initiating the internal appeal process and documenting the clinical rationale.", "B": "Comply with the organization's decision since cost management is a legitimate organizational goal.", "C": "Contact the patient's attorney to initiate litigation against the managed care organization immediately.", "D": "Transfer the patient to a different health plan that will authorize the needed rehabilitation services."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The case manager has an ethical and professional obligation to advocate for the patient when a clinically inappropriate denial occurs, starting with the internal appeal process and documenting the clinical rationale that supports the medical necessity of the denied services. Complying without advocacy violates the case manager's professional obligation to act in the patient's best interest. Contacting an attorney is premature before internal and external appeal processes are exhausted. Transferring to another plan is not within the case manager's authority and does not resolve the immediate denial."}, {"id": 160, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A competent patient asks the case manager to keep her HIV diagnosis from her husband without giving a reason. The case manager's most appropriate response is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Inform the husband because he has a right to know about a communicable disease risk to his own health.", "B": "Respect the patient's confidentiality and do not disclose her diagnosis to her husband.", "C": "Consult the ethics committee to determine whether the husband's safety outweighs the patient's privacy.", "D": "Notify the state health department since HIV is a reportable disease requiring immediate partner notification."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A competent patient's right to medical confidentiality applies even to serious communicable diseases, and the case manager must respect this privacy. Partner notification for HIV in most states is the responsibility of the state health department through legal notification programs, not the case manager or provider. Disclosing to the husband without consent violates HIPAA. Ethics committee consultation is not required for a situation clearly governed by established patient confidentiality law. State health departments conduct partner notification through separate legal processes that do not require the case manager to disclose to the partner directly."}, {"id": 161, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager who is also a licensed registered nurse is asked to administer a medication injection to a patient during a home visit because the home health nurse is unavailable. Which principle most directly governs the case manager's decision about whether to perform this task?", "options": {"A": "Beneficence, since performing the injection directly benefits the patient who needs the medication today.", "B": "Nonmaleficence, since performing the injection could introduce risk of medication error or physical harm.", "C": "Scope of practice, which determines what tasks the case manager may perform in the case manager role.", "D": "Autonomy, since the patient has the right to receive the medication as prescribed by the physician."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Scope of practice determines what actions a case manager may legally and professionally perform in the case manager role, which typically does not include direct clinical interventions such as medication injections. Even if the individual holds a nursing license, performing a clinical task outside the case manager role may create liability and role boundary confusion. Beneficence and nonmaleficence are relevant but secondary to determining whether the task is within scope. The case manager should arrange for appropriate clinical personnel rather than performing clinical tasks outside the defined case management role."}, {"id": 162, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager receives a $200 restaurant gift card from a grateful patient's family after a successful discharge. According to CCMC ethical standards, the case manager's most appropriate action is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Accept the gift since it was given voluntarily after the case management relationship had ended.", "B": "Accept the gift but report it to the supervisor within five business days per organizational policy.", "C": "Donate the gift card to a hospital charity fund and notify the family of the donation decision.", "D": "Decline the gift politely, explaining that accepting gifts from patients could compromise professional objectivity."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "CCMC ethical standards and most healthcare professional codes prohibit accepting gifts from patients or their families because doing so can compromise professional objectivity and create the appearance of a conflict of interest. The timing of the gift after discharge does not make it acceptable. Reporting the gift after accepting it does not resolve the ethical problem. Donating the gift card is a creative workaround but the preferred professional response is to decline and explain the professional reasoning. Declining respectfully models professional boundaries and maintains the integrity of the case management relationship."}, {"id": 163, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A hospital implements a policy requiring case managers to discharge all patients whose LOS exceeds the DRG threshold regardless of clinical status, to improve the facility's financial performance. This policy most directly conflicts with which ethical principle?", "options": {"A": "Nonmaleficence, which requires avoiding harm to patients including through premature clinically unsafe discharge.", "B": "Justice, which requires equitable treatment of all patients regardless of their financial characteristics.", "C": "Beneficence, which requires acting in the patient's best interest even when inconvenient or costly.", "D": "Veracity, which requires case managers to communicate honestly with patients about discharge timing."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Discharging patients who are not clinically ready for discharge based solely on financial criteria exposes patients to harm such as readmission, complications, or injury at a lower level of care, directly violating nonmaleficence. Case managers have a professional and ethical obligation to discharge patients when clinically appropriate, not when financially convenient. Justice addresses equity but is not the primary principle violated here. Beneficence and veracity are also relevant but the most direct violation is nonmaleficence because patient harm is the likely consequence of the policy."}, {"id": 164, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager working for a health insurance plan is reviewing a prior authorization request from a physician she personally knows and considers credible. Which is the case manager's most appropriate action?", "options": {"A": "Approve the prior authorization quickly based on the physician's established credibility and track record.", "B": "Recuse herself from reviewing the case and assign it to a colleague to prevent a conflict of interest.", "C": "Review the request using standard criteria and approve it only if it meets clinical review standards.", "D": "Contact the physician directly about clinical details before completing the formal authorization review."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A personal relationship with the treating physician creates a conflict of interest that could compromise the objectivity of the clinical review, and recusing herself from the case preserves the integrity of the utilization review process. Approving the request based on the personal relationship rather than clinical criteria violates the objectivity required for fair utilization review. Reviewing the request using standard criteria is appropriate practice but does not address the conflict of interest the relationship creates. Consulting the physician outside the formal process may introduce additional bias and further compromises objectivity."}, {"id": 165, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "An 82-year-old patient with early dementia has a healthcare proxy but no living will. When a treatment decision arises, the healthcare proxy disagrees with the patient's previously stated verbal preferences. Which principle best guides decision-making in this situation?", "options": {"A": "The healthcare proxy's decision must be followed since the patient lacks the ability to provide written consent.", "B": "The attending physician has final authority over treatment decisions when there is a proxy-patient conflict.", "C": "The patient's previously expressed preferences should guide the proxy's decision using substituted judgment.", "D": "The ethics committee must be convened to resolve any disagreement between the proxy and the patient."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The standard for surrogate decision-making is substituted judgment, meaning the proxy should make decisions based on what the patient would want given her known values and previously expressed preferences, not on what the proxy personally prefers. The proxy's role is to represent the patient's wishes, not substitute their own. The attending physician provides medical judgment but does not have sole final authority in proxy conflicts. Ethics committee consultation is helpful for unresolved conflicts but is not the first step when the substituted judgment standard can guide the decision."}, {"id": 166, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is offered financial incentives by a home health agency for every post-discharge patient she refers to their agency. Accepting these incentives most directly violates which legal provision?", "options": {"A": "HIPAA privacy rule, which prohibits sharing patient information with any financial incentive involved.", "B": "EMTALA, which requires hospitals to screen and stabilize patients regardless of insurance status.", "C": "The ADA, which prohibits discrimination against patients with disabilities in referral decisions.", "D": "The federal anti-kickback statute, which prohibits financial incentives for healthcare referrals."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The federal anti-kickback statute prohibits offering, paying, soliciting, or receiving anything of value to induce or reward referrals of services covered by federal healthcare programs such as Medicare and Medicaid, and accepting per-referral financial incentives from a home health agency is a textbook violation. HIPAA addresses privacy and data security, not referral incentives. EMTALA governs emergency screening and stabilization requirements. The ADA prohibits discrimination based on disability but does not address financial kickback arrangements between providers and referral sources."}, {"id": 167, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A hospital emergency department refuses to perform a medical screening examination on an uninsured patient presenting with chest pain, citing the patient's inability to pay. This action most directly violates which federal law?", "options": {"A": "EMTALA, which requires hospitals to screen all patients who present to the ED regardless of ability to pay.", "B": "HIPAA, which prohibits discrimination against patients in the delivery of covered healthcare services.", "C": "The ADA, which requires hospitals to provide equal access to services regardless of disability status.", "D": "The False Claims Act, which prohibits fraudulent billing practices in Medicare and Medicaid programs."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "EMTALA requires all Medicare-participating hospitals with emergency departments to provide a medical screening examination to anyone who presents seeking care, regardless of ability to pay, insurance status, or citizenship. Refusing to screen a patient with chest pain due to inability to pay is a clear EMTALA violation. HIPAA governs privacy and data security, not access to emergency care. The ADA prohibits discrimination based on disability, not financial status. The False Claims Act pertains to fraudulent billing practices and is not the primary law violated by this refusal to screen."}, {"id": 168, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager realizes she documented inaccurate information about a patient contact in the medical record. Which is the correct method for handling this documentation error?", "options": {"A": "Delete the entry and retype a corrected version so the record contains only accurate information.", "B": "Draw a single line through the error, write the correct information, then date and initial the correction.", "C": "Add a new entry in the record noting the error without making any changes to the original entry.", "D": "Ask a supervisor to approve the correction before making any changes to the medical record at all."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The legally correct method for correcting a medical record error is to draw a single line through the incorrect information so it remains legible, write the correct information next to it, and then date, time, and initial the correction. Deleting or whiting out an entry destroys the original record and may constitute falsification. Adding only a new entry without correcting the original leaves incorrect information visible and may cause clinical confusion. Supervisory approval may be required per organizational policy but drawing the single-line correction is the universally recognized documentation standard."}, {"id": 169, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is asked to provide a deposition in a lawsuit alleging negligent hospital discharge. Which elements would the plaintiff need to prove to establish professional negligence against the case manager?", "options": {"A": "That the case manager was motivated by financial incentives when recommending the early discharge.", "B": "That the case manager had malicious intent to harm the patient when planning the discharge.", "C": "That the case manager had a duty, breached that duty, and the breach directly caused patient harm.", "D": "That the case manager failed to document the discharge plan in the required institutional format."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Establishing professional negligence requires four elements: duty of care, breach of duty, causation, and damages. The plaintiff must prove the case manager had a professional duty to the patient, the standard of care was violated, the breach caused the harm, and actual damages resulted. Financial motivation and malicious intent are not required elements of negligence, which can be unintentional. Documentation errors may be relevant as evidence of a breach but are not standalone proof of negligence. All four elements must be established simultaneously for a negligence claim to succeed."}, {"id": 170, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager learns that a Medicaid patient is allowing her adult daughter to use her Medicaid card to receive covered medical services. The most appropriate action by the case manager is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Counsel the patient that this is inappropriate but take no further action to avoid damaging the relationship.", "B": "Educate the patient privately about Medicaid eligibility rules and document the education session.", "C": "Contact the daughter directly and explain the legal implications of using a Medicaid card fraudulently.", "D": "Report the suspected Medicaid fraud to the appropriate state Medicaid fraud control unit."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Using a Medicaid card to obtain services for an ineligible person constitutes Medicaid fraud, a federal and state crime, and case managers have an obligation to report suspected fraud to the appropriate authority such as the state Medicaid fraud control unit. Counseling without reporting allows the fraud to continue and may expose the case manager to liability for failure to report. Education alone is insufficient when a crime is actively occurring. Contacting the daughter directly is not the appropriate reporting channel and may not stop the fraudulent activity."}, {"id": 171, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A patient with serious mental illness lacks decision-making capacity, has no advance directive, and has no available family members to serve as surrogate. A critical medical decision must be made urgently. Who in the surrogate decision-making hierarchy is typically authorized to make this decision?", "options": {"A": "The court-appointed guardian, or if none exists, one appointed through a formal legal proceeding.", "B": "The attending physician, who has the authority to make all decisions for incapacitated patients.", "C": "The hospital administration, which can authorize emergency decisions in the absence of family members.", "D": "The case manager, who has the most comprehensive knowledge of the patient's ongoing care needs."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "When a patient lacks capacity with no advance directive and no available family, legal authority typically falls to a court-appointed guardian, and if none exists, a guardianship proceeding may be initiated. The attending physician provides medical recommendations and may make immediate emergency decisions but does not have ongoing proxy legal authority to make decisions for incapacitated patients unilaterally. Hospital administration does not have legal authority over patient care decisions. The case manager knows the patient well but does not hold legal proxy authority over medical treatment decisions."}, {"id": 172, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is developing a care plan for a patient with a physical disability. According to the Americans with Disabilities Act, what obligation does this create for the case manager's organization in delivering services?", "options": {"A": "Providing services exclusively through telehealth to avoid requiring the patient to travel to facilities.", "B": "Making reasonable accommodations to ensure the patient has equal access to case management services.", "C": "Exempting the patient from program participation requirements that may be physically challenging.", "D": "Ensuring the patient receives all case management services at no cost since the ADA mandates free services."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The ADA requires organizations to make reasonable accommodations to ensure individuals with disabilities have equal access to services, which may include accessible meeting locations, modified communication formats, or adjusted scheduling. The ADA does not require converting all services to telehealth, which may itself be a barrier for some patients. Exempting patients from program requirements removes accountability without addressing the access barrier. The ADA mandates equal access, not free services; it does not guarantee cost-free delivery of case management services to individuals with disabilities."}, {"id": 173, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager discovers from chart review that a physician appears to be prescribing controlled substances to patients without conducting appropriate clinical evaluations. What is the most appropriate initial action by the case manager?", "options": {"A": "Confront the physician directly about the prescribing pattern observed during the record review.", "B": "Document the concern privately and monitor the physician's prescribing patterns for three more months.", "C": "Report the concern through the organization's compliance program or medical staff reporting mechanism.", "D": "Contact the state medical board directly without first informing the organization's compliance team."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Inappropriate controlled substance prescribing is a serious patient safety and legal concern that should be reported through the organization's established compliance reporting mechanism or medical staff peer review process. Confronting the physician directly may create professional conflict without ensuring a systematic investigation occurs. Monitoring privately for months delays addressing ongoing patient safety risk. Bypassing the organization's compliance process and going directly to the medical board is premature before internal reporting mechanisms have been engaged, though the board may be an appropriate escalation if internal reporting fails."}, {"id": 174, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A patient's advance directive clearly states she does not want cardiopulmonary resuscitation. During hospitalization, her son demands the physician rescind the DNR order, claiming he knows what is best for his mother. What is the case manager's most appropriate role?", "options": {"A": "Support the son's request since family members are legally empowered to override valid advance directives.", "B": "Ask the attending physician to make a final ruling and document that the family conflict was noted.", "C": "Suggest a compromise in which limited resuscitation attempts are made to satisfy both parties.", "D": "Explain to the son that the advance directive reflects his mother's legal wishes."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The case manager's role is to advocate for the patient's documented wishes by explaining the legal authority of the advance directive and facilitating a family meeting to help the son understand and honor his mother's choices. Family members cannot legally override a valid advance directive by a previously competent patient. The attending physician supports the advance directive rather than adjudicating family conflict. Compromising on the DNR order violates the patient's clearly documented wishes. A family meeting often helps grieving family members process their emotions and accept their loved one's preferences."}, {"id": 175, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager receives a subpoena requesting that she testify about a patient's care in an ongoing legal proceeding. Before responding or testifying, the case manager's most appropriate first step is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Contact the patient and inform her that a subpoena has been received and testimony will be required.", "B": "Consult with the organization's legal counsel before responding to the subpoena or providing testimony.", "C": "Provide a written summary of the patient's care to the court and decline to appear for a deposition.", "D": "Refuse to testify on the grounds that all patient information is protected by HIPAA confidentiality."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When served with a subpoena, the case manager's first step is to consult with the organization's legal counsel, who can advise whether the subpoena is valid, whether to comply or seek to quash it, and how to respond appropriately to protect both the patient's rights and the case manager's interests. Contacting the patient may not be appropriate depending on the type of legal proceeding involved. Providing a written summary without appearing may not satisfy the court's order. Refusing to testify solely on HIPAA grounds is incorrect since valid court orders may permit or require disclosure under HIPAA exceptions."}, {"id": 176, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A patient asks the case manager for a copy of her own medical records. Under HIPAA, which statement accurately describes the patient's right to access her own medical records?", "options": {"A": "Patients may only access their records after the treating physician reviews and approves the request.", "B": "Patients have the right to access their own medical records within 30 days and may request amendments.", "C": "Patients may access records only for completed episodes of care, not for current or ongoing treatment.", "D": "Patients must demonstrate a specific clinical need for their records before access can be granted."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "HIPAA grants patients the right to access their own protected health information within 30 days of a written request (extendable by 30 days with notice) and the right to request amendments to records they believe are inaccurate or incomplete. Physician review and approval is not required before patients access their own records. Patients may access records from both completed and current episodes of care. Patients do not need to demonstrate a specific reason to exercise this right; it is a fundamental HIPAA entitlement that applies to all individuals."}, {"id": 177, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager overhears a colleague loudly discussing a patient's diagnosis and test results in the hospital cafeteria within earshot of other staff and visitors. This behavior most directly violates which standard?", "options": {"A": "The CCMC standard requiring case managers to communicate clearly and effectively with the care team.", "B": "The HIPAA minimum necessary standard for sharing only required information for treatment purposes.", "C": "The HIPAA privacy rule requiring protection of PHI from incidental or unnecessary disclosure.", "D": "The ethics standard of veracity, requiring honest and accurate communication about patient care."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Discussing a patient's PHI in a public area where others can overhear is a violation of the HIPAA privacy rule, which requires covered entities to implement reasonable safeguards to protect PHI from incidental or unauthorized disclosure in public or semi-public spaces. The minimum necessary standard applies to intentional data-sharing decisions, not incidental verbal disclosure in public settings. The CCMC communication standard is a professional standard but is not the most directly violated principle here. Veracity requires truthfulness in communication and is unrelated to this privacy violation scenario."}, {"id": 178, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager suspects that a child in one of her patient's households shows signs of neglect including poor hygiene, inappropriate clothing for the weather, and frequent school absences. The most appropriate action is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Ask the patient directly whether the child is being adequately cared for before taking any further action.", "B": "Consult with a supervisor and document the conversation before making a formal report to authorities.", "C": "Wait until evidence of physical abuse is directly observed before contacting child protective services.", "D": "Report the suspected neglect to child protective services as required by mandatory reporting law."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Case managers are mandatory reporters of suspected child abuse and neglect in all U.S. states, required to report to child protective services when there is reasonable suspicion of neglect without waiting for confirmation or certainty. Child neglect including poor hygiene and school absences meets the threshold for a mandatory report. Asking the patient first may alert the abuser before the report is made. Consulting a supervisor is reasonable as a concurrent step but does not delay the mandatory report. Waiting for evidence of physical abuse increases the child's risk and violates mandatory reporting obligations."}, {"id": 179, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A pharmaceutical representative visits the case management department offering gift cards and complimentary meals to case managers in exchange for enrolling patients in a branded medication adherence tracking program. Which action by the case manager is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Report the promotional activity to the organization's compliance department as a potential conflict of interest.", "B": "Accept the gifts since they are modest in value and benefit patients through a medication program.", "C": "Ask the representative to limit promotional materials to non-patient-contact areas of the facility.", "D": "Participate in the program since the patient benefit justifies a minor industry relationship."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Pharmaceutical promotional activities that link healthcare worker participation to patient enrollment create conflicts of interest that must be reported to the organization's compliance department. Even modest gifts from pharmaceutical representatives may violate organizational conflict-of-interest policies and professional ethics standards. Asking the representative to relocate materials does not address the underlying conflict. A program's potential patient benefit does not justify operating under an undisclosed conflict of interest or accepting value in exchange for clinical decisions."}, {"id": 180, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is ending her relationship with a patient who is being transferred to a new case manager. Which action best demonstrates ethical termination of the case management relationship?", "options": {"A": "Close the case immediately and inform the patient by mail that the case has been transferred.", "B": "Provide the patient with a warm handoff to the new case manager.", "C": "Ask the patient to contact the new case manager on her own and provide the new case manager's name.", "D": "Complete a formal case closure note and archive all records before notifying the patient of the change."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Ethical termination of a case management relationship includes ensuring continuity of care through a warm handoff, communicating the transition clearly to the patient, and transferring the care plan to the new case manager so there is no gap in services. Closing the case immediately without a transition plan abandons the patient. Asking the patient to initiate contact with the new case manager places the burden on the patient and increases the risk of a gap in care. Completing administrative closure before notifying the patient inverts the appropriate order of ethical responsibilities."}, {"id": 181, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is asked to withhold information from a patient about a treatment option that the physician believes the patient would pursue but that the physician considers lower quality. Complying with this request would most directly violate which ethical principle?", "options": {"A": "Beneficence, the obligation to act in the patient's best interest across all care interactions.", "B": "Nonmaleficence, the obligation to refrain from causing unnecessary harm to the patient.", "C": "Veracity, the obligation to communicate honestly and not deceive patients about their care options.", "D": "Justice, the obligation to ensure fair treatment and equitable access to available medical options."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Withholding information about an available treatment option from a patient constitutes deception and directly violates veracity, the ethical obligation to communicate truthfully and not conceal clinically relevant information from patients. Informed consent requires patients to receive complete information about all reasonable treatment alternatives. Beneficence requires acting in the patient's best interest, which includes honest communication. Nonmaleficence addresses avoiding harm. Justice addresses equitable treatment. Veracity is the most directly violated principle when a provider deliberately withholds relevant treatment information."}, {"id": 182, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A state legislature passes a law requiring healthcare providers to report suspected cases of elder financial exploitation to Adult Protective Services. A case manager who suspects a patient's adult son is using her finances without her consent should take which action?", "options": {"A": "Consult with the patient's attorney before reporting to ensure the report is legally necessary.", "B": "Discuss the concern with the patient and ask her to file the report herself if she chooses to proceed.", "C": "Document the concern in the clinical record and inform the attending physician only for oversight.", "D": "Report the suspected financial exploitation to Adult Protective Services as required by state law."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Mandatory reporting laws for elder financial exploitation require healthcare providers to report suspected exploitation to Adult Protective Services without waiting for legal confirmation or patient permission. Consulting an attorney before reporting delays the protective process and is not required by mandatory reporting law. Asking the patient to file the report herself places the burden on a potentially vulnerable adult and does not fulfill the professional's mandatory reporting obligation. Informing only the physician does not constitute the required report to the mandated state agency."}, {"id": 183, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager maintains a personal social media profile and is tempted to post general comments about a frustrating patient encounter without using the patient's name or any obvious identifiers. The most appropriate action is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Post the comment since no names or direct identifiers are shared and the patient cannot be identified.", "B": "Post only on a private social media account with strict privacy settings limiting who can view the post.", "C": "Refrain from posting since even de-identified patient information may violate HIPAA and professional standards.", "D": "Seek supervisor approval before posting to ensure organizational social media policies are followed."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Case managers must not post patient-related information on social media, even without direct identifiers, because small communities, unique clinical details, or combinations of information may allow re-identification of patients in violation of HIPAA. Professional standards also prohibit using social media in ways that undermine patient dignity or trust. Private account settings do not guarantee information remains private once posted. Supervisor approval is good practice for organizational content but does not make patient-related social media posting acceptable under professional and HIPAA standards."}, {"id": 184, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is documenting care for a patient receiving palliative services. The patient's family asks the case manager to document that the patient 'had no pain' during a visit when the patient actually reported moderate pain. Which action is most appropriate?", "options": {"A": "Accommodate the family's request since they are acting out of concern for the patient's dignity.", "B": "Document what the family reports rather than the patient's own report to prevent conflict.", "C": "Explain to the family that documentation must accurately reflect the patient's own reported experience.", "D": "Leave the pain assessment field blank in the record to avoid documenting inaccurate information."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Medical records must accurately reflect the patient's own reported experience and clinical findings. Falsifying documentation at a family's request, even with good intentions, constitutes medical record falsification and violates legal and professional standards. Documenting the family's report instead of the patient's report misrepresents the patient's subjective experience and may affect clinical decision-making. Leaving the pain assessment blank is an incomplete record that obscures a clinically relevant finding. The case manager must document the patient's actual report and explain this obligation to the family."}, {"id": 185, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is asked to supervise a case management student intern during a clinical placement. When the intern makes a documentation error that affects a patient's care plan, who bears professional and legal responsibility for the error?", "options": {"A": "The student intern alone, since she performed the documentation that contained the error.", "B": "The educational institution that placed the student in the clinical setting without adequate preparation.", "C": "The supervising case manager, who is professionally responsible for work performed under her supervision.", "D": "Shared responsibility equally between the case manager, the student, and the institution."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The supervising case manager bears professional and legal responsibility for the work performed by students under her supervision, including documentation errors that affect patient care. Supervision creates a duty to oversee, review, and correct work in progress. The student intern may also bear responsibility depending on the circumstances, but the supervisor's oversight duty is a central principle of professional supervision. The educational institution has administrative responsibilities but is not the primary party legally responsible for clinical supervision failures. Shared liability frameworks vary but the supervisor's primary responsibility is the foundational standard."}, {"id": 186, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager learns she is being named in a malpractice lawsuit related to a patient's care two years ago. Before the statute of limitations expired, the patient alleged negligent discharge planning. The case manager's first action should be which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Review the patient's old chart and update any documentation to better reflect the care provided.", "B": "Contact the patient directly to discuss the situation and attempt to resolve the dispute informally.", "C": "Reach out to the patient's attorney to understand the nature of the allegations before consulting counsel.", "D": "Notify the organization's risk management department and legal counsel immediately without altering records."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When named in a malpractice lawsuit, the case manager should immediately notify organizational risk management and legal counsel without altering any records, since changes to records after litigation is initiated may constitute obstruction and could be considered spoliation of evidence. Altering old documentation to improve its appearance is illegal and constitutes medical record falsification. Contacting the patient directly when litigation is initiated is inadvisable without attorney guidance. Reaching out to the patient's attorney without one's own legal counsel is inappropriate and potentially harmful to the case manager's legal position."}, {"id": 187, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager employed by a hospital observes that financial pressures are causing the organization to systematically delay care authorizations for Medicaid patients compared to commercially insured patients. This practice most directly violates which ethical principle?", "options": {"A": "Justice, which requires fair and equitable access to care regardless of insurance type or payer status.", "B": "Beneficence, which requires case managers to act in the best interest of every individual patient.", "C": "Veracity, which requires honest communication with patients about delays affecting their care access.", "D": "Nonmaleficence, which requires avoiding harm to patients through unnecessary clinical care delays."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Systematically delaying care authorizations for Medicaid patients compared to commercially insured patients creates inequitable access based on payer status, directly violating the ethical principle of justice, which requires fair and equitable treatment regardless of a patient's insurance type. While nonmaleficence and beneficence are also relevant since delays may harm patients, the systematic disparity in treatment based on payer classification is the defining feature of a justice violation. Veracity addresses honesty in communication. The primary ethical violation here is the systemic inequity in care access."}, {"id": 188, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A patient enrolled in Medicare Advantage is denied coverage for a knee replacement that his physician considers medically necessary. The patient appeals the denial and the health plan upholds it. What is the patient's next available recourse?", "options": {"A": "File a complaint with the state insurance commissioner for review of the denial decision.", "B": "Request an expedited external review through the Independent Review Organization process.", "C": "Ask the case manager to re-submit the prior authorization request with additional documentation.", "D": "Contact the employer that selected the Medicare Advantage plan to request an exception to coverage."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "After an internal appeal is upheld by a Medicare Advantage plan, the patient has the right to request an external review through an Independent Review Organization (IRO), which is a federally required third-party process that reviews the clinical merits of the denial independent of the health plan. The state insurance commissioner handles complaints about non-Medicare commercial insurance. Re-submitting the prior authorization is a first-level process that has already been exhausted. Employers who select Medicare Advantage plans do not have authority over individual coverage exception decisions."}, {"id": 189, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is working with a terminally ill patient whose family insists on continuing life-sustaining treatment that the clinical team considers medically futile. The patient previously stated verbally that he would not want to 'be kept alive by machines.' Which ethical principle most supports honoring the patient's previously stated wishes?", "options": {"A": "Beneficence, the obligation to pursue all available treatments that may provide clinical benefit.", "B": "Nonmaleficence, the obligation to avoid harm, which includes burdensome and futile interventions.", "C": "Justice, the obligation to allocate scarce ICU resources equitably across all patients in need.", "D": "Autonomy, the patient's right to self-determination, which extends to prior verbal statements of values."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Autonomy supports honoring the patient's previously stated preferences about end-of-life care, even when those preferences were expressed verbally rather than in writing, as long as they were expressed by a competent patient. Beneficence supports pursuing treatments that provide genuine clinical benefit, not futile interventions. Nonmaleficence is also relevant since futile treatment may cause suffering without benefit, but the most direct supporting principle for honoring prior verbal preferences is autonomy and self-determination. Justice addresses resource allocation across populations rather than individual treatment decisions."}, {"id": 190, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager disagrees with a payer's denial of inpatient treatment for a patient with severe depression, believing the denial is clinically inappropriate. After completing internal appeals without success, what is the appropriate next step?", "options": {"A": "Accept the final internal appeal decision and inform the patient that no further recourse is available.", "B": "File a grievance with the case manager's professional association citing unethical payer behavior.", "C": "Refer the matter to the patient's employer to negotiate a coverage exception directly with the payer.", "D": "Assist the patient in requesting an external independent review of the denial decision."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "After exhausting internal appeals, the patient has the right to an external independent review by a third-party organization not affiliated with the health plan, which is required under state and federal law for most health insurance denials. Accepting the final internal appeal decision without informing the patient of external review rights fails to fully advocate for the patient. Filing with a professional association does not resolve the coverage denial for the patient. The employer may have some influence over plan administration but requesting an independent review is the legally established next step."}, {"id": 191, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A patient diagnosed with a terminal illness asks the case manager whether she can legally request that treatment be stopped even though she is still alive. The case manager's most accurate response is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Competent patients have the legal right to refuse or withdraw any treatment including life-sustaining care.", "B": "Withdrawing treatment is considered passive euthanasia and is not legally permitted in any U.S. state.", "C": "Only a physician can legally authorize withdrawal of treatment; patients can only request but not decide.", "D": "Patients may refuse new treatments but cannot request withdrawal of treatments that have already begun."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Competent patients have the constitutionally recognized legal right to refuse or withdraw any medical treatment, including life-sustaining care, in all U.S. states. This principle was affirmed in landmark cases including Cruzan v. Director. Withdrawing treatment at a competent patient's request is not legally or ethically equivalent to euthanasia, which involves an active step to end life. The physician carries out the withdrawal clinically but the right to decide rests with the patient. The distinction between refusing new versus withdrawing ongoing treatment is not a legal or ethical limitation."}, {"id": 192, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is creating a care plan for a patient who speaks limited English and has a different cultural background. The case manager notices the care plan was developed entirely without input from the patient because the team assumed the patient would defer to family. Which ethical principle was most directly violated?", "options": {"A": "Beneficence, since the care plan may not adequately reflect the patient's best clinical interests.", "B": "Autonomy, since the patient was excluded from decision-making about her own care without consent.", "C": "Veracity, since the team communicated inaccurately about the patient's preferences to the plan.", "D": "Nonmaleficence, since developing a care plan without patient input may lead to clinical errors."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Excluding a patient from care planning decisions about her own health without her consent violates autonomy, the right to self-determination and participation in one's own healthcare. The assumption that a patient will defer to family based on cultural background without asking her is paternalistic and bypasses her right to be heard. Using a qualified interpreter to include the patient in care planning is the ethically required approach. While beneficence, nonmaleficence, and veracity may also be affected, the most direct violation is autonomy, since the patient was denied participation in her own care."}, {"id": 193, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager in a hospital setting is aware that her colleague routinely provides patient information to a pharmaceutical company without patient authorization, saying it is 'just de-identified data.' The case manager is concerned this is a HIPAA violation. What is the most appropriate action?", "options": {"A": "Trust the colleague's assertion that the data is de-identified and take no action at this time.", "B": "Review the data being shared personally to confirm whether it is truly de-identified before deciding.", "C": "Report the concern to the organization's privacy officer or compliance department for investigation.", "D": "Warn the colleague privately that sharing patient data with pharmaceutical companies is inappropriate."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Suspected unauthorized disclosure of patient data to a pharmaceutical company should be reported to the organization's privacy officer or compliance department, which has the authority and expertise to investigate whether the data meets HIPAA de-identification standards and whether the disclosure is lawful. Trusting the colleague's self-assessment without a formal review leaves a potential HIPAA violation unaddressed. The case manager is not the appropriate person to review clinical data files to assess de-identification compliance. A private warning without formal reporting does not ensure the practice is investigated or stopped."}, {"id": 194, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager reviews a patient's case and discovers the patient has been receiving case management services from two different health plans simultaneously for the same condition. The case manager's most appropriate action is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Continue providing services without change since the patient may benefit from additional support.", "B": "Contact the other health plan to share clinical information and coordinate their respective care plans.", "C": "Request the patient's signed authorization before sharing any information with the other health plan.", "D": "Coordinate care with the other case management program after confirming the patient's knowledge and consent."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When a patient is enrolled in case management with two health plans simultaneously, coordinating care with the other program is appropriate to prevent duplication and ensure a unified care plan, but the case manager must first confirm the patient's knowledge of and consent to the coordination. Continuing without coordination may result in conflicting care plans and duplicated services. Contacting the other health plan to share information without the patient's knowledge or consent violates HIPAA privacy rules. A signed authorization is the formal mechanism but confirming patient consent in any form is the essential first step."}, {"id": 195, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is preparing for a peer review discussion of a complex case. Which behavior would most clearly demonstrate adherence to the CCMC standard of professional conduct during the peer review?", "options": {"A": "Presenting the case in a way that avoids mentioning clinical errors the case manager personally made.", "B": "Declining to participate in peer review since the case involves confidential patient information.", "C": "Focusing the discussion exclusively on the patient's lack of adherence as the primary barrier to success.", "D": "Presenting an honest and balanced account of the case including challenges and areas for improvement."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The CCMC Code of Professional Conduct requires case managers to maintain integrity and transparency, which includes presenting an honest and balanced account of a case during peer review, including personal errors or missed opportunities for improvement. Omitting clinical errors misrepresents the case and undermines the peer review's quality improvement purpose. Declining to participate because of patient confidentiality is inappropriate since peer review is a protected process using appropriately de-identified information. Attributing poor outcomes solely to patient non-adherence avoids professional accountability and limits the learning value of peer review."}, {"id": 196, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A physician orders a medication that the case manager knows is contraindicated based on the patient's most recent laboratory values. The case manager's most appropriate action is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Proceed with coordinating care per the physician's order since the physician has prescribing authority.", "B": "Contact the physician immediately to communicate the laboratory finding and the potential contraindication.", "C": "Contact the pharmacist and ask them to substitute a safer medication without the physician's knowledge.", "D": "Document the concern in the chart and wait to see if the patient develops an adverse reaction."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When a case manager identifies a potential patient safety concern such as a medication ordered despite a contraindicated laboratory value, the professional obligation is to communicate the concern to the prescribing physician immediately so they can make an informed clinical decision. The physician retains prescribing authority, but the case manager's advocacy role includes patient safety vigilance. Proceeding without communicating the concern risks patient harm. Contacting the pharmacist to substitute a medication without physician knowledge is outside the case manager's scope. Waiting for an adverse reaction before acting is a failure to protect the patient."}, {"id": 197, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is asked to participate in developing a policy that would limit case management services to patients with certain insurance types. The case manager believes this policy would discriminate against Medicaid patients. The most appropriate professional response is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Implement the policy as directed since the organization has the authority to make coverage decisions.", "B": "Refuse to participate and submit a formal written resignation to avoid professional ethical conflict.", "C": "Voice objections through appropriate professional and organizational channels and document the concern.", "D": "Implement the policy for commercial patients only while continuing services for all Medicaid patients."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "When a case manager believes a proposed policy is ethically problematic or discriminatory, the appropriate professional response is to voice objections through legitimate organizational and professional channels such as committee input, a formal written concern, or consultation with ethics leadership, and to document those concerns. Implementing a discriminatory policy without objection violates the professional obligation to advocate for equitable care. Resigning without attempting to address the concern through proper channels is premature. Selectively implementing the policy for some patients creates a different set of ethical and legal problems."}, {"id": 198, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager provides case management services to a patient and later begins a romantic relationship with the patient's adult sibling, whom she met during a family care conference. This situation most directly raises which ethical concern?", "options": {"A": "Autonomy concern, since the patient may feel pressured to comply with care recommendations given the relationship.", "B": "Beneficence concern, since the personal relationship may cause the case manager to over-serve the patient.", "C": "Justice concern, since other patients may receive less attention while the case manager focuses on this family.", "D": "Professional boundary concern, since personal relationships with members of a patient's family create conflicts."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Entering a personal romantic relationship with a member of a patient's immediate family creates a professional boundary issue and a potential conflict of interest that can compromise the objectivity and therapeutic nature of the case management relationship. This boundary concern is directly addressed in professional codes of conduct. Autonomy, beneficence, and justice are each secondarily affected but the foundational concern is the professional boundary violation itself. Case managers must maintain appropriate boundaries not only with patients but also with their families to preserve the integrity of the case management relationship."}, {"id": 199, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager receives a request from a patient's adult daughter, who lives out of state, asking to be listed as the patient's healthcare decision-maker for all future care. The patient is currently cognitively intact. What is the most appropriate response?", "options": {"A": "Add the daughter to the healthcare proxy section of the care plan based on her written request.", "B": "Inform the daughter that the hospital automatically designates the nearest family member as decision-maker.", "C": "Facilitate the process of the patient formally designating a healthcare proxy through a completed legal document.", "D": "List the daughter as the case management care coordinator contact but not as the formal healthcare proxy."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A healthcare proxy must be formally designated by the patient through a legally recognized document such as a healthcare power of attorney or durable power of attorney for healthcare. The patient, while cognitively intact, is the appropriate person to formally designate who will make decisions on her behalf. The case manager cannot designate a proxy based on a family member's unilateral written request. Most states do not automatically designate a decision-maker based on proximity; designation requires a legal document. Listing the daughter as a care contact is not equivalent to a legally recognized healthcare proxy designation."}, {"id": 200, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is coordinating care for a patient who is undocumented and uninsured. Which ethical principle most strongly guides the case manager to provide equitable care management services to this patient?", "options": {"A": "Beneficence, the obligation to act in the best interest of each individual patient in care management.", "B": "Justice, the obligation to ensure equitable access to care without discrimination based on status.", "C": "Autonomy, the obligation to respect the patient's right to make her own healthcare decisions.", "D": "Veracity, the obligation to communicate honestly about available resources and service limitations."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Justice requires equitable treatment and access to care without discrimination based on immigration status, insurance status, race, ethnicity, or any other characteristic. The principle of justice most directly obligates the case manager to provide equal care management services regardless of the patient's documentation or insurance status. Beneficence supports acting in each patient's best interest, which is also relevant. Autonomy relates to the patient's own decision-making. Veracity addresses honest communication. Justice is the most directly applicable principle when the question is one of equal access and non-discrimination."}, {"id": 201, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager working in a home care setting discovers that the patient's adult son, who is also the primary caregiver, has been stealing prescription opioid medications from the patient's supply. The most appropriate action is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Confront the son directly and ask him to stop and seek help for his substance use problem.", "B": "Discuss the observation privately with the patient and follow her preferences about how to proceed.", "C": "Report the situation to the patient's physician and through applicable elder abuse reporting channels.", "D": "Remove the medications from the home on the next visit to protect the patient from further theft."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "A caregiver stealing a patient's prescription opioids constitutes both medication diversion and potential elder abuse or neglect. The case manager should report the situation to the patient's physician, who needs to know the patient's medications are being diverted and who can assess whether the patient's pain management is compromised, and through applicable elder abuse reporting channels if indicated. Confronting the son directly without reporting may alert him to change behavior without addressing the patient's safety or unmet medication needs. Allowing the patient to decide whether to report may place undue burden on a vulnerable adult. Removing medications is outside the case manager's clinical authority."}, {"id": 202, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager is asked to complete a patient's disability insurance form stating that the patient is unable to work. Based on her case management observations, the case manager believes the patient has more functional capacity than the physician's documentation reflects. The most appropriate action is which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Complete the form as requested since the physician's clinical judgment supersedes the case manager's observations.", "B": "Refuse to complete any portion of the form and document the refusal in the case management notes.", "C": "Complete the form truthfully based on the case manager's own professional scope and documented observations.", "D": "Discuss the discrepancy with the physician first, and if unresolved, decline to sign a form she believes is inaccurate."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When a case manager observes a discrepancy between a patient's documented functional limitations and her clinical observations, the appropriate first step is to discuss the discrepancy with the physician to clarify the basis for the documentation. If the discrepancy remains unresolved and the case manager believes the form is inaccurate, she should decline to certify it rather than sign a document she believes misrepresents the patient's functional status. Completing the form without raising the concern perpetuates a potentially inaccurate record. Refusing to complete any portion without discussion bypasses a clinical conversation that may resolve the discrepancy."}, {"id": 203, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager reviewing documentation standards wants to understand the primary purpose of clinical documentation in case management practice. Which statement most accurately describes the purpose of case management documentation?", "options": {"A": "To provide a legal, chronological, and clinical record supporting continuity, accountability, and quality review.", "B": "To satisfy regulatory requirements and payer audits rather than to guide ongoing clinical care decisions.", "C": "To demonstrate to supervisors that the case manager has completed all required patient contact intervals.", "D": "To create a financial record for billing and reimbursement purposes as the primary documentation goal."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Documentation in case management serves multiple essential purposes including creating a legal clinical record, supporting continuity of care across settings and providers, demonstrating professional accountability, and enabling quality review and peer review of case management practice. Documentation is not limited to regulatory compliance or payer audits; it is a clinical and professional tool that guides care decisions. Demonstrating completion of contacts is a performance monitoring function, not the primary purpose of clinical documentation. Billing documentation is a specific subset; case management documentation serves much broader clinical, legal, and professional purposes."}, {"id": 204, "domain": "ethical_legal_and_practice_standards", "question": "A case manager who holds the CCM credential is involved in a quality improvement project at her hospital. Which CCMC standard most directly requires her to maintain current knowledge and practice in case management to ensure competent service to patients?", "options": {"A": "The standard of professional conduct requiring ethical behavior in all case management interactions.", "B": "The standard of professional development requiring ongoing education and maintaining current competency.", "C": "The standard of advocacy requiring case managers to speak on behalf of patients in all care settings.", "D": "The standard of resource management requiring cost-conscious use of healthcare services and resources."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The CCMC standard of professional development requires CCMs to maintain current knowledge and competency in case management practice through continuing education, staying current with evidence-based practice, and meeting CCM recertification requirements. The professional conduct standard addresses ethical behavior. The advocacy standard addresses speaking for patients. The resource management standard addresses efficient use of healthcare resources. Professional development is the standard most directly concerned with maintaining current knowledge and clinical competency throughout the case manager's career."}, {"id": 205, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "Under the Medicare inpatient prospective payment system, a hospital receives a fixed payment based on the patient's principal diagnosis, procedures, and complicating factors, regardless of the actual costs incurred during the stay. Which payment mechanism does this describe?", "options": {"A": "Diagnosis Related Groups, which pay a fixed amount based on the patient's diagnosis category.", "B": "Fee-for-service, where hospitals are reimbursed for each individual service provided during the stay.", "C": "Cost-based reimbursement, where hospitals are paid for actual allowable costs incurred per case.", "D": "Capitation, where hospitals receive a fixed monthly payment for each enrolled patient in a plan."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Diagnosis Related Groups (DRGs) are the basis of Medicare's inpatient Prospective Payment System, which pays a fixed predetermined amount based on the patient's diagnosis and complicating factors, regardless of actual costs. Fee-for-service pays for each individual service rendered. Cost-based reimbursement covers actual costs and was the predecessor to PPS. Capitation is a per-member per-month payment used primarily in health plan contracts, not for inpatient hospital services."}, {"id": 206, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A Medicare Part A beneficiary is hospitalized for 10 days in her first hospital admission of the year. Under Medicare Part A, which cost-sharing structure applies to her inpatient stay within this benefit period?", "options": {"A": "A daily copay applies for every day of the hospital stay beginning on day one of admission.", "B": "A single benefit-period deductible covers days 1-60 and daily coinsurance applies for days 61-90.", "C": "No patient cost-sharing applies for inpatient stays of fewer than 20 days in the same benefit period.", "D": "A flat copay per hospitalization applies regardless of the patient's total length of stay."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Medicare Part A has a single benefit-period deductible covering the first 60 days of hospitalization. Days 61 through 90 require daily coinsurance, and days 91 through 150 (lifetime reserve days) require higher daily coinsurance. There is no per-day copay for days 1 through 60. Inpatient stays under 20 days are not automatically free; the benefit-period deductible still applies. Medicare Part A does not use a flat copay structure for inpatient admissions."}, {"id": 207, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A patient enrolled in a Medicare Advantage HMO seeks care from a specialist outside the plan's network without a referral for a non-emergency condition. Under most Medicare Advantage HMO plans, which statement about this situation is most accurate?", "options": {"A": "Medicare Advantage plans must cover all out-of-network providers at the same rate as in-network providers.", "B": "The patient may see any specialist without referral since Medicare Advantage provides enhanced Medicare access.", "C": "Out-of-network non-emergency care in an HMO generally requires higher cost-sharing or may not be covered.", "D": "Original Medicare covers the out-of-network specialist at standard Medicare rates as a secondary payer."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Medicare Advantage HMO plans typically restrict non-emergency care to in-network providers, and out-of-network non-emergency care often requires significantly higher cost-sharing or is not covered at all. Medicare Advantage PPO plans allow out-of-network care at higher cost-sharing. Plans set their own network requirements, and original Medicare does not step in as a secondary payer for Medicare Advantage beneficiaries. Referral requirements vary by plan type; HMOs typically require referrals while PPOs do not."}, {"id": 208, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A Medicare Part D beneficiary reports paying 100% of her drug costs after her plan has paid $4,660 in total covered drug expenses but before she has reached the catastrophic spending threshold. Which term describes this phase of her Part D coverage?", "options": {"A": "The Part D annual deductible, the initial out-of-pocket amount before any drug coverage begins.", "B": "The formulary tier system, which determines the patient's copay level for each drug category.", "C": "Catastrophic coverage, where the patient pays only small amounts after reaching high expenditures.", "D": "The coverage gap or donut hole, a temporary reduction in coverage between initial and catastrophic phases."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The coverage gap (donut hole) is the period between the initial coverage limit and the catastrophic threshold where beneficiaries historically paid higher out-of-pocket drug costs. The ACA gradually reduced this gap and it was fully closed for brand-name drugs in 2020. The deductible is the initial out-of-pocket amount before any coverage begins. Formulary tiers determine copay levels within coverage phases but are not the coverage gap itself. Catastrophic coverage kicks in after the out-of-pocket spending threshold is met, at which point the patient pays only small coinsurance amounts."}, {"id": 209, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A managed care organization pays a primary care physician a fixed monthly payment for each enrolled patient, regardless of how many office visits or services that patient uses in the month. This payment model is best described as which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Capitation, a per-member per-month payment that transfers utilization financial risk to the provider.", "B": "Fee-for-service, where providers are paid individually for each service rendered to each patient.", "C": "Salary, where physicians receive a fixed annual income from the employing health system.", "D": "Bundled payment, where a single payment covers all services within a defined care episode."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Capitation is a fixed per-member per-month payment made to a provider regardless of the volume of services used, which transfers some financial risk to the provider since high utilization consumes the fixed payment. Fee-for-service pays per individual service and creates volume incentives. Salary provides fixed income from an employer, not a per-patient payment from a payer. Bundled payment covers a defined episode such as a surgery with post-acute care, not an ongoing monthly per-patient arrangement."}, {"id": 210, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "An Accountable Care Organization (ACO) achieves significant cost savings compared to benchmark spending while meeting quality performance thresholds. Under a shared savings model, what happens to the savings generated?", "options": {"A": "All generated savings are retained by the payer as a return on investment in the care management system.", "B": "A portion of the savings is shared with the ACO as an incentive for achieving quality and efficiency goals.", "C": "Savings are used exclusively to expand the number of participating providers in the ACO network.", "D": "Generated savings are returned directly to patients as reduced monthly premiums or cost-sharing."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In a shared savings model, an ACO that reduces costs below a benchmark while meeting quality performance thresholds shares a portion of those savings with the payer such as Medicare. This financial incentive encourages providers to coordinate care and reduce unnecessary utilization. Payers do not retain all savings; the shared savings distribution to the ACO is the defining feature of the model. Savings are not dedicated solely to network expansion. Patients benefit indirectly through better care coordination but do not typically receive direct financial distributions."}, {"id": 211, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A hospital is reimbursed through a bundled payment model for total hip replacement, which includes all acute hospital, surgeon, anesthesia, and 90-day post-acute rehabilitation costs in a single episode payment. Which incentive does this model create for care coordination?", "options": {"A": "The model incentivizes hospitals to extend the patient's length of stay to justify the bundle value.", "B": "The model creates an incentive to order more post-acute services to maximize the total bundle value.", "C": "The model incentivizes efficient coordination across the episode to reduce total costs below the bundle.", "D": "The model creates an incentive to readmit patients within 90 days to trigger an additional bundle payment."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Bundled payment models create strong financial incentives for efficient care coordination across all providers and settings within the episode because the total reimbursement is fixed and excess costs reduce the provider's net return. Extended length of stay increases costs that consume the fixed bundle rather than generating additional revenue. Ordering more post-acute services increases episode costs beyond the fixed payment, reducing net reimbursement. Readmissions within the bundle period add cost to the episode rather than generating an additional payment."}, {"id": 212, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A 72-year-old patient is enrolled in both Medicare and full Medicaid. After a qualifying hospital stay, she requires skilled nursing facility care. Which payer covers the Medicare SNF daily coinsurance that begins after day 20 of the SNF stay?", "options": {"A": "Medicare Part A covers all SNF costs up to 100 days with no patient cost-sharing for dual-eligible patients.", "B": "The patient is personally responsible for the daily SNF coinsurance from days 21 through 100.", "C": "Medicare Part B covers SNF costs when Part A benefit days are reduced or the stay is extended.", "D": "Medicaid covers the Medicare SNF coinsurance amounts for beneficiaries enrolled in full Medicaid."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "For dual-eligible beneficiaries enrolled in full Medicaid, Medicaid covers the Medicare SNF cost-sharing amounts including the daily coinsurance required for days 21 through 100, eliminating out-of-pocket costs for this population. Medicare Part A is not free for all 100 SNF days; days 21 through 100 carry daily coinsurance requirements. Personal patient cost-sharing is eliminated for full dual-eligibles because Medicaid covers it. Medicare Part B does not cover SNF room and board, which is a Medicare Part A benefit."}, {"id": 213, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A health plan denies coverage for a cancer treatment the oncologist considers medically necessary. The patient has completed all internal appeals and all were upheld. What external recourse is available under ACA requirements?", "options": {"A": "An independent external review by a third-party organization not affiliated with the health plan.", "B": "A civil lawsuit filed against the health plan for breach of contract in the applicable state court.", "C": "A formal complaint submitted to the employer who selected the health plan on the patient's behalf.", "D": "Re-application to the health plan with a new prior authorization request and additional documentation."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The ACA requires health plans to provide access to independent external review for coverage denials after internal appeals are exhausted, and the external reviewer's decision is binding on the health plan. Litigation is a legal remedy but is a much slower and more burdensome process than the external review available under ACA. The employer may have influence over plan administration but cannot overturn individual coverage decisions. Re-applying after exhausting all appeals restarts a process that has already concluded; external review is the established formal next step."}, {"id": 214, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A 45-year-old patient is diagnosed with end-stage renal disease requiring regular dialysis three times per week. Under Medicare rules, when does this patient generally become eligible for Medicare coverage based on ESRD?", "options": {"A": "Immediately upon the first dialysis treatment at a certified Medicare dialysis facility.", "B": "Generally after a three-month waiting period following the initiation of regular dialysis.", "C": "Upon reaching age 65, when standard Medicare eligibility age criteria are met regardless of ESRD.", "D": "After meeting income and asset limits established by Medicaid for low-income adult coverage."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Medicare ESRD eligibility typically begins after a three-month waiting period from the start of regular dialysis, unless the patient has a prior qualifying Medicare enrollment period or receives a kidney transplant. Coverage does not begin immediately upon the first dialysis treatment. ESRD Medicare coverage is available at any age and is not limited to those 65 and older. ESRD Medicare eligibility is based on ESRD status and work history, not income or asset means testing like Medicaid."}, {"id": 215, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A hospital receives notification from a Recovery Audit Contractor (RAC) demanding repayment for inpatient admissions identified as appropriate only for outpatient observation. Which statement accurately describes the hospital's recourse?", "options": {"A": "The hospital must repay all flagged claims within 30 days with no right to formally appeal the determination.", "B": "The hospital can only appeal RAC decisions through the federal court system after all other options fail.", "C": "The hospital may appeal RAC determinations through a multi-level administrative appeals process.", "D": "RAC audits are limited to reviewing claims from the current fiscal year and cannot review prior years."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Hospitals have the right to appeal RAC determinations through a multi-level administrative appeals process including redetermination, reconsideration, ALJ hearing, Medicare Appeals Council review, and federal court as a final step. Repayment is not mandatory within 30 days without an opportunity to appeal; the appeals process can be initiated before repayment. RAC appeals follow an administrative process before federal court. RAC audits can review Medicare claims going back up to three years from the date of the original claim."}, {"id": 216, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A 42-year-old patient with a work-related back injury cannot return to his previous physically demanding job. The workers' compensation case manager is coordinating his return-to-work plan. Which workers' compensation benefit most directly supports his transition to a different type of employment?", "options": {"A": "Temporary total disability benefits, which replace wages while the patient recovers from his acute injury.", "B": "Permanent partial disability benefits, which compensate for a lasting reduction in earning capacity.", "C": "Medical-only benefits, which cover treatment costs for the work injury without income replacement.", "D": "Vocational rehabilitation services, which provide retraining and job placement for injured workers."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Vocational rehabilitation services under workers' compensation provide job analysis, skills assessment, retraining, and job placement assistance to injured workers who cannot return to their previous occupation. Temporary total disability benefits replace lost wages during the acute recovery period but do not address career retraining or job transition. Permanent partial disability benefits provide financial compensation for lasting functional limitations but are not a return-to-work service. Medical-only benefits cover treatment costs only and do not address employment transition needs."}, {"id": 217, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A physician orders monthly injections for a patient with age-related macular degeneration to be administered in the physician's office. Which Medicare benefit most appropriately covers physician-administered medications in an outpatient office setting?", "options": {"A": "Medicare Part B, which covers physician services and medications administered in the physician's office.", "B": "Medicare Part A, which covers hospital-based drugs administered during an inpatient stay.", "C": "Medicare Part D, which covers all prescription medications regardless of where they are administered.", "D": "Medicare Advantage, which is required by law to cover all physician-administered injectable medications."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Medicare Part B covers physician services and certain physician-administered medications including anti-VEGF injections for macular degeneration, chemotherapy, and biologics when given in a physician's office or outpatient setting. Medicare Part A covers inpatient hospital drugs, not office-based physician-administered medications. Medicare Part D covers self-administered prescription drugs, not injections administered by a physician. Medicare Advantage covers the same benefits as original Medicare with plan-specific variations, but Part B is the specific benefit covering this service."}, {"id": 218, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A 68-year-old Medicare beneficiary is also covered by her 55-year-old husband's active employer group health plan at a company with 35 employees. Which payer is the primary payer for her healthcare services?", "options": {"A": "Medicare is primary since the patient is 68 years old and has been Medicare-eligible by age for three years.", "B": "The employer group health plan is primary since the employer has 20 or more employees.", "C": "Both plans share costs equally as co-primary payers under standard coordination of benefits rules.", "D": "Medicare is primary for hospital services while the employer plan is primary for physician services."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Under Medicare Secondary Payer rules, when a Medicare beneficiary is covered by an active employer group health plan at an employer with 20 or more employees, the employer plan is the primary payer and Medicare is secondary. The patient's age and individual Medicare eligibility do not make Medicare primary when a qualifying employer group plan exists. Plans do not share as co-primary payers; one is always primary and the other secondary. The primary and secondary designation applies to all covered services, not divided by service category."}, {"id": 219, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A 32-year-old single adult with no children has an income of 110% of the Federal Poverty Level in a state that adopted the ACA Medicaid expansion. Under the ACA, which program would this individual most likely qualify for?", "options": {"A": "Medicare, since he has a disability that qualifies him for federal health coverage at any age.", "B": "CHIP, which covers low-income children and pregnant women under a defined income threshold.", "C": "ACA Medicaid expansion coverage, which extended eligibility to low-income adults under 65 regardless of family status.", "D": "Premium tax credits through the ACA marketplace, since his income exceeds standard Medicaid thresholds."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The ACA Medicaid expansion made Medicaid available to adults under 65 with incomes up to 138% of the Federal Poverty Level in expansion states, regardless of disability, family composition, or parental status. This covers the 32-year-old single adult with income at 110% FPL. Medicare covers individuals 65 and older or those with qualifying disabilities, which does not apply here. CHIP covers children and pregnant women, not working-age adults without dependents. Premium tax credits apply to incomes between 100% and 400% FPL for those not eligible for Medicaid."}, {"id": 220, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A payer denies home health authorization for a diabetic patient citing that the patient does not meet the homebound criterion. The case manager disagrees with the denial. Which documentation most strengthens a medical necessity appeal for homebound status?", "options": {"A": "A copy of the patient's most recent HbA1c result demonstrating poor glycemic control for six months.", "B": "The patient's pharmacy records documenting consistent use of multiple antidiabetic medications.", "C": "A signed statement from the patient confirming that leaving home is difficult due to her condition.", "D": "A physician's detailed clinical note documenting the patient's functional limitations and homebound status."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "A detailed physician's clinical note that specifically documents the patient's functional limitations, mobility restrictions, and the substantial effort required to leave home provides the most authoritative clinical evidence of homebound status for a medical necessity appeal. HbA1c results document disease severity but not homebound functional status. Pharmacy records demonstrate medication use but not functional limitations. The patient's signed statement may support the appeal but a physician's objective clinical documentation is the most compelling evidence for a homebound status determination by the payer."}, {"id": 221, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A disease management organization is under contract to provide telephonic care management for a health plan at a rate of $12 per member per month for a population of 5,000 enrolled members. What is the total monthly payment the disease management organization receives?", "options": {"A": "$60,000 per month, calculated by multiplying the PMPM rate by total enrolled members.", "B": "$12,000 per month, calculated by multiplying the PMPM rate by 1,000 enrolled members.", "C": "$600 per month, calculated by multiplying the PMPM rate by the 50 highest-risk members.", "D": "$720,000 per year, representing the total annual contract value paid in one installment."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The monthly payment is calculated by multiplying the PMPM rate ($12) by the total number of enrolled members (5,000), resulting in $60,000 per month. PMPM rates apply to the entire enrolled population, not a subset of members. The annual payment would be $720,000 per year ($60,000 x 12 months), paid in monthly installments rather than a single annual payment. Understanding PMPM calculations is a core financial literacy competency for case managers working in population health management contracts."}, {"id": 222, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A case manager is evaluating whether a patient qualifies for Medicare-covered home health services after hospital discharge. Which requirement must the ordering physician fulfill to properly authorize Medicare home health services?", "options": {"A": "The physician must certify that the patient is unable to perform all activities of daily living without assistance.", "B": "The physician must certify the patient's homebound status, the need for skilled care, and sign the plan of care.", "C": "The physician must have personally performed a home visit within 90 days of certifying home health need.", "D": "The physician must document that the patient was hospitalized for at least five consecutive days before referral."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "For Medicare home health authorization, the physician must certify that the patient is homebound, requires at least one skilled service such as nursing or therapy, and must sign the home health plan of care. There is no requirement that the patient be unable to perform all ADLs; homebound status and skilled care need are the defining criteria. Face-to-face encounter requirements under CMS have evolved over time. There is no five-day hospitalization requirement; Medicare home health can be authorized directly from the community without a preceding hospitalization."}, {"id": 223, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A hospital's 30-day readmission rate for pneumonia patients significantly exceeds the national benchmark. Under the Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program (HRRP), what financial consequence does this hospital face?", "options": {"A": "The hospital receives additional Medicare funding to invest in transitional care and readmission prevention.", "B": "The hospital loses Medicare participation status until readmission rates are brought within acceptable limits.", "C": "The hospital receives reduced Medicare inpatient payments as a penalty for excess readmission rates.", "D": "The hospital is required to report the readmission data to the state health department for oversight review."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Under HRRP, hospitals with excess readmission rates for defined conditions receive reduced Medicare inpatient payments as a financial penalty. This incentive was designed to encourage hospitals to invest in discharge planning, care transitions, and post-discharge follow-up. Hospitals do not receive additional funding for poor performance. Loss of Medicare participation requires a far more serious failure than a high readmission rate. State health department reporting is a separate quality reporting obligation that is not the HRRP financial consequence."}, {"id": 224, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A Medicare beneficiary is admitted to the hospital on a Tuesday as an inpatient and remains for three consecutive nights before being discharged to a skilled nursing facility on Friday. Does this patient meet the Medicare three-day qualifying inpatient stay requirement for SNF coverage?", "options": {"A": "No, because Medicare requires five consecutive inpatient nights to qualify for Part A SNF coverage.", "B": "No, because hospital weekends are not counted as qualifying inpatient days under Part A rules.", "C": "No, because the discharge day is excluded and only two qualifying inpatient days can be counted.", "D": "Yes, because three consecutive inpatient nights satisfy the qualifying hospital stay requirement."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Medicare requires at least three consecutive days as an inpatient (not including the discharge day) to qualify for the Part A SNF benefit. Being admitted Tuesday and staying three nights (Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday night) with discharge on Friday satisfies the requirement. Medicare does not require five inpatient nights. All days of the week, including weekends, count equally as qualifying inpatient days. The discharge day is not counted toward the three-day requirement, but three nights of inpatient status prior to discharge fully satisfies the rule."}, {"id": 225, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A patient is injured in a car accident by an at-fault driver and receives medical treatment. She is covered by both her personal health insurance and the at-fault driver's automobile liability insurance. Which payer is the primary payer for the accident-related medical claims?", "options": {"A": "The at-fault driver's liability insurance, as the liable third-party payer responsible for the injury.", "B": "The patient's personal health insurance, since it was in force prior to the accident.", "C": "Both insurers share costs equally under standard coordination of benefits principles.", "D": "Medicare if the patient is over 65 and enrolled, since Medicare is always the primary payer."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Third-party liability insurance such as the at-fault driver's auto insurance is the primary payer for injuries caused by that party's negligence, and the patient's health insurance is secondary. Prior enrollment in personal health insurance does not make it primary over a liable third party. Liability insurance and health insurance do not share costs equally; the liable party's insurance pays first. Medicare Secondary Payer rules also require liability insurance to pay before Medicare in liability injury claims, not after."}, {"id": 226, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A commercial health insurance plan has an annual out-of-pocket maximum of $7,500. A patient has accumulated $7,500 in cost-sharing during the plan year. Which statement accurately describes the patient's coverage for the remainder of the plan year?", "options": {"A": "The patient continues paying cost-sharing but at a reduced percentage rate for the rest of the year.", "B": "The plan covers 100% of in-network covered service costs for the patient for the rest of the plan year.", "C": "The patient may access any provider including out-of-network at no cost for covered services.", "D": "The patient's cost-sharing accumulation resets to zero at the beginning of the following month."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Once a patient reaches the annual out-of-pocket maximum, the insurance plan covers 100% of covered in-network service costs for the remainder of the plan year with no additional patient cost-sharing required. Cost-sharing does not continue at a reduced rate after the maximum is reached; coverage becomes complete for in-network services. The out-of-pocket maximum typically applies to in-network services; out-of-network care may have separate out-of-pocket requirements or may not be covered. The out-of-pocket maximum resets annually at the beginning of each new plan year, not monthly."}, {"id": 227, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A case manager wants to understand how Medicare pays physicians for evaluation and management services. Which payment methodology forms the basis of Medicare physician payment under the physician fee schedule?", "options": {"A": "The cost-based system where Medicare reimburses each physician's actual submitted charges for services.", "B": "The DRG system that assigns each physician visit to a diagnosis-related payment category.", "C": "The Resource-Based Relative Value Scale, assigning values based on physician work, practice costs, and malpractice.", "D": "A capitation model where each physician receives a flat monthly payment per enrolled Medicare patient."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Medicare pays physicians through the Resource-Based Relative Value Scale (RBRVS), which assigns relative value units to each service based on physician work, practice expenses, and malpractice costs, then multiplied by a national conversion factor to determine the payment amount. Medicare does not reimburse physicians based on actual submitted charges; it maintains its own fee schedule. DRGs apply to inpatient hospital payments, not physician fees. Most Medicare physician payment is fee-for-service through RBRVS, though alternative payment models such as MSSP may use different structures."}, {"id": 228, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A patient covered by an HMO visits an out-of-network emergency physician after a motor vehicle accident and now wants to follow up at the same out-of-network physician's office for non-emergency care. Under HMO plan rules, which statement most accurately describes the follow-up visit coverage?", "options": {"A": "The HMO must cover all follow-up emergency-related care at in-network rates regardless of provider network.", "B": "The HMO covers the follow-up visit if the primary care physician provides a written referral first.", "C": "The HMO covers all follow-up visits with the out-of-network physician without restriction or approval.", "D": "The HMO typically does not cover non-emergency follow-up visits with out-of-network providers."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "HMOs cover emergency care at out-of-network facilities but typically require that follow-up non-emergency care be transferred to in-network providers as soon as the patient is medically stable. Non-emergency follow-up visits with out-of-network physicians are generally not covered by HMOs. The emergency exception does not extend to routine post-emergency follow-up visits once the emergency condition is stabilized. A primary care referral does not guarantee coverage for out-of-network providers under a standard HMO plan benefit design."}, {"id": 229, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A Medicare Part A beneficiary was hospitalized for five days, discharged home, and required another hospitalization 40 days later. Under Medicare Part A, does the second admission begin a new benefit period with a new deductible?", "options": {"A": "No, because the patient has not been out of a hospital or SNF for 60 consecutive days to start a new period.", "B": "Yes, because any new hospital admission after a discharge automatically begins a new Medicare benefit period.", "C": "Yes, because hospital admissions separated by more than 30 days automatically begin a new benefit period.", "D": "No, because Medicare Part A covers unlimited hospitalizations within a calendar year without new deductibles."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A Medicare Part A benefit period ends only after the patient has been out of a hospital or skilled nursing facility for 60 consecutive days. Since only 40 days elapsed between admissions, the patient remains within the same benefit period and the inpatient deductible does not reset for the second admission. A new benefit period does not begin automatically with each new admission. The threshold is 60 consecutive days out of a facility, not 30 days. Medicare Part A is not unlimited; the benefit period structure governs deductible resets."}, {"id": 230, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A Medicare patient underwent cardiac bypass surgery and was discharged to a skilled nursing facility. Under the Bundled Payments for Care Improvement (BPCI) model, which event triggers the start of the bundled payment episode?", "options": {"A": "The date the patient first contacts the cardiologist to schedule the initial surgical consultation.", "B": "The date of the index hospitalization for the procedure that initiates the defined care episode.", "C": "The date the patient is discharged from the acute care hospital to the post-acute facility.", "D": "The date the patient completes all post-acute rehabilitation services in the skilled nursing facility."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In BPCI and related bundled payment models, the index hospitalization for the defined procedure triggers the episode, and all related services within the subsequent 90-day window are included in the bundle. The initial outpatient consultation does not trigger the episode. Discharge to post-acute care is within the episode but is not the trigger event. Completion of SNF services occurs during the episode but does not define when the episode begins. The anchor hospitalization is the defining event that initiates the episode measurement period."}, {"id": 231, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A patient currently hospitalized for a psychiatric crisis is at risk of premature discharge because the payer is denying continued inpatient authorization. The case manager wants to challenge the denial. Which type of appeal is most appropriate given the patient's active inpatient status?", "options": {"A": "A standard internal appeal, submitted within 60 days of the denial with full clinical documentation.", "B": "A retrospective appeal, filed after the patient is discharged to request reversal of the denied coverage.", "C": "An expedited or urgent appeal, processed within 72 hours due to ongoing risk to the patient's health.", "D": "A civil lawsuit against the payer for failure to provide medically necessary psychiatric services."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "An expedited or urgent appeal is required when a patient's health, safety, or ability to regain maximum function could be seriously jeopardized by the standard appeal timeline. A patient currently hospitalized for a psychiatric crisis meets the criteria for expedited review, which must be processed within 72 hours under federal regulations. A standard 60-day timeline is too slow for an active inpatient whose discharge would create immediate risk. A retrospective appeal after discharge addresses the past coverage but does not prevent premature discharge. Litigation is a last resort, not the immediate clinical response."}, {"id": 232, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A Medicare patient spent four nights in the hospital under observation status and was then discharged to a skilled nursing facility for rehabilitation. What is the most important financial implication the case manager should communicate to this patient?", "options": {"A": "The patient will receive a refund of observation costs paid since the stay lasted fewer than five days.", "B": "Medicare Part A will cover all SNF costs for up to 100 days since the patient requires skilled nursing care.", "C": "The patient is exempt from SNF cost-sharing since the observation stay occurred in a Medicare hospital.", "D": "The patient does not qualify for Medicare Part A SNF coverage since observation days do not count toward the three-day rule."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The most critical counseling point is that observation status days do not count toward the three-day qualifying inpatient stay required for Medicare Part A SNF coverage. Four observation nights, regardless of their clinical nature or the patient's experience of the hospital stay, do not qualify the patient for Part A SNF benefits, meaning she would be responsible for full SNF costs or would need to qualify through Medicaid. There is no refund provision for observation stays. Medicare Part A SNF coverage is not triggered solely by the need for skilled care; the three-day inpatient requirement must be met independently."}, {"id": 233, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A case manager wants to help her hospital reduce Recovery Audit Contractor (RAC) audit vulnerability related to inpatient level of care documentation. Which practice is most effective at reducing RAC audit risk?", "options": {"A": "Ensuring clinical documentation fully supports the medical necessity of inpatient admission for every case.", "B": "Submitting claims 60 days after service to allow complete documentation review before filing.", "C": "Limiting the number of Medicare patients admitted as inpatients to reduce the volume of auditable claims.", "D": "Retroactively converting all short inpatient stays to outpatient observation after discharge."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The most effective strategy for reducing RAC audit vulnerability is ensuring that clinical documentation clearly and completely supports the medical necessity of inpatient admission level of care for every case, as RACs primarily target admissions where documentation does not justify the billed level of care. Delayed claim submission does not improve documentation quality and may create timely filing compliance issues. Limiting Medicare admissions is not an appropriate response and may compromise patient access to necessary inpatient care. Retroactive billing conversion without valid clinical basis constitutes billing fraud and would significantly increase legal risk."}, {"id": 234, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A health plan uses a nationally recognized, evidence-based clinical criteria tool to determine whether a requested inpatient admission meets the appropriate level of care. Which tool is most commonly used by managed care organizations for this utilization review purpose?", "options": {"A": "The DSM-5, which provides diagnostic criteria for mental health and substance use disorders.", "B": "InterQual or MCG (Milliman Care Guidelines), used to evaluate appropriateness of level of care.", "C": "The Karnofsky Performance Scale, which measures functional performance in oncology patients.", "D": "The APACHE II score, which predicts mortality risk in critically ill patients in the ICU."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "InterQual and MCG (formerly Milliman Care Guidelines) are the two most widely used evidence-based criteria tools for evaluating the medical necessity and appropriateness of level of care for inpatient admissions, continued stays, and post-acute placement in managed care organizations. DSM-5 provides psychiatric diagnostic criteria and is not a utilization review tool. The Karnofsky Performance Scale measures oncology patient functional status, not level of care criteria. The APACHE II score predicts ICU mortality but is not a utilization management criteria instrument."}, {"id": 235, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A medical claim is denied with reason code CO-97, indicating that the charge is included in the allowance for another service billed on the same claim. The case manager assists the patient with this denial. What type of coding issue does this most likely reflect?", "options": {"A": "The patient has reached the plan's annual out-of-pocket maximum, requiring no further payments.", "B": "The claim was submitted after the timely filing deadline outside the payer's permissible filing window.", "C": "A separate procedure code was billed for a component bundled within a primary procedure payment.", "D": "The patient's prior authorization for the service was not obtained before the service was rendered."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Denial code CO-97 indicates that a billed service is considered bundled with or included in the payment for another procedure billed on the same claim, meaning the payer will not pay separately for the component service. This is a coding issue related to unbundling, where procedures that should be billed together under one comprehensive code are billed separately. Out-of-pocket maximum has its own specific denial codes. Timely filing denials carry separate denial codes. Prior authorization denial carries a different reason code."}, {"id": 236, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A Medicare Advantage HMO plan member is traveling out of state and has a non-emergency medical need. Which statement most accurately describes coverage for this out-of-state non-emergency visit under Medicare Advantage?", "options": {"A": "Medicare Advantage plans must cover all non-emergency care nationwide at in-network cost-sharing rates.", "B": "The patient may receive care anywhere in the United States at original Medicare rates as a backup option.", "C": "The patient has full out-of-state coverage since Medicare Advantage must follow federal travel rules.", "D": "Coverage depends on the plan type; HMO plans typically do not cover non-emergency out-of-network care."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Coverage for out-of-state non-emergency care depends on the Medicare Advantage plan type. HMO plans generally restrict coverage to network providers and typically do not cover non-emergency out-of-network care while traveling. PPO plans provide coverage nationwide for non-emergency care at higher cost-sharing. Medicare Advantage does not mandate universal non-emergency nationwide coverage for all plan types. Original Medicare does not act as a fallback coverage option for Medicare Advantage members. No federal travel rule requires non-emergency coverage for HMO members outside their service area."}, {"id": 237, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A Medicare Advantage plan member receives an initial denial for a prior authorization request for knee replacement surgery. Under CMS regulations governing Medicare Advantage plans, within how many days must the plan respond to a standard non-urgent prior authorization request?", "options": {"A": "14 calendar days for standard prior authorization requests in Medicare Advantage plans.", "B": "5 business days for all prior authorization requests regardless of the level of clinical urgency.", "C": "30 calendar days for all non-urgent prior authorization requests under Medicare Advantage rules.", "D": "72 hours for all prior authorization requests since any surgery is considered clinically urgent."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "CMS regulations require Medicare Advantage plans to respond to standard non-urgent prior authorization requests within 14 calendar days. For urgent or expedited requests when a standard review would seriously jeopardize health, the plan must respond within 72 hours. Five business days applies to some commercial insurance standards but not to the specific Medicare Advantage federal regulation. Thirty days is too long and does not comply with current Medicare Advantage CMS requirements. The 72-hour expedited timeline applies specifically to clinically urgent requests, not all surgical authorizations."}, {"id": 238, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A 67-year-old Medicare beneficiary visits her primary care physician for the Annual Medicare Wellness Visit. Under Medicare Part B, which cost-sharing rule applies to this preventive service visit?", "options": {"A": "The patient is responsible for the standard 20% Part B coinsurance for all physician office visits.", "B": "The Annual Wellness Visit is covered by Medicare Part B at no cost with no deductible or coinsurance.", "C": "The patient pays only the Part B annual deductible but not the 20% coinsurance for preventive visits.", "D": "The Annual Wellness Visit is covered under Medicare Part A as a hospital-based outpatient service."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The Medicare Annual Wellness Visit is covered under Part B at no cost to the patient with no deductible or coinsurance when delivered by a Medicare-enrolled provider, as mandated under the ACA's prevention provisions. Standard Part B office visits carry 20% coinsurance after the deductible. The Annual Wellness Visit is exempt from both the deductible and coinsurance requirements to encourage preventive care utilization. The Annual Wellness Visit is a Part B preventive benefit, not a Part A service. This no-cost-sharing provision applies as long as the visit is billed and coded correctly as a wellness visit."}, {"id": 239, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A Medicare Part A beneficiary has used 90 inpatient hospital days and 40 skilled nursing facility days in the same benefit period. How many inpatient lifetime reserve days remain available to this patient for additional hospitalization in the same benefit period?", "options": {"A": "The patient has 60 lifetime reserve days remaining for use in this or any future benefit period.", "B": "The patient has 30 lifetime reserve days remaining since the 30 SNF days above 10 reduced them.", "C": "The patient has 60 lifetime reserve days remaining as lifetime reserve days are a separate hospital pool.", "D": "The patient has 20 lifetime reserve days remaining since the SNF stay consumed 40 hospital benefit days."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Medicare lifetime reserve days are a separate pool of 60 days available for inpatient hospital stays beyond the initial 90-day hospital benefit within a benefit period. SNF days used do not reduce the 60 hospital lifetime reserve days, which apply exclusively to inpatient hospital stays. The patient has used all 90 benefit period hospital days and would use lifetime reserve days if additional hospitalization occurs, beginning with the day beyond day 90. SNF benefit days are governed by separate rules and do not affect the 60 hospital lifetime reserve days available to this patient."}, {"id": 240, "domain": "reimbursement_methods", "question": "A retired physician reports being surprised to learn his Medicare Part B and Part D premiums are significantly higher than the standard amounts he expected. Which Medicare rule explains why higher-income beneficiaries pay more than the standard Medicare premium?", "options": {"A": "Medicare Secondary Payer rules, which require higher-income individuals to pay more as the primary payer.", "B": "The Medicare Savings Program, which adjusts premiums based on beneficiary income for low-income earners.", "C": "The Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act of 1988, which created income-tiered premium structures.", "D": "The Income-Related Monthly Adjustment Amount (IRMAA), which increases premiums for higher-income earners."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "IRMAA (Income-Related Monthly Adjustment Amount) requires Medicare beneficiaries whose modified adjusted gross income exceeds defined thresholds to pay higher Part B and Part D premiums, with the adjustment based on income reported two years prior. Medicare Secondary Payer rules govern which payer pays first for beneficiaries with other coverage, not premium amounts. The Medicare Savings Program helps low-income individuals pay premiums, which is the opposite situation. The Medicare Catastrophic Coverage Act of 1988 was repealed in 1989 and is not the basis for current income-tiered premium structures."}, {"id": 241, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A hospital case management department wants to test a new post-discharge phone call protocol for heart failure patients to reduce 30-day readmissions. Which quality improvement methodology provides a structured framework for testing changes in rapid small-scale iterative cycles?", "options": {"A": "The Plan-Do-Study-Act (PDSA) cycle, which tests changes iteratively before broader implementation.", "B": "Six Sigma, which uses statistical analysis to identify and eliminate sources of process defects.", "C": "Lean methodology, which focuses on eliminating waste and non-value-added steps from care processes.", "D": "Root cause analysis, which identifies underlying causes of an adverse event after it has occurred."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The PDSA cycle is the primary quality improvement methodology for testing changes through iterative small-scale cycles: planning the change, implementing it on a small scale, studying the results, and acting on what was learned before broader implementation. Six Sigma uses statistical process control to reduce defects and variation but is less focused on rapid iterative testing. Lean focuses on waste elimination and workflow efficiency. Root cause analysis is a reactive methodology used after adverse events, not for prospective protocol testing. PDSA is the foundational improvement method in healthcare quality improvement science."}, {"id": 242, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager working in a population health program wants to compare her organization's diabetes management outcomes to those of similar organizations nationally. Which approach best represents evidence-based benchmarking practice?", "options": {"A": "Comparing outcomes internally year-over-year to track trend improvement without external reference.", "B": "Comparing outcomes to nationally published HEDIS benchmarks for relevant diabetic quality measures.", "C": "Selecting comparison organizations informally based on the case manager's professional knowledge.", "D": "Comparing outcomes only to organizations in the same geographic region and payer market."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "HEDIS publishes nationally standardized benchmarks for quality measures including diabetes management metrics, making it the most evidence-based and widely recognized source for external benchmarking. Internal year-over-year comparison tracks progress but does not establish external competitiveness or national performance positioning. Informal comparison selection introduces bias and lacks standardization. Geographic region comparison limits the benchmark to local markets rather than national standards, which may miss broader performance improvement opportunities and underestimate or overestimate performance."}, {"id": 243, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A health plan's quality team is reviewing HEDIS performance data for the diabetes care population. Which of the following represents a HEDIS quality measure applicable to diabetes care management?", "options": {"A": "The HCAHPS score measuring patient satisfaction with nurse communication during hospitalization.", "B": "The average length of stay for diabetic ketoacidosis admissions compared to the national DRG average.", "C": "The percentage of diabetic members who received an HbA1c test during the past measurement year.", "D": "The number of emergency department visits per 1,000 diabetic members in the last six months."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "HEDIS includes the Comprehensive Diabetes Care measure set, which tracks the percentage of diabetic members receiving HbA1c testing, retinal exams, nephropathy screening, and blood pressure control within the measurement year. HCAHPS measures patient satisfaction during hospitalization and is not a HEDIS measure. Average length of stay is a utilization metric, not a HEDIS quality measure. ED visits per 1,000 members is a utilization management metric. HEDIS measures focus on process and intermediate outcome indicators tied to recommended preventive and chronic disease care standards."}, {"id": 244, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A sentinel event occurs when a skilled nursing facility patient receives the wrong medication, leading to a serious adverse outcome. The quality team conducts a root cause analysis. What is the primary purpose of a root cause analysis in this quality improvement context?", "options": {"A": "To identify the staff member responsible for the medication error and document the disciplinary actions taken.", "B": "To satisfy the Joint Commission's mandatory reporting requirements for all quality incidents in the facility.", "C": "To calculate the financial liability associated with the sentinel event for organizational risk management.", "D": "To identify the underlying system failures and contributing factors that led to the adverse event."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Root cause analysis is a structured quality improvement tool designed to identify the underlying system failures, process gaps, and contributing factors that led to an adverse event, with the goal of preventing recurrence through system-level improvement. RCA is not primarily designed to assign individual blame or document disciplinary actions, as blame-focused approaches do not address systemic causes. Joint Commission reporting may be required, but the purpose of the RCA itself is quality improvement, not compliance reporting. Financial liability calculation is a risk management function separate from quality improvement."}, {"id": 245, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A hospital quality team is beginning a project to reduce catheter-associated urinary tract infections on a medical-surgical unit. Before implementing any interventions, what is the most important first step in the quality improvement process?", "options": {"A": "Establish a baseline measurement of the current CAUTI rate using standardized data collection methods.", "B": "Implement a care bundle intervention immediately and measure the infection rate at six months.", "C": "Survey nursing staff about their perceptions of current CAUTI prevention practices on the unit.", "D": "Review published clinical guidelines for CAUTI prevention and distribute them to all unit staff."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Establishing a baseline measurement using standardized data is the essential first step in any quality improvement initiative because it defines the current state and provides the benchmark against which improvement will be measured. Implementing interventions before measuring baseline makes it impossible to determine whether improvement occurred or to what degree. Staff perception surveys provide qualitative data but are not a substitute for quantitative baseline measurement. Distributing guidelines is an educational intervention, not a measurement step. Measurement before intervention is a foundational principle of evidence-based quality improvement."}, {"id": 246, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A patient falls in the hospital and sustains a traumatic brain injury. According to the Joint Commission, this qualifies as a sentinel event. What does the Joint Commission require or strongly recommend of accredited organizations when a sentinel event occurs?", "options": {"A": "The organization must suspend all clinical operations pending a full external accreditation safety audit.", "B": "The organization should conduct a root cause analysis and develop an action plan to prevent recurrence.", "C": "The organization must report the event directly to CMS within 24 hours of its discovery.", "D": "The organization must notify the patient's family within one business day of the event's discovery."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "When a sentinel event occurs at a Joint Commission-accredited facility, the organization should conduct a thorough root cause analysis and develop a credible action plan to prevent similar events from recurring. The Joint Commission does not require suspension of clinical operations for sentinel events. Sentinel events are reported to the Joint Commission voluntarily (though strongly encouraged); CMS has separate reporting requirements with different timelines. Family notification is governed by disclosure standards and state law, not solely by the Joint Commission sentinel event policy."}, {"id": 247, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A hospital's HCAHPS scores show patients frequently rate communication about medications as unsatisfactory. Which quality improvement intervention most directly targets this specific HCAHPS domain?", "options": {"A": "Implementing a daily nurse rounding protocol to check on patient comfort and call light response time.", "B": "Adding a pharmacist to the multidisciplinary team to improve medication reconciliation at discharge.", "C": "Training nurses to use the teach-back method when explaining new medications and their side effects.", "D": "Installing medication barcode scanning technology to reduce administration errors on all inpatient units."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "HCAHPS measures patient-reported experience with communication about medications, specifically whether patients were told about medication purpose and side effects in understandable language. Training nurses to use teach-back when explaining medications directly targets this communication gap. Daily rounding improves overall patient experience but does not specifically target medication communication. Pharmacist involvement improves reconciliation accuracy but not bedside patient-reported communication about side effects. Barcode scanning improves medication safety but does not address the patient experience of communication."}, {"id": 248, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A health plan is seeking NCQA Health Plan accreditation. Which aspect of the plan's operations does NCQA most directly evaluate during the accreditation review?", "options": {"A": "The plan's financial solvency and reserve fund requirements as regulated by state insurance commissioners.", "B": "The plan's network adequacy measured by provider-to-member ratios in each geographic service area.", "C": "The plan's claims payment accuracy and adjudication speed relative to contracted payment timelines.", "D": "The plan's quality management programs, member experience, and care coordination performance and outcomes."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "NCQA Health Plan accreditation evaluates the plan's quality management programs, clinical performance measured through HEDIS, member experience measured through CAHPS surveys, and care coordination and utilization management structures and outcomes. NCQA focuses on quality, not financial solvency, which is regulated by state insurance commissioners. Network adequacy is one evaluated component within the broader NCQA quality framework. Claims payment accuracy and adjudication timelines are operational functions reviewed by states and CMS, not the primary focus of NCQA accreditation evaluation."}, {"id": 249, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager is developing a care management protocol for patients with chronic heart failure. Which source provides the highest level of evidence to support the clinical interventions to be included in the protocol?", "options": {"A": "A systematic review or meta-analysis of multiple randomized controlled trials on heart failure management.", "B": "Expert consensus opinions from a panel of nationally recognized heart failure cardiologists.", "C": "A single well-designed randomized controlled trial published in a peer-reviewed cardiology journal.", "D": "Observational cohort studies tracking heart failure outcomes in a large regional health system."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Systematic reviews and meta-analyses of multiple randomized controlled trials represent the highest level of evidence in the evidence-based practice hierarchy, as they synthesize findings across multiple high-quality studies to produce the most reliable and generalizable conclusions. Expert consensus is a lower level of evidence that is valuable when RCT data is unavailable but reflects opinion rather than systematic evidence. A single RCT is strong evidence but less definitive than a systematic review of multiple RCTs. Observational cohort studies are lower in the evidence hierarchy because they cannot control for confounding variables the way RCTs can."}, {"id": 250, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager quality specialist monitors monthly 30-day readmission rates on a control chart over 12 months and notices that seven consecutive data points fall below the center line. According to statistical process control rules, this pattern most likely indicates which of the following?", "options": {"A": "Random natural variation in readmission rates within the expected normal range of process performance.", "B": "A non-random signal suggesting a meaningful shift in the process that warrants investigation.", "C": "A data measurement error in the readmission data requiring recalculation of the monthly rates.", "D": "An unusual outlier that should be excluded from the control chart to prevent skewing the analysis."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "In statistical process control, seven or more consecutive points on the same side of the center line is a recognized Western Electric rule indicating a non-random signal or process shift that warrants investigation, as the probability of this occurring by chance alone is extremely low. Random variation produces data points that fluctuate on both sides of the center line without extended runs on one side. A consecutive run does not indicate measurement error; it signals a meaningful process change. Outliers are identified by points outside control limits, not by runs, and should not be excluded from the chart without valid cause."}, {"id": 251, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager program tracks both process measures and outcome measures to evaluate program effectiveness. Which of the following best represents an outcome measure rather than a process measure?", "options": {"A": "The percentage of enrolled patients who received a post-discharge follow-up call within 48 hours.", "B": "The proportion of high-risk patients who had a care plan completed within 30 days of program enrollment.", "C": "The 30-day all-cause hospital readmission rate for patients enrolled in the case management program.", "D": "The percentage of patients who received medication reconciliation review at the time of hospital discharge."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "An outcome measure reflects the actual result or impact of care on the patient, such as the 30-day readmission rate, which measures whether the case management intervention actually reduced hospitalizations. Process measures assess whether recommended care steps were performed, such as completing follow-up calls, care plans, or medication reconciliation reviews. Process measures indicate whether the intended actions occurred but do not directly measure patient health outcomes. Distinguishing process from outcome measures is fundamental to quality measurement and program evaluation in case management."}, {"id": 252, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager is reviewing HEDIS preventive care measures for her adult patient panel. Which HEDIS measure specifically assesses whether adult patients are appropriately screened for colorectal cancer?", "options": {"A": "The Comprehensive Diabetes Care measure set tracking HbA1c testing, retinal exams, and nephropathy screening.", "B": "The Antidepressant Medication Management measure tracking follow-up after antidepressant initiation.", "C": "The Childhood Immunization Status measure tracking recommended vaccination rates in two-year-olds.", "D": "The Colorectal Cancer Screening measure tracking appropriate screening rates in adults aged 45 to 75."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "HEDIS includes the Colorectal Cancer Screening measure, which tracks the percentage of adults aged 45 to 75 who completed appropriate CRC screening such as a colonoscopy, stool-based test, or CT colonography within the recommended timeframe. The Comprehensive Diabetes Care set is a separate HEDIS measure set for diabetes management metrics. Antidepressant Medication Management is a behavioral health HEDIS measure for depression treatment. Childhood Immunization Status tracks pediatric vaccination rates in a different patient population. Each HEDIS measure set addresses a specific clinical domain and population group."}, {"id": 253, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case management department identifies that nurses spend 45 minutes each morning manually transcribing patient names from the hospital census into the case management tracking system. A Lean quality improvement team reviews this process. Which Lean concept best describes this transcription activity?", "options": {"A": "Waste (muda), specifically the non-value-added activity of unnecessary manual data re-entry duplication.", "B": "Standard work, a Lean tool establishing the most efficient sequence of case management activities.", "C": "A value stream, representing the full sequence of steps that add value to the case management process.", "D": "Kaizen, the Lean principle of continuous incremental improvement through small daily process changes."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In Lean methodology, muda (waste) refers to any activity that consumes resources without adding value to the patient or process. Manual transcription of data that already exists in one system into another is a non-value-added activity and a classic example of waste in the form of unnecessary processing. Standard work defines the optimal efficient sequence of steps but is a solution tool, not a description of a wasteful problem. A value stream maps all process steps to identify which add value and which are waste. Kaizen is the philosophy of continuous improvement, not the label for a specific wasteful activity."}, {"id": 254, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A quality team investigating frequent medication errors in the discharge coordination process wants to visually map all potential contributing causes by category. Which quality improvement tool is most appropriate for this purpose?", "options": {"A": "A Pareto chart, which displays the frequency of problems in descending order to identify the vital few causes.", "B": "A fishbone (Ishikawa) diagram, which organizes potential causes of a problem into categorical branches.", "C": "A run chart, which displays data points over time to identify trends and patterns in the process.", "D": "A scatter diagram, which shows the relationship or correlation between two process variables."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "A fishbone (Ishikawa or cause-and-effect) diagram is specifically designed to visually organize and display all potential contributing causes to a problem, grouped by categories such as people, process, equipment, and environment. It is the most appropriate tool for brainstorming and categorizing potential causes. A Pareto chart identifies the most frequent causes but requires data already collected. A run chart tracks trends over time. A scatter diagram shows correlations between two variables. The fishbone diagram is the starting point for cause identification before data collection begins."}, {"id": 255, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A health plan program director wants to calculate the return on investment (ROI) of a telephonic disease management program for patients with COPD. Which calculation most directly measures the program's ROI?", "options": {"A": "The total cost of staffing the telephonic program divided by the total number of enrolled members.", "B": "The patient satisfaction scores for the program compared to satisfaction before enrollment.", "C": "The reduction in total medical costs for enrolled members minus program cost, divided by program cost.", "D": "The number of patients enrolled in the program divided by the number eligible for enrollment."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "ROI for a case management or disease management program is calculated as the net financial benefit (reduction in medical costs minus program cost) divided by the program cost, expressed as a ratio or percentage. This formula captures whether the clinical program generates more savings than it costs to operate. Total program cost divided by enrolled members calculates cost per member, not ROI. Patient satisfaction measures patient experience, not financial return. Enrollment rate measures program reach and penetration, not financial impact or return on investment."}, {"id": 256, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "The Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program was established under the ACA to penalize hospitals for excess readmission rates. Which three conditions were originally targeted when HRRP launched in 2012?", "options": {"A": "Diabetes, hypertension, and chronic kidney disease as the three initial HRRP target conditions.", "B": "COPD, sepsis, and stroke as conditions with the highest national readmission rates.", "C": "Asthma, pneumonia, and depression as the most preventable causes of hospital readmission.", "D": "Acute myocardial infarction, heart failure, and pneumonia as the three original HRRP conditions."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "When HRRP launched under the ACA in fiscal year 2013, the three original conditions targeted for excess readmission penalties were acute myocardial infarction, heart failure, and pneumonia. The program subsequently expanded to include COPD, elective total hip and knee arthroplasty, and coronary artery bypass graft surgery. Diabetes, hypertension, CKD, asthma, sepsis, stroke, and depression were not among the original HRRP conditions. Understanding the HRRP conditions is important for case managers managing high-risk discharge populations covered by Medicare."}, {"id": 257, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case management team wants to ensure that their risk stratification tool classifies patients consistently regardless of which case manager administers it. Which measurement property are they most concerned about establishing?", "options": {"A": "Inter-rater reliability, the consistency of the tool's results across different administrators and users.", "B": "Validity, the ability of the tool to accurately measure the construct it is designed to measure.", "C": "Sensitivity, the ability of the tool to correctly identify all true high-risk patients in the population.", "D": "Specificity, the ability of the tool to correctly exclude all patients who are not truly high-risk."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Inter-rater reliability is the degree to which a measurement tool produces consistent results when used by different administrators or raters, which is exactly what the team is concerned about when multiple case managers apply the same tool. Validity assesses whether the tool measures what it is intended to measure, not whether different raters use it consistently. Sensitivity measures how well the tool identifies true positives. Specificity measures how well the tool identifies true negatives. For a risk stratification tool deployed across multiple case managers, inter-rater reliability is the essential measurement property to establish."}, {"id": 258, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case management program wants to measure the impact of its interventions on patients' overall health-related quality of life across a broad population with multiple chronic conditions. Which outcome measurement tool is most widely validated for this purpose?", "options": {"A": "The PHQ-9, which measures the severity of depressive symptoms as a proxy for overall patient wellbeing.", "B": "The SF-36.", "C": "The Katz Index, which measures functional independence in basic self-care activities of daily living.", "D": "The Barthel Index, which assesses motor function and self-care independence in rehabilitation populations."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The SF-36 (Short Form-36) is one of the most widely validated and used generic health-related quality of life instruments, assessing physical functioning, role limitations, bodily pain, general health, vitality, social functioning, emotional role function, and mental health across diverse patient populations with chronic conditions. The PHQ-9 measures depression severity specifically, not overall health-related quality of life. The Katz Index measures functional independence in basic ADLs, which is one component of quality of life. The Barthel Index measures basic ADL performance in rehabilitation populations, not comprehensive quality of life."}, {"id": 259, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager works in a hospital participating in CMS Value-Based Purchasing. CMS has identified never events (Serious Reportable Events) for which Medicare will not provide additional reimbursement. Which of the following is an example of a never event?", "options": {"A": "A patient who is readmitted within 30 days of discharge for a condition related to the index admission.", "B": "A patient who experiences a medication error that requires an extended hospital stay beyond the DRG.", "C": "A patient who undergoes a surgical procedure performed on the wrong body site.", "D": "A patient who acquires a catheter-associated urinary tract infection after the third hospital day."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Wrong-site surgery is a classic example of a never event (Serious Reportable Event) as defined by the National Quality Forum and adopted by CMS, for which Medicare does not provide additional reimbursement. Thirty-day readmissions are addressed through HRRP payment penalties, not never event policy. Medication errors causing harm are serious safety events but are not on the defined never event list. CAUTI is addressed under the CMS Hospital-Acquired Conditions program with separate reimbursement consequences, distinct from the never event category."}, {"id": 260, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case management director reviews a dashboard showing that the percentage of patients with a scheduled follow-up appointment at hospital discharge improved from 65% to 89% over six months. This metric is best classified as which type of quality measure?", "options": {"A": "An outcome measure reflecting the direct impact of case management on patient health status.", "B": "A structural measure reflecting the organizational resources available to support case management.", "C": "A patient satisfaction measure reflecting how patients perceive the quality of care coordination.", "D": "A process measure reflecting whether a specific recommended care step was consistently performed."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Whether a follow-up appointment was scheduled at discharge is a process measure because it assesses whether a recommended care step was performed rather than measuring the resulting impact on patient health. Process measures document adherence to evidence-based care steps. Outcome measures reflect patient health results such as readmission rates or clinical values. Structural measures assess organizational capacity such as staffing ratios or technology. Patient satisfaction measures capture the patient's reported experience of care. Scheduling a follow-up appointment is an action taken, not a health outcome."}, {"id": 261, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A hospital implements a central line-associated bloodstream infection (CLABSI) prevention bundle in the ICU. Which statement best describes the concept of a care bundle in quality improvement?", "options": {"A": "A small set of evidence-based practices that when implemented together reliably improve patient outcomes.", "B": "A comprehensive checklist of all possible interventions for every clinical condition or procedure.", "C": "A standardized physician order set used at admission to prescribe care for a specific diagnosis.", "D": "A financial incentive package offered to providers who meet specific performance benchmarks."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "A care bundle is a structured set of three to five evidence-based practices that when reliably implemented together produce better outcomes than any single intervention alone. The reliability of consistent bundle implementation is the core principle. A care bundle is not a comprehensive checklist of all possible interventions but a focused set of the highest-impact evidence-based elements. A physician order set is a prescribing tool used at admission, not a prevention bundle. A financial incentive package is a payment mechanism, not a clinical quality improvement intervention."}, {"id": 262, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager's quarterly performance review shows her documentation compliance rate is 62%, below the required 85% threshold. The supervisor implements a performance improvement plan. What is the primary purpose of a performance improvement plan in this professional context?", "options": {"A": "To create a formal record of the case manager's deficiency for the purpose of future termination proceedings.", "B": "To provide structured support, clear goals, and a measurable timeline for achieving the required standard.", "C": "To redistribute the case manager's caseload to other staff members while she works to improve.", "D": "To notify the CCMC of a potential professional standards violation requiring credential review."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The primary purpose of a performance improvement plan is to provide the employee with structured support, clearly defined performance goals, practical resources, and a defined timeline for achieving the required standard. PIP is a developmental management tool, not primarily a precursor to termination. Caseload redistribution may or may not occur depending on the circumstances but is not the defining purpose of a PIP. CCMC notification is appropriate for ethical violations, not performance metric shortfalls, which are addressed through internal organizational management processes."}, {"id": 263, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A skilled nursing facility is required to implement a Quality Assurance and Performance Improvement (QAPI) program under CMS requirements. Which statement best describes the intended scope of a QAPI program?", "options": {"A": "A QAPI program focuses exclusively on regulatory compliance activities and survey preparation only.", "B": "A QAPI program is limited to reviewing clinical care quality and excludes administrative processes.", "C": "A QAPI program encompasses systematic quality measurement, performance improvement, and root cause analysis.", "D": "A QAPI program is required only for SNFs with prior quality deficiency citations from state inspections."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "QAPI programs in post-acute care settings encompass systematic approaches to quality measurement, data-driven performance analysis, performance improvement projects, and root cause analysis of adverse events across all aspects of facility operations including both clinical care and administrative processes. QAPI is not limited to regulatory compliance or survey preparation; it is a proactive quality management system. QAPI includes both clinical and non-clinical quality domains. QAPI is required of all Medicare and Medicaid-certified SNFs regardless of their prior deficiency citation history."}, {"id": 264, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A hospital implements a protocol requiring same-day discharge for all uncomplicated elective procedure patients. Within one month, the team notices a significant increase in 72-hour emergency department returns among this patient group. This pattern best illustrates which quality improvement concept?", "options": {"A": "A sentinel event related to the same-day discharge protocol requiring immediate Joint Commission reporting.", "B": "Natural variation in ED return rates that is statistically unrelated to the new discharge protocol.", "C": "A structural measure improvement since same-day discharge increased hospital bed availability.", "D": "An unintended consequence, where improvement in one area produces a negative effect in another."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "An unintended consequence in quality improvement occurs when a change designed to improve one aspect of care produces a negative effect in another area, such as the increase in 72-hour ED returns following the same-day discharge protocol. The temporal relationship between the protocol implementation and the ED returns suggests a causal link that warrants investigation and protocol modification. This is not a sentinel event requiring formal reporting. The close temporal relationship between the protocol and the ED increase suggests it is not simply natural variation. The bed availability gain is a structural benefit that must be weighed against the patient safety consequence."}, {"id": 265, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager program uses Donabedian's quality framework to evaluate its performance. Under this framework, which of the following represents a structural measure of quality?", "options": {"A": "The number of CCM-certified case managers relative to the total case management workforce.", "B": "The percentage of enrolled patients who received a comprehensive assessment within 30 days of enrollment.", "C": "The 90-day disease-specific readmission rate for patients enrolled in the cardiac case management program.", "D": "The proportion of patients who report satisfaction with the quality of case management services received."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "In Donabedian's structure-process-outcome framework, structural measures evaluate the organizational capacity and resources available to deliver care, such as workforce qualifications, staffing ratios, and certification rates. Process measures assess whether recommended care actions were performed, such as assessment completion rates. Outcome measures reflect the results of care, such as readmission rates. Patient satisfaction measures are often categorized separately or as patient-reported outcomes. Workforce certification rate is a foundational structural element that influences care quality delivery."}, {"id": 266, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager discovers that an error in care plan coordination caused a delay in a patient's treatment, worsening her condition. According to quality improvement and ethical standards, what is the most appropriate action?", "options": {"A": "Document the error fully in the chart and inform the supervisor only, without disclosing it to the patient.", "B": "Disclose the error to the patient transparently and report it through the organization's event reporting system.", "C": "Correct the care plan immediately and monitor closely without formal disclosure since the error is now resolved.", "D": "Wait to disclose until a full investigation is completed to ensure all facts are available to the patient."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Most ethical, legal, and accreditation standards require transparent disclosure of errors that caused patient harm, both to the patient directly and through the organization's internal event reporting system. Disclosing errors to patients is an ethical obligation that builds trust and supports informed decision-making about continued care. Informing only the supervisor without patient disclosure fails the transparency standard. Correcting the error without disclosure does not acknowledge the patient's right to know about events affecting her health outcomes. Waiting until investigation is complete delays disclosure and may compound harm or loss of trust."}, {"id": 267, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case manager in an inpatient rehabilitation facility uses the Functional Independence Measure (FIM) to track patient progress toward discharge goals. Which statement accurately describes what the FIM measures?", "options": {"A": "The patient's clinical disease severity and acuity calibrated to predict inpatient mortality risk.", "B": "The patient's degree of pain interference with daily functioning across seven functional domains.", "C": "The patient's level of functional independence across 18 motor and cognitive task items.", "D": "The patient's estimated return-to-work timeline based on functional performance and job demands."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "The FIM measures the patient's level of functional independence across 18 items in two domains: motor activities including self-care, sphincter control, transfers, and locomotion, and cognitive activities including communication and social cognition. Each item is scored 1 to 7, where 7 indicates complete independence and 1 indicates total assistance. The FIM does not measure disease severity or predict mortality. It does not specifically assess pain interference. Return-to-work timelines may be informed by FIM data but are not what the instrument directly measures. The FIM is the standard functional outcome tool in inpatient rehabilitation."}, {"id": 268, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case management department wants to adopt high reliability organization (HRO) principles to reduce care coordination errors. Which HRO principle most directly promotes the proactive identification and reporting of near misses before patient harm occurs?", "options": {"A": "Sensitivity to operations, which requires leaders to stay aware of front-line conditions in real time.", "B": "Reluctance to simplify, which cautions against oversimplifying complex processes and safety situations.", "C": "Deference to expertise, which prioritizes front-line staff knowledge during safety-critical decisions.", "D": "Preoccupation with failure, which involves proactively identifying and reporting potential failure points."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Preoccupation with failure is the HRO principle that drives organizations to actively identify, report, and learn from near misses, small deviations, and potential failure points before they result in adverse patient outcomes. It creates a culture where reporting small problems is valued rather than discouraged. Sensitivity to operations focuses on leadership awareness of front-line conditions. Reluctance to simplify guards against oversimplification of complex processes. Deference to expertise ensures safety decisions involve those with the most relevant knowledge. Preoccupation with failure is the principle most directly linked to near-miss identification and reporting culture."}, {"id": 269, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "Under the Hospital Value-Based Purchasing (VBP) program, Medicare adjusts inpatient payments to hospitals based on performance across multiple domains. Which domains are included in the VBP scoring methodology?", "options": {"A": "Clinical outcomes, person and community engagement, safety, and efficiency and cost reduction.", "B": "Nurse staffing ratios, physician board certification rates, and facility accreditation status.", "C": "Length of stay, supply chain costs, and administrative overhead relative to national averages.", "D": "Insurance payer mix, patient census, and geographic market competition indicators."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "The Hospital VBP program evaluates hospitals across four domains: clinical outcomes (mortality and complication rates), person and community engagement (HCAHPS patient experience), safety (hospital-acquired infection and safety measure performance), and efficiency and cost reduction (Medicare spending per beneficiary). Nurse staffing ratios, physician board certification, and accreditation status are not VBP scoring domains. Length of stay, supply chain costs, and administrative overhead are operational efficiency metrics not directly scored in VBP. Payer mix and geographic competition are business factors unrelated to the VBP quality performance scoring domains."}, {"id": 270, "domain": "quality_and_outcomes_evaluation_and_measurements", "question": "A case management leader wants to distinguish between quality assurance (QA) and quality improvement (QI) as distinct approaches to managing care quality. Which statement most accurately differentiates QA from QI?", "options": {"A": "QA and QI are interchangeable terms that both describe the ongoing process of improving clinical outcomes.", "B": "QA focuses on improving processes, while QI focuses on finding and disciplining staff who cause errors.", "C": "QA detects and corrects deviations from standards after they occur, while QI proactively improves processes.", "D": "QA uses the PDSA cycle for systematic improvement, while QI uses audits to detect standard deviations."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Quality assurance is a reactive approach that detects and corrects deviations from established standards after they occur, often through audits and inspections. Quality improvement is a proactive, systematic approach that analyzes processes and tests changes to achieve better outcomes going forward. QA and QI are not interchangeable; they reflect different philosophies about how to manage quality. QA does not focus primarily on disciplining staff; that conflation creates a punitive culture that undermines safety reporting. The PDSA cycle is a QI tool, not a QA instrument. Understanding this distinction is foundational to case management quality program management."}, {"id": 271, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A physiatrist is reviewing an inpatient rehabilitation facility's compliance with Medicare certification requirements. CMS requires that 60% of patients are admitted with one of 13 qualifying diagnostic categories. Which condition is included in the CMS list of qualifying diagnoses for IRF admission?", "options": {"A": "Stroke, which is one of the 13 qualifying conditions for Medicare-certified inpatient rehabilitation.", "B": "Uncontrolled hypertension requiring ongoing cardiovascular monitoring and medication adjustment.", "C": "Post-surgical wound healing complications requiring intensive nursing wound care after orthopedic surgery.", "D": "Generalized deconditioning in an elderly patient following a two-week hospitalization for pneumonia."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Stroke is one of the 13 qualifying conditions for CMS-certified IRF admission, along with spinal cord injury, congenital deformity, amputation, major multiple trauma, hip fracture, brain injury, neurological disorders, burns, active polyarthritis, systemic vasculitis, severe osteoarthritis, and qualifying knee or hip joint replacement. Uncontrolled hypertension alone does not qualify. Post-surgical wound complications do not qualify without a concurrent qualifying diagnosis. Generalized deconditioning is not among the 13 IRF qualifying conditions and does not satisfy the 60% rule."}, {"id": 272, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A 74-year-old patient recovering from hip fracture repair is being considered for either an inpatient rehabilitation facility or a skilled nursing facility. Which factor most strongly supports placement in an IRF rather than a SNF?", "options": {"A": "The patient requires daily nursing assessment and monitoring of anticoagulation therapy after surgery.", "B": "The patient can tolerate at least three hours of physical and occupational therapy per day five days per week.", "C": "The patient needs wound care for a surgical site infection that occurred on postoperative day three.", "D": "The physician has certified the need for skilled nursing care for at least 20 days post-discharge."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "The primary criterion distinguishing IRF from SNF placement is the patient's ability to tolerate at least three hours per day of physical and occupational therapy (or two modalities totaling three hours) five days per week. This intensive therapy tolerance defines IRF-level care. Daily nursing assessment and anticoagulation monitoring can be provided appropriately in a SNF. Wound care is a skilled nursing service appropriate for SNF level of care. Physician certification of skilled nursing need supports SNF placement rather than IRF referral."}, {"id": 273, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A 58-year-old patient has been in the ICU for three weeks with ventilator dependence, severe malnutrition, and multi-organ dysfunction after sepsis. She is medically stable but requires ongoing ventilator management and complex wound care. Which post-acute setting is most appropriate for this patient?", "options": {"A": "Skilled nursing facility, which provides 24-hour nursing care for medically complex patients.", "B": "Inpatient rehabilitation facility, which provides intensive therapy for neurologically impaired patients.", "C": "Long-term acute care hospital (LTACH), which provides extended acute-level care for complex patients.", "D": "Home health with visiting nurse services and respiratory therapy equipment for ventilator weaning."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "LTACHs are specifically designed for patients requiring extended acute-level care including ventilator weaning, complex wound management, and IV therapy, with a Medicare average length of stay of 25 or more days. Medically complex ventilator-dependent patients frequently exceed SNF clinical capabilities and staffing. IRFs serve patients who can tolerate intensive physical and occupational therapy, which this severely deconditioned patient cannot at this stage. Home ventilator management is generally not appropriate for a patient who has not yet been successfully weaned from the ventilator."}, {"id": 274, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is coordinating care for a patient with hemiplegia after an ischemic stroke. She wants to know which team member should address the patient's gait abnormalities and fall risk during inpatient rehabilitation. Which rehabilitation team member primarily addresses mobility, balance, and gait retraining?", "options": {"A": "The physical therapist, who specializes in mobility, strength, balance, and gait retraining after neurological injury.", "B": "The occupational therapist, who specializes in upper extremity function and activities of daily living.", "C": "The speech-language pathologist, who specializes in communication, swallowing, and cognitive function.", "D": "The recreational therapist, who addresses community reintegration through leisure and social activities."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Physical therapists specialize in mobility, strength training, balance, gait retraining, and fall prevention, making them the primary team member for addressing gait abnormalities and fall risk after stroke. Occupational therapists focus on upper extremity function, fine motor skills, and ADL performance such as dressing and grooming. Speech-language pathologists address communication disorders such as aphasia, and dysphagia. Recreational therapists address community reintegration and quality of life through leisure and social activities, not mobility and gait training."}, {"id": 275, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A patient who had a right hemisphere stroke has difficulty with dressing, meal preparation, and using utensils. She has intact speech but significant visual-spatial perceptual deficits. Which rehabilitation team member primarily addresses these daily living skill deficits?", "options": {"A": "The physical therapist, who addresses mobility and lower extremity strength to improve functional performance.", "B": "The occupational therapist, who specializes in functional performance in self-care and daily living tasks.", "C": "The speech-language pathologist, who addresses perceptual deficits arising from cognitive-communication disorders.", "D": "The case manager, who coordinates community resources for meal preparation and ADL support at home."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Occupational therapists specialize in functional performance in daily living tasks including dressing, grooming, meal preparation, and use of adaptive equipment to compensate for perceptual and motor deficits. They also assess and treat visual-spatial and perceptual deficits that affect function. Physical therapists address mobility and ambulation, not upper extremity ADL performance. Speech-language pathologists address communication and swallowing, not perceptual-motor ADL deficits as a primary area. The case manager coordinates resources but is not the clinical specialist for ADL retraining."}, {"id": 276, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A 70-year-old patient with Parkinson's disease is referred to inpatient rehabilitation after hospitalization for aspiration pneumonia. The team is concerned about safe swallowing before oral diet resumption. Which team member should conduct the dysphagia assessment and develop the safe swallowing plan?", "options": {"A": "The physical therapist, who addresses motor control deficits including oral motor weakness.", "B": "The occupational therapist, who manages daily living activities including adaptive feeding equipment.", "C": "The speech-language pathologist, who specializes in swallowing assessment and dysphagia management.", "D": "The registered dietitian, who calculates caloric needs and recommends appropriate nutritional supplements."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Speech-language pathologists are the clinical specialists for dysphagia assessment and management, including bedside swallowing evaluation, instrumental assessments such as modified barium swallows, diet texture recommendations, and swallowing therapy techniques. Physical therapists address motor control but not swallowing assessment, which is within the SLP's clinical scope. Occupational therapists manage adaptive feeding positioning and equipment but not the dysphagia assessment. Registered dietitians address nutritional needs and diet composition and defer to the SLP for swallowing function assessment and texture recommendations."}, {"id": 277, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is reviewing the Functional Independence Measure (FIM) for a patient who requires a caregiver to perform 100% of the effort for bathing because the patient cannot contribute any effort at all. Which FIM score level does this represent?", "options": {"A": "FIM level 1 (Total Assistance), where the patient contributes less than 25% of the effort for the activity.", "B": "FIM level 2 (Maximal Assistance), where the patient contributes 25-49% of the effort for the activity.", "C": "FIM level 3 (Moderate Assistance), where the patient contributes 50-74% of the effort for the activity.", "D": "FIM level 4 (Minimal Assistance), where the patient contributes 75% or more of the effort independently."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "FIM level 1 (Total Assistance) indicates that the helper expends more than 75% of the effort or the patient contributes less than 25% of the effort for the specific task. With 100% caregiver effort and zero patient contribution, the correct FIM score is 1. FIM level 2 (Maximal Assistance) indicates the patient contributes 25 to 49% of the effort. FIM level 3 (Moderate Assistance) indicates the patient contributes 50 to 74% of the effort. FIM level 4 (Minimal Assistance) indicates the patient contributes 75% or more and needs only light touch or cueing."}, {"id": 278, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A patient in inpatient rehabilitation can perform all steps of lower body dressing independently but requires an adaptive dressing stick and takes three times longer than typical. No human assistance is needed at any step. Which FIM score level is most appropriate for this activity?", "options": {"A": "FIM level 4 (Minimal Assistance).", "B": "FIM level 6 (Modified Independence).", "C": "FIM level 7 (Complete Independence).", "D": "FIM level 5 (Supervision)."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "FIM level 6 (Modified Independence) is assigned when the patient completes a task independently but requires an assistive device, extra time beyond typical, or modified techniques, and no human assistance is needed. Using a dressing stick with extra time but without human assistance is a classic example of Modified Independence. FIM level 7 (Complete Independence) requires performing the task without any device and within a typical time frame. FIM levels 1 through 4 require human physical assistance, which is not present here. Level 5 (Supervision) requires a helper for safety monitoring but no physical contact."}, {"id": 279, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is helping family members understand a stroke patient's communication deficit. The patient can hear normally and fully understands spoken language but cannot produce fluent speech and speaks only in halting single words and short phrases. Which type of aphasia does this pattern describe?", "options": {"A": "Wernicke's aphasia, characterized by fluent output but severely impaired language comprehension.", "B": "Global aphasia, characterized by severely impaired both expressive and receptive language function.", "C": "Broca's aphasia, characterized by non-fluent, effortful speech with relatively preserved comprehension.", "D": "Conduction aphasia, characterized by fluent speech with disproportionate difficulty in word repetition."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Broca's aphasia (expressive or non-fluent aphasia) is characterized by non-fluent, effortful, telegraphic speech output with relatively preserved comprehension of spoken language, matching this patient's presentation. Wernicke's aphasia produces fluent but meaningless speech with impaired comprehension. Global aphasia severely impairs both expression and comprehension and produces very little speech with poor understanding. Conduction aphasia produces relatively fluent speech with better comprehension but disproportionate difficulty repeating words and phrases heard from others."}, {"id": 280, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is reviewing documentation on a traumatic brain injury patient described as confused, agitated, and responding to the environment with non-purposeful behavior while unable to follow commands consistently. According to the Rancho Los Amigos Scale, which level best describes this patient?", "options": {"A": "Level IV (Confused-Agitated), characterized by heightened activity, confusion, and non-purposeful behavior.", "B": "Level VI (Confused-Appropriate), where the patient follows simple commands and responds appropriately.", "C": "Level II (Generalized Response), where the patient responds inconsistently to stimulation non-purposefully.", "D": "Level VIII (Purposeful-Appropriate), where the patient functions with minimal cognitive impairment."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Rancho Level IV (Confused-Agitated) describes patients in a heightened state of activity who are confused, disoriented, show non-purposeful behavior, and may be verbally or physically aggressive. They cannot cooperate with treatment due to short attention span and lack of appropriate response to the environment. Level VI (Confused-Appropriate) indicates the patient follows simple commands consistently. Level II (Generalized Response) indicates inconsistent, non-purposeful responses to stimulation with no agitation. Level VIII indicates near-independent function. The combination of agitation, confusion, and non-purposeful behavior is hallmark Level IV."}, {"id": 281, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A 32-year-old patient with a cervical spinal cord injury has complete loss of all motor and sensory function below the injury level, with no preservation of sacral sensation or voluntary motor function. According to the ASIA Impairment Scale, how is this injury classified?", "options": {"A": "ASIA B (Incomplete), where sensory function is preserved below the neurological level including sacral segments.", "B": "ASIA A (Complete), where no sensory or motor function is preserved in sacral segments S4-S5.", "C": "ASIA C (Incomplete), where motor function is preserved below the level with less than half normal strength.", "D": "ASIA D (Incomplete), where motor function is preserved with most key muscles graded 3 or higher."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "ASIA A (Complete) is defined as the complete absence of sensory and motor function in the sacral segments S4-S5, including no perianal sensation and no voluntary anal sphincter contraction. The absence of preserved sacral function is the key defining criterion for a complete injury. ASIA B indicates incomplete injury with preserved sacral sensation but no motor function below the level. ASIA C indicates incomplete injury with motor function preserved but most key muscles graded below 3 out of 5. ASIA D indicates incomplete injury with most key muscles graded 3 or higher."}, {"id": 282, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A 58-year-old patient undergoes a below-knee amputation due to peripheral arterial disease. The rehabilitation team is developing a prosthetic training plan. Which intervention is the primary priority in the immediate post-amputation rehabilitation phase before prosthetic fitting?", "options": {"A": "Beginning ambulation training with a temporary prosthetic limb immediately on the first postoperative day.", "B": "Educating the patient about carbon fiber prosthetic options to maximize long-term ambulatory potential.", "C": "Residual limb shaping, wound healing monitoring, and positioning to prevent flexion contracture formation.", "D": "Referring the patient immediately to a vocational rehabilitation counselor for job retraining planning."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "In the immediate post-amputation phase, the priority rehabilitation goals are residual limb shaping using elastic bandaging or shrinker socks, monitoring wound healing, and positioning to prevent hip or knee flexion contractures that would complicate future prosthetic fitting and ambulation. Ambulation with a temporary prosthesis typically begins after the residual limb has healed sufficiently, not on postoperative day one. Prosthetic selection discussions are important but secondary to wound healing and contracture prevention. Vocational rehabilitation is addressed after the patient has achieved functional mobility."}, {"id": 283, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A patient is recovering from an acute myocardial infarction and has been referred to cardiac rehabilitation. Which phase of cardiac rehabilitation typically begins during the inpatient hospital stay immediately after the cardiac event?", "options": {"A": "Phase I (inpatient cardiac rehabilitation), focused on early ambulation, education, and risk factor counseling.", "B": "Phase II (outpatient cardiac rehabilitation), a supervised exercise program at an outpatient cardiac facility.", "C": "Phase III (maintenance cardiac rehabilitation), a self-directed exercise program continued in the community.", "D": "Phase IV (advanced cardiac rehabilitation), an intensive supervised program for complex cardiac patients."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Phase I cardiac rehabilitation is the inpatient phase that begins during the hospitalization after a cardiac event such as MI, CABG, or PCI. It focuses on early progressive ambulation, patient and family education about cardiac risk factors and activity guidelines, and discharge planning. Phase II is the outpatient supervised exercise and monitoring program that typically begins one to three weeks after discharge. Phase III is the community-based self-directed maintenance phase. There is no formally designated Phase IV in the standard four-phase cardiac rehabilitation framework."}, {"id": 284, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A 65-year-old patient with severe COPD experiences significant activity limitation and breathlessness with daily activities. Her pulmonologist refers her to pulmonary rehabilitation. Which outcome does pulmonary rehabilitation most consistently demonstrate in patients with COPD?", "options": {"A": "Significant improvement in spirometry values including FEV1 and FVC with a full program.", "B": "Improved exercise tolerance, reduced dyspnea, and improved health-related quality of life.", "C": "Elimination of the need for supplemental oxygen in most patients completing the full program.", "D": "Complete elimination of COPD hospitalizations for all patients who complete a 12-week program."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Pulmonary rehabilitation consistently demonstrates improved exercise tolerance measured by 6-minute walk distance, reduced dyspnea perception, and improved health-related quality of life in patients with COPD. Pulmonary rehabilitation does not significantly improve spirometry values such as FEV1 or FVC; underlying lung physiology changes minimally. Oxygen requirements are determined by the underlying disease state and are not eliminated by rehabilitation. Hospitalizations are reduced but not eliminated; the outcome is a meaningful relative reduction, not elimination."}, {"id": 285, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is facilitating a wheelchair evaluation for a patient with a C6 complete spinal cord injury who has full wrist extension but no finger function. Which wheelchair type most supports this patient's maximum functional independence?", "options": {"A": "A standard manual wheelchair with push handles for family caregiver-assisted propulsion.", "B": "A power wheelchair with a standard joystick, since C6 level injury precludes all manual propulsion.", "C": "A manual ultralight wheelchair with modified hand rims allowing propulsion using wrist extension.", "D": "A tilt-in-space power wheelchair with a head array designed for high cervical injuries."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Individuals with C6 complete SCI retain wrist extension and can propel a manual ultralight wheelchair using modified hand rims such as friction-coated or knobbed rims, allowing wrist extension and tenodesis function to be used for propulsion. This maximizes independence and upper extremity conditioning. A caregiver-dependent standard wheelchair limits independence unnecessarily for a C6-level patient. C6-level patients can often propel manual chairs independently, so a power chair is not always the most appropriate recommendation. Head array power wheelchairs are designed for high cervical injuries at C3 and above with no upper extremity function."}, {"id": 286, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is working with a patient with T10 paraplegia from a spinal cord injury who will return home using a manual wheelchair. Which discharge education topic is the highest priority for pressure injury prevention in the home setting?", "options": {"A": "Teaching the patient to perform pressure relief maneuvers such as wheelchair push-ups every 15-30 minutes.", "B": "Recommending a standard foam cushion available at any medical supply store for everyday use.", "C": "Instructing the patient to call a home health nurse whenever redness is noted on the sacrum.", "D": "Advising the patient to limit wheelchair time to four hours per day to reduce cumulative pressure."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Teaching the patient to independently perform pressure relief maneuvers such as wheelchair push-ups or lateral weight shifts every 15 to 30 minutes is the highest-priority preventive intervention for pressure injury in SCI, since the patient has impaired sensation and cannot feel ischemic pressure building. Standard foam cushions provide inadequate pressure distribution for SCI patients; specialized pressure-relieving cushions are required. Relying on a nurse to respond to redness represents reactive rather than preventive management. Limiting wheelchair time to four hours would significantly impair the patient's community mobility and independence."}, {"id": 287, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is referring a 38-year-old patient with multiple sclerosis who can no longer perform her previous job as a clinical nurse. She wants to continue working in a healthcare-adjacent role that accommodates her functional limitations. Which service most directly helps her identify and pursue an alternative career path?", "options": {"A": "Social Security Disability Insurance, which provides income replacement for those unable to work.", "B": "State vocational rehabilitation services, which provide counseling, retraining, and job placement support.", "C": "The Americans with Disabilities Act, which requires her former employer to create a new position for her.", "D": "Medicare home health services, which provide skilled nursing care during the period of career transition."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "State vocational rehabilitation (VR) services provide comprehensive support including vocational assessment, career counseling, educational retraining, job placement assistance, and assistive technology support for individuals with disabilities who want to return to or remain in the workforce. SSDI provides income replacement for people unable to work but does not support career transition or retraining. The ADA requires reasonable accommodation in existing jobs, not creation of new positions for employees who can no longer perform their original roles. Medicare home health is a clinical service unrelated to career transition planning."}, {"id": 288, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A patient with limited hand dexterity following a stroke has difficulty holding and using standard utensils for independent eating. The occupational therapist recommends adaptive equipment. Which adaptive equipment item most directly addresses this patient's specific functional deficit?", "options": {"A": "A Hoyer lift, which assists caregivers in transferring the patient safely from bed to a wheelchair.", "B": "A shower chair with non-slip rubber feet, which provides a seated bathing alternative in the shower.", "C": "Built-up handle utensils, which provide a larger grip diameter to compensate for reduced hand dexterity.", "D": "A hospital-style overbed table, which positions food within reach to reduce the reaching distance required."}, "correct": "C", "explanation": "Built-up handle utensils have an enlarged handle diameter that reduces the grip strength and dexterity required to hold and manipulate eating utensils, directly compensating for the hand dexterity deficit described. A Hoyer lift addresses transfer dependence, not upper extremity dexterity for eating. A shower chair addresses bathing safety, not eating function. A repositioned overbed table reduces reach demands but does not address the gripping and manipulation challenge caused by reduced hand dexterity after stroke."}, {"id": 289, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is coordinating care for a patient with Parkinson's disease who experiences significant gait freezing and postural instability with multiple near-falls in the past month. Which rehabilitation-focused strategy has the strongest evidence for reducing fall risk in Parkinson's disease?", "options": {"A": "LSVT BIG therapy, a high-amplitude movement training program designed specifically for Parkinson's motor impairments.", "B": "Aquatic therapy in a heated pool, which eliminates fall risk during sessions by providing buoyancy support.", "C": "Passive range-of-motion exercises performed by a caregiver twice daily to maintain joint flexibility.", "D": "Power wheelchair prescription to eliminate walking and associated fall risk in community environments."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "LSVT BIG is an intensive, standardized physical therapy program designed specifically for Parkinson's disease that uses high-amplitude movements to improve gait, balance, and functional mobility, with strong evidence for reducing fall risk and improving function. Aquatic therapy reduces fall risk during pool sessions but does not address land-based gait and balance function for everyday activities. Passive range-of-motion exercises maintain flexibility but do not address gait freezing, postural instability, or fall risk. Wheelchair prescription eliminates fall risk by eliminating ambulation but dramatically reduces independence and long-term functional capacity."}, {"id": 290, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A 45-year-old patient with a moderate traumatic brain injury has regained independence in basic ADLs but has persistent executive function deficits affecting planning, sequencing, and safety judgment. Which discharge setting most appropriately supports her current needs?", "options": {"A": "Independent living at home with no formal services since she has achieved independence in all basic ADLs.", "B": "A supervised residential program or intensive outpatient day program with structure and cognitive support.", "C": "Long-term skilled nursing facility placement given the permanent nature of her cognitive impairment.", "D": "Immediate return to her previous job to promote cognitive stimulation and neuroplasticity-based recovery."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Executive function deficits affecting safety judgment, planning, and sequencing require supervised support beyond what the patient can manage independently at home, even when basic ADL independence has been regained. A supervised residential program or intensive outpatient day program with cognitive rehabilitation services provides the structure and oversight needed at this stage of recovery. Independent home living without services would leave the patient unsafe given her safety judgment deficits. A skilled nursing facility is not appropriate for a 45-year-old with rehabilitation potential. Immediate return to work is not safe until executive function is further rehabilitated."}, {"id": 291, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A patient in inpatient rehabilitation following a spinal cord injury reports 8/10 neuropathic pain described as burning and stabbing sensations in the lower extremities. Which pharmacological agent class has the strongest evidence for treating neuropathic pain specifically in spinal cord injury?", "options": {"A": "Short-acting opioid analgesics, which are the first-line treatment for all pain types following spinal cord injury.", "B": "Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, which address peripheral inflammation causing the burning sensations.", "C": "Muscle relaxants such as baclofen, which primarily address spasticity rather than neuropathic pain.", "D": "Anticonvulsants such as gabapentin or pregabalin, which have the strongest evidence for SCI neuropathic pain."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Anticonvulsants, particularly gabapentin and pregabalin, have the strongest evidence base for treating central neuropathic pain in spinal cord injury and are recommended as first-line pharmacological agents by clinical practice guidelines. Short-acting opioids are not first-line for neuropathic pain and carry significant dependency and side effect risks. NSAIDs address peripheral inflammatory pain mechanisms and are not effective for the central neuropathic pain characteristic of SCI. Baclofen effectively addresses spasticity but has limited efficacy for neuropathic burning and stabbing pain."}, {"id": 292, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is preparing for the weekly interdisciplinary team conference for a Medicare patient in an inpatient rehabilitation facility. Which Medicare Conditions of Participation requirement governs the frequency and required composition of IRF team conferences?", "options": {"A": "IRF Medicare requirements mandate a weekly interdisciplinary team conference that includes the physician, nursing, and treating therapists.", "B": "IRF Medicare requirements permit monthly team conferences as long as individualized care plans are documented.", "C": "IRF Medicare requirements mandate team conferences only at admission and discharge, not during the stay.", "D": "IRF Medicare requirements permit team conferences via asynchronous electronic communication without live meetings."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Medicare Conditions of Participation for IRFs require a weekly interdisciplinary team conference that includes at minimum the physician, nurse, physical therapist, occupational therapist, and other relevant treating professionals to review and update the patient's individualized plan of care. Monthly conferences do not satisfy the Medicare weekly requirement. The COP requires team conferences throughout the stay, not only at admission and discharge. While electronic communication may supplement team collaboration, the formal weekly conference must occur as an actual meeting with required disciplines present or available."}, {"id": 293, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is helping a family understand why their loved one is continuing intensive therapy three months after a stroke. The family asks whether meaningful recovery is still possible this far from the original event. Which principle most accurately explains the basis for continued rehabilitation at this stage?", "options": {"A": "Recovery from stroke is primarily limited to the first three weeks post-event; after that, gains are minimal.", "B": "Neuroplasticity allows the brain to reorganize and form new neural connections throughout the recovery period.", "C": "Continued therapy is required by Medicare coverage rules regardless of recovery potential at three months.", "D": "Intensive therapy at three months is solely for maintaining current function, not achieving meaningful new gains."}, "correct": "B", "explanation": "Neuroplasticity is the brain's capacity to reorganize by forming new neural connections in response to experience and intensive practice, and this capacity persists well beyond the acute phase of stroke recovery. Meaningful functional gains can occur months and even years post-stroke with continued intensive, task-specific rehabilitation. Recovery is not limited to the first three weeks; the greatest gains occur early but improvement can continue. Continued therapy is clinically indicated when functional goals are achievable, not solely for coverage compliance. Therapy at three months can yield genuine new functional improvement."}, {"id": 294, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager in an inpatient rehabilitation facility is coordinating discharge for a 78-year-old patient who lives alone after hip replacement. She has achieved walker independence but requires assistance with meal preparation and medication management. Which discharge plan most appropriately addresses her home safety and support needs?", "options": {"A": "Discharge directly home with no services since the patient has achieved functional ambulation independence.", "B": "Discharge to a skilled nursing facility since the patient lives alone and has some care needs.", "C": "Discharge to an assisted living facility since the patient requires support for some daily activities.", "D": "Discharge home with home health nursing, physical therapy, home health aide, and meal delivery services."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The most appropriate plan supports the patient's independence and preference to return home while addressing documented care gaps through coordinated home services. Home health nursing addresses medication management, physical therapy continues gait training, a home health aide provides personal care assistance, and meal delivery addresses nutrition needs. No-services discharge ignores documented needs for meal preparation and medication management. SNF placement is not warranted for a patient who has achieved functional ambulation independence. Assisted living involves a major lifestyle change that may be premature following a single surgical event."}, {"id": 295, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A patient is recovering from burn injuries covering 30% of his body surface area and is beginning rehabilitation. Which rehabilitation concern is uniquely critical in burn injury recovery that is less prominent in other rehabilitation populations?", "options": {"A": "Prevention and management of hypertrophic scar formation through pressure garments and scar massage therapy.", "B": "Prevention of pressure injuries from prolonged immobility during the acute phase of burn wound treatment.", "C": "Cognitive rehabilitation for burn-related brain injury from smoke inhalation occurring during the fire.", "D": "Prosthetic fitting for limb loss since most significant burn injuries result in amputation of affected limbs."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Hypertrophic scar formation and contracture prevention are unique and critical rehabilitation concerns in burn injury, requiring early and sustained use of custom-fitted pressure garments worn up to 23 hours per day for up to two years, along with scar massage, stretching, and silicone gel treatments to minimize contracture and cosmetic deformity. Pressure injury prevention is a universal concern for immobile patients but is not uniquely distinctive to burn rehabilitation. Cognitive rehabilitation for smoke inhalation injury is important when present but does not occur in most burn cases. Most significant burns do not result in amputation."}, {"id": 296, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A patient in rehabilitation following a brainstem stroke has been evaluated by the speech-language pathologist, who recommends pureed foods and nectar-thick liquids based on a modified barium swallow study. Which standardized framework describes these diet texture and liquid consistency levels?", "options": {"A": "The American Dietetic Association diet level system, which classifies food textures by preparation method only.", "B": "The Joint Commission dietary standard for post-stroke patients requiring all modified texture diets.", "C": "The Medicare home health guidelines for modified diet therapy in patients with swallowing dysfunction.", "D": "The IDDSI (International Dysphagia Diet Standardisation Initiative) framework for food textures and liquid levels."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "The International Dysphagia Diet Standardisation Initiative (IDDSI) is the internationally adopted standardized framework that classifies both food texture levels (Levels 3 through 7) and drink thickness levels (Levels 0 through 4). IDDSI replaced the earlier National Dysphagia Diet framework in most healthcare settings and provides consistent terminology across clinical settings. The American Dietetic Association does not have a widely adopted dysphagia-specific diet classification matching this description. The Joint Commission does not set specific diet texture standards. Medicare does not have its own dysphagia diet framework."}, {"id": 297, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A patient with a cervical spinal cord injury has developed significant lower extremity spasticity interfering with transfers, positioning, and skin care. The rehabilitation team is considering pharmacological management. Which medication is most commonly used as the first-line oral agent for spasticity in spinal cord injury?", "options": {"A": "Diazepam, a benzodiazepine used for acute muscle spasm but not for long-term spasticity management.", "B": "Dantrolene, which acts directly on muscle fibers but carries risk of liver toxicity with prolonged use.", "C": "Cyclobenzaprine, a muscle relaxant approved for short-term management of acute musculoskeletal spasm.", "D": "Baclofen, a GABA-B receptor agonist and the first-line oral agent for spinal cord injury spasticity."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Baclofen is the first-line oral medication for spinal cord injury spasticity, acting as a GABA-B receptor agonist at the spinal cord level to inhibit hyperreflexia and reduce muscle tone. Intrathecal baclofen delivered via a pump is available for severe refractory cases. Diazepam is a benzodiazepine with significant sedation and dependency risk and is not a preferred long-term choice for neurogenic spasticity. Dantrolene acts at the muscle level and is associated with hepatotoxicity limiting prolonged use. Cyclobenzaprine is indicated for acute musculoskeletal spasm, not neurogenic spasticity from SCI."}, {"id": 298, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is facilitating goal setting for an inpatient rehabilitation patient. The patient states his personal priority is to walk independently to his mailbox after discharge, but the therapy team has set goals focused only on indoor walker ambulation within the facility. Which approach best aligns with patient-centered rehabilitation goal setting principles?", "options": {"A": "Collaboratively revise the therapy goals to incorporate the patient's stated priority of outdoor independent ambulation.", "B": "Educate the patient that the clinical team's evidence-based goals must take precedence over personal preferences.", "C": "Document the patient's stated preference in the chart without modifying the current therapy goal structure.", "D": "Refer the patient to social work if he insists on his own goals rather than accepting the established program goals."}, "correct": "A", "explanation": "Patient-centered rehabilitation requires that the patient's own functional goals and priorities be incorporated into the treatment plan. The patient's goal of walking to the mailbox is a concrete, meaningful functional outcome that can drive motivation and guide therapy task selection. Replacing the patient's goals with team-determined goals without collaboration undermines engagement and violates patient-centered care principles. Documenting without acting on the patient's stated priority fails to meaningfully incorporate it into care. Referring to social work for a goal-setting disagreement is an inappropriate use of social work consultation and dismisses the patient's legitimate role in his own rehabilitation."}, {"id": 299, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager wants to refer a patient with a traumatic brain injury to state vocational rehabilitation services. Which criterion is essential for eligibility for state vocational rehabilitation services under the Rehabilitation Act?", "options": {"A": "The patient must have been continuously employed for at least five years before the disability occurred.", "B": "The patient must be receiving Social Security Disability Insurance or SSI benefits to qualify for VR services.", "C": "The patient must be under age 60, since vocational rehabilitation is limited to prime working-age adults.", "D": "The patient must have a documented disability that constitutes a barrier to competitive integrated employment."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Eligibility for state vocational rehabilitation services requires that the individual have a documented physical or mental disability that constitutes a substantial impediment to competitive integrated employment and that VR services are expected to benefit the individual in achieving an employment outcome. There is no five-year prior work history requirement for VR eligibility. SSDI or SSI receipt is not required; VR serves any qualifying individual with a disability regardless of benefit status. VR services are available to adults of working age without a strict upper age cutoff of 60, and older adults approaching retirement may also be served depending on state policy and individual goals."}, {"id": 300, "domain": "rehabilitation_concepts_and_strategies", "question": "A case manager is determining when a patient with hemiplegia after stroke is ready for home discharge from inpatient rehabilitation. The patient is independent with a cane, performs all ADLs with modified techniques, and demonstrates safe judgment with all transitions. Which additional factor is most important to confirm before authorizing home discharge?", "options": {"A": "The patient must have achieved full neurological return to pre-stroke baseline before any home discharge.", "B": "The patient must demonstrate the ability to walk without any assistive device for community ambulation.", "C": "The patient must have a home care nursing plan in place covering daily nurse visits for the first 90 days.", "D": "The patient's home environment has been assessed for safety and necessary modifications have been arranged."}, "correct": "D", "explanation": "Before authorizing home discharge from inpatient rehabilitation, confirming that the patient's home environment is safe and that necessary modifications such as grab bars, ramp installation, and removal of fall hazards have been arranged is a critical step that directly affects safety and successful transition. Full neurological baseline is an unrealistic criterion; patients safely discharge with residual deficits when functional goals are met. Cane ambulation is an appropriate functional level for home discharge without requiring device-free walking. Daily nursing visits for 90 days are ordered based on individual skilled need assessment, not as a standard requirement."}];
